{"title_page": "Red House (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|Song first recorded by the Jimi Hendrix Experience in 1966}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Other uses|Red House (disambiguation){{!}}Red House}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name = Red House\n| type = song\n| artist = [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]]\n| album = [[Are You Experienced]]\n| released = {{Start date|1967|05|12}}\n| recorded = December 13, 1966\n| studio = [[CBS Records International|CBS]], London\n| genre = <!-- Provide reliable sources for changes -->[[Blues]]{{sfn|Carroll|2005|p=107|ps=: \"Hendrix playing 'Red House' in 1966 in England for his first album{{nbsp}}... was not producing the hybrid of blues-rock, as he did later in live performance, but was instead producing an indigenous blues displaying those differences directly attributable to Hendrix's cultural life\".}}\n| length = {{Duration|m=3|s=44}}\n| label = [[Track Records|Track]]\n| writer = [[Jimi Hendrix]]\n| producer = [[Chas Chandler]] \n}}\n\"'''Red House'''\" is a song written by [[Jimi Hendrix]] and one of the first songs recorded in 1966 by [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]].  It has the [[musical form]] of a conventional [[twelve-bar blues]] and features Hendrix's guitar playing.  He developed the song prior to forming the Experience and was inspired by earlier blues songs.  \n\n\"Red House\" was first released on the British edition of Hendrix's debut album ''[[Are You Experienced]]'' in May 1967 (for the American album release, previously released Experience singles were used in its place).  A second similar take was eventually released in the US in July 1969 on the American ''[[Smash Hits (The Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Smash Hits]]'' compilation.\n\nThe song was a fixture of Hendrix concerts throughout his career.  Although the lyrics and basic structure were followed, his performances usually varied from the original recording.  Many were recorded and continue to be released officially for the first time, including on ''[[Miami Pop Festival (Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Miami Pop Festival]]'' (2013) and ''[[Freedom: Atlanta Pop Festival]]'' (2015). \"Red House\" has also been performed and recorded by a variety of blues and other artists.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Albert King 1978.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Albert King in Paris, 1978]]\n\"Red House\" was inspired by blues songs Hendrix was performing early in his career as a sideman.  Music critic [[Charles Shaar Murray]] describes a song he calls \"California Night\", which Hendrix performed with [[Curtis Knight and the Squires]], as \"a dead ringer, both in structure and mood, for his 1967 perennial 'Red House'\".{{sfn|Murray|1991|p=139}}  Originally recorded by [[Albert King]] in 1961 as \"Travelin' to California\",{{sfn|McDermott|2017|p=11}} it is a slow blues with lyrics that follow the common blues theme of the rambling man and his lost love (sometimes also misidentified as \"[[Every Day I Have the Blues]]\" \u2013 both songs use the verse \"nobody loves me\").{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=67}}{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=581}}{{efn|[[Albert King]]'s \"Travelin' to California\" was issued as a single in 1961 (King 5588)<ref>{{Discogs master|1115450|Travelin' to California|type=single}}</ref> and included on his album ''[[The Big Blues]]'' (1962); he also recorded it for [[Chess Records]] in 1961 \u2013 it was released with the title \"California\" or \"California Blues\" on the ''Door to Door'' (1969) compilation album (Chess LP-1538).<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/door-to-door-mw0000201978\n| title = Albert King / Otis Rush: ''Door to Door''\n| last = Koda\n| first = Cub\n| authorlink = Cub Koda\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = August 21, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>}}\n\nHendrix recorded two live versions of \"Travelin' to California\" with Knight, which prominently feature his vocal and guitar playing.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=584}}  Both were recorded at George's Club 22 in Hackensack, New Jersey, on December 26, 1965 and/or January 22, 1966.{{sfn|McDermott|2017|p=10}}  After Hendrix's death in 1970, the recordings (using various names) were released by several European record companies that specialized in [[Bootleg recording|bootleg]] and [[grey-market]] albums.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|pp=581, 584}} In 2017, a version was officially released on ''Curtis Knight [Featuring Jimi Hendrix]: Live at George's Club 20''.{{sfn|McDermott|2017|pp=10\u201311}}\n\nMusic writer Keith Shadwick describes Hendrix's performance as \"a staggering display of blues guitar playing that is worthy of mention in the same breath as his later efforts with the Experience\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=67}} Although Shadwick compares his guitar tone and phraseology to that of [[Buddy Guy]], he adds that his techniques \"simply transcend any previous models, and breaks new ground\" and shows that \"his ability to spin out long and consistently surprising lines across the standard blues changes is already full grown\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=67}} In 1966, during his residency as [[Jimmy James and the Blue Flames]] at the [[Cafe Wha?]] in New York City's Greenwich Village, Hendrix continued to develop his slow blues number that became \"Red House\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=80}}\n\n==Composition==\n\"Red House\" is a moderately slow blues, which music writers Tom Wheeler and Joe Gore describe as having \"the [[twelve-bar blues|twelve-bar structure]], the lyrics, the accompaniment, and the arrangement [that] are more or less conventional\".{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=3}}  The song is notated in 12/8 time in the [[key of B]] with a tempo of 66 [[beats per minute]]{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=217}} (although Hendrix fingered the song in the key of B, he usually tuned his guitar one-half step and sometimes one step lower, resulting in a lower pitch).{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=3}}  The song opens with a [[diminished seventh chord]] frequently found in blues songs, including the intros to the [[Robert Johnson (musician)|Robert Johnson]] songs \"[[Dead Shrimp Blues]]\", \"[[Kind Hearted Woman Blues|Kind Hearted Woman]]\", and \"[[32-20 Blues]]\".{{sfn|Fairchild|1994|pp=21\u201322}}   After the four-bar intro, Redding and Experience drummer [[Mitch Mitchell]] come in while Hendrix solos up to the vocal at bar thirteen.{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|pp=218\u2013219}}  After two twelve-bar vocal sections, Hendrix solos for twelve bars, then finishes up with another vocal section.{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|pp=219\u2013227}}\n\nThe song's most prominent characteristic is Hendrix's guitar work.<ref name=\"Ward\"/>  Author Jeffrey Carroll describes his solo as \"concise and packed solid with vocalisms, the bending and glissandos, jumps, drops and whoops of his guitar kept within a traditional structure of a break\".{{sfn|Carroll|2005|p=109}} Shadwick also compares it to a vocal, calling it a \"close approximation of the human voice{{nbsp}}... scooping and bending his phrases to maximum expressive effect\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=93}}  American bluesman [[John Lee Hooker]] commented, \"That 'Red House', that'll make you grab your mother and choke her!  Man, that's really hard, that tears you apart.  He could get down, he could mash it, yeah, Lord!  He had so many blues\".{{sfn|Fairchild|1994|p=18}}\n\n==Lyrics==\nIn his biography ''[[Room Full of Mirrors]]'', biographer [[Charles R. Cross]] comments that the song's theme is \"as old as the blues itself; the singer's woman doesn't love him any more and has moved\".{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=175}} Author Kay Norton describes the broader blues influence as \"balancing a celebration of love and sex with dark humor and wry commentary on loss, mistreatment, corruption, and poverty\".{{sfn|Norton|2016|p=82}}  The lyrics follow a blues [[Call and response (music)|call and response]] or AAB pattern, where the first line (A) is repeated (often with a slight variation), followed by the response (B):\n{{poemquote|\nWait a minute something's wrong here, the key won't unlock this door\nWait a minute something's wrong, Lord have mercy this key won't unlock this door\n(Something's goin' on here)\nI have a bad, bad feeling, that my baby don't live here no more{{nbsp}}...\n\nWell I might as well go back over yonder, way back among the hills\n(Yeah that's what I'm gonna do)\nLord I might as well go back over yonder, way back yonder across the hills\n'Cause if my baby don't love me no more, I know her sister will\n(Yeah, how's that?){{sfn|Hendrix|2003|p=136}}}}\n\nAccording to Experience bassist [[Noel Redding]], Hendrix told him it was about Hendrix' girlfriend in high school, Betty Jean Morgan.{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=175}}  Jimi's brother, [[Leon Hendrix]], also felt that it was about Betty Jean, but also included her sister Maddy,{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=172}} although their house was brown.{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=175}} Shadwick suggests that the song was inspired by [[Linda Keith]], [[Keith Richards]]' then-girlfriend and early Hendrix supporter.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=93}}  Keith referred to her friend's Manhattan apartment, with its red velvet walls and decor,{{sfn|Roby|Schreiber|2010|p=148}} as the \"red house\", and the two frequently stayed there during the summer of 1966.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=78}} In London in 1970, Hendrix met up with Keith and when he performed \"Red House\" at the [[Isle of Wight Festival 1970|1970 Isle of Wight Festival]], he dedicated the song to her and added \"I got to get out of here, because my Linda don't live here no more\" to the lyrics.{{sfn|Roby|Schreiber| 2010|p=182}} However, [[Billy Cox]], longtime friend and bassist for Hendrix' post-Experience groups, explained, \"As far as I know, 'Red House' didn't have any significance in reference to a particular person, place, or thing. It was just a blues number that Jimi put together\".{{sfn|Fairchild|1994|pp=21\u201322}}\n\n==Recording==\n[[File:Noel Redding playing guitar - Photo by Doug Naismith.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Noel Redding returned to playing guitar after quitting the Experience, 1969]]\n\"Red House\" was one of the earliest songs recorded by the Experience.  The group first attempted it at the [[CBS Records International|CBS]] Studios in London on Tuesday, December 13, 1966, following their performance of \"[[Hey Joe#Tim Rose and Jimi Hendrix (1966)|Hey Joe]]\" for the ''[[Ready Steady Go!]]'' music television program.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=92}} Basic tracks for several songs were recorded during the three-hour session.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=27}} Producer [[Chas Chandler]] recalled: \"The 'Red House' on the album [''[[Are You Experienced]]''] came about during the last fifteen minutes of [the December 13] session.  Noel even played rhythm guitar on the track, playing the bass line. Jimi just winged through one take for reference and we started rolling\".{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=29}}\n\nRedding added, \"I had borrowed a terrible old hollow-body electric guitar from someone at the studio{{nbsp}}... because I liked to play along on rhythm to familiarise myself with a sequence, not being quite at home on the bass yet\".{{sfn|Redding|Appleby|1990|p=45}}  The guitar was tuned down one-half step, with the tone controls set to resemble a bass guitar.{{sfn|Black|1999|p=67}}\n\nAdditional takes of the song were recorded at [[De Lane Lea Studios]] on December 21, 1966, which closely followed the earlier arrangement.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=28\u201329}} However, both Hendrix and Redding had problems with missed notes and the takes were not used, except for a backing track that Hendrix later overdubbed at the [[Olympic Studios]] on March 29{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=107}} or early April 1967.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=28\u201329}}\n\n==Releases==\nWhen preparing the final mixes for the Experience's debut album, Chandler chose to use the December 13, 1966, track recorded at CBS:  \"Later when we were scrambling to put the album together, we carted that [December 13 track] out and gave it a listen.  We remixed it at Olympic and added it to the album\".{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=28\u201329}}  [[Track Records]] issued the monaural mix on ''Are You Experienced'',{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=28\u201329}} which was released on May 12, 1967, in the UK.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=50}}  At the time, it was industry practice in the US to include singles on albums.{{sfn|Perry|2004|p=91}}  So when the album was released in the US, \"[[Purple Haze]]\", \"Hey Joe\" and \"[[The Wind Cries Mary]]\" were included at the expense of \"Red House\" and two other songs.{{sfn|Perry|2004|p=91}}  Hendrix later questioned the choice and commented \"Everybody was scared to release 'Red House' in America because they said, 'America don't like the blues, man!'\"{{sfn|Fairchild|1994|p=12}}\n\n\"Red House\" finally saw an American release on July 30, 1969.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=168\u2013169}} [[Reprise Records]] issued a stereo mix of the version recorded at De Lane Lea/Olympic on the ''[[Smash Hits (The Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Smash Hits]]'' compilation.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=28\u201329}} This version was later released internationally on the 1984 ''[[Kiss the Sky (Jimi Hendrix album)|Kiss the Sky]]'' compilation.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=553}}  The original mono take became available in the US and Canada when it was released  (without most of the studio talk at the end) on the 1994 ''[[Blues (Jimi Hendrix album)|Blues]]'' album.{{sfn|Fairchild|1994|p=21}}\n\n==Other recordings==\n{{quote box|quote=\"Although Hendrix seeks to follow roughly the same musical roadmap in each performance, visiting many of the same locations, he never takes the same route twice\"|source=\u2014Tom Wheeler & Joe Gore, ''Variations on a Theme: Red House'' (1992){{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=3}}|width=25%|bgcolor = #E0E6F8 |align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\n\n\"Red House\" was a staple of Jimi Hendrix's concerts and [[jam session]]s and often his performances showed considerable variety.{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=3}} Some later renditions show [[B.B. King]] influences as well as the use of [[T-Bone Walker]]-style [[ninth chord]]s and [[Curtis Mayfield]] rhythm stylings.{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|pp=3\u20134}}  Also, it was one of few songs that Hendrix sometimes used a guitar other than a [[Fender Stratocaster]], choosing mostly a [[Gibson Flying V]]{{sfn|Heatley|2009|p=134}} and occasionally a [[Gibson SG]] Custom.{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=5}}  Redding normally accompanied him on his signature [[Fender Jazz]] bass,{{sfn|Redding|Appleby|1990|p=45}} instead of a guitar; Cox also used a bass.{{sfn|Heatley|2009|p=142|ps=: \"Billy Cox provided a more solid bass foundation than converted guitarist Noel Redding\".}}\n  \n''Variations on a Theme: Red House'' (1992), a music reference with analyses, transcriptions, and accompanying [[Compact Disc Digital Audio|compact disc]], explores several live versions.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=253}}  Several more performances have been released on various live and compilation albums over the years.{{sfn|Belmo|Loveless|1998|pp=415\u2013425}}<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/song/red-house-mt0008918982\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Red House \u2013 Song Review\n| last = Greenwald \n| first = Matthew\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = December 4, 2013\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Ward\">\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/song/red-house-mt0008575075\n| last = Ward\n| first = Thomas \n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Red House \u2013 Song Review\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = December 4, 2013\n}}</ref>  Generally, these later performances were much longer (on ''Variations'' they range from seven to fourteen minutes){{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|loc=Back cover}}  than the original recording and slower (36 to 60 bpm with shifts in tempo, on ''Variations''). Some of these later versions by the Experience and Hendrix's later lineups include (all live, except two studio performances):{{efn|\"Red House\" appears on several earlier album editions that are now out of print \u2013 the albums listed are limited to those currently available.}}\n*October 9, 1967, at the [[Olympia (Paris)|Olympia Theatre]] in Paris (''[[Paris 1967/San Francisco 1968]]'')<ref name=\"Paris 1967/SF\">\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/paris-1967-san-francisco-1968/\n| title = Paris 1967 / San Francisco 1968\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2003\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*January 29, 1968, also at the Olympia (''[[Live in Paris & Ottawa 1968]]'');<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/live-paris-ottawa-1968/\n| title = Live in Paris & Ottawa 1968\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2008\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>  for the performance, Redding revisited the original by playing the bass part on guitar (a [[Gibson Les Paul]] Custom, borrowed last minute from Keith Richards){{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=245}}{{efn|In Paris in 1968, Hendrix introduced the song as featuring Redding on guitar, although his part is limited to the bass accompaniment.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=245}}}}\n*February 4, 1968,  at the [[The Fillmore|Fillmore Auditorium]] in San Francisco (''Paris 1967/San Francisco 1968'')<ref name=\"Paris 1967/SF\"/>\n*March 1968, at a jam at [[The Scene (performance venue)|the Scene]] club in New York City (''[[Woke Up This Morning and Found Myself Dead]]''); unlike his other versions, Hendrix used a guitar figure similar to [[Cream (band)|Cream]]'s \"[[Crossroads (Cream song)|Crossroads]]\"{{sfn|Murray|1991|p=220}}{{efn|Although [[Cream (band)|Cream]]'s \"[[Crossroads (Cream song)|Crossroads]]\" was not officially released until ''[[Wheels of Fire]]'' in August 1968, they had been playing it since 1966.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/bbc-sessions-mw0000023539\n| title = Cream: BBC Sessions \u2013 Review\n| last = Unterberger\n| first = Richie\n| authorlink = Richie Unterberger\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = December 8, 2014\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>}}\n*March 15, 1968, at [[Clark University]], in Worcester, Massachusetts (''[[Live at Clark University]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/live-clark-university/\n| title = Live at Clark University\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 1999\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*March 19, 1968, at the [[Capitol Cinema (Ottawa)|Capitol Theatre]] in Ottawa, Canada (''[[Live in Ottawa]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/dagger-live-ottawa/\n| title = Dagger: Live in Ottawa\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2001\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*May 18, 1968, at the [[Miami Pop Festival (May 1968)|Miami Pop Festival]] (''[[Miami Pop Festival (Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Miami Pop Festival]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/miami-pop-festival-cd-and-limited-edition-2lp/\n| title = Miami Pop Festival (CD and Limited Edition 2LP)\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2013\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*October 10, 11, and 12, 1968, (three versions) at the [[Winterland Ballroom]] in San Francisco (''[[Winterland (The Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Winterland]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/winterland-4cd-and-8lp-box-sets/\n| title = Winterland (4CD and 8LP Box Sets)\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2011\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*October 29, 1968, at [[TTG Studios]] in Hollywood (''[[Blues (Jimi Hendrix album)|Blues]]''), this version was performed in the style of \"[[Voodoo Chile]]\" with organist [[Lee Michaels]]{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=165}}{{efn|The 1968 [[TTG Studios]] version on ''[[Blues (Jimi Hendrix album)|Blues]]'' is actually a composite of two songs, with an earlier recorded TTG jam named \"Electric Church\" serving as the intro{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=165}} (''Variations on a Theme'' includes an extra 1:15 of the intro jam).}}\n*February 17, 1969, at [[Olympic Studios]] in London (''[[Valleys of Neptune]]''); it was recorded during a rehearsal for the upcoming Experience concerts at the [[Royal Albert Hall]].{{sfn|McDermott|2010a|p=7}}\n*April 27, 1969, at the [[Oakland Coliseum]] (''[[Live at the Oakland Coliseum]]''){{sfn|Belmo|Loveless|1998|p=421}}\n*May 24, 1969, at the [[San Diego Sports Arena]] (''[[Hendrix in the West]]''{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|pp=543\u2013544}} and ''[[The Jimi Hendrix Experience (album)|The Jimi Hendrix Experience]]'' box set<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/jimi-hendrix-experience-box-set-0/\n| title = The Jimi Hendrix Experience Box Set\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2013\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>)\n*August 18, 1969, at [[Woodstock]] (''[[Live at Woodstock (Jimi Hendrix album)|Live at Woodstock]]'');<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/live-woodstock/\n| title = Live at Woodstock (2CD and Vinyl Version)\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2010\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>{{efn|At [[Woodstock]], Hendrix played much of the song with a broken string.{{sfn|Heatley|2009|p=144}}}} it did not appear in the 1970 [[Woodstock (film)|''Woodstock'' film]] or the ''[[Woodstock: Music from the Original Soundtrack and More]]'' album\n*May 30, 1970, at the [[Berkeley Community Theater]] (''[[West Coast Seattle Boy: The Jimi Hendrix Anthology]]''){{sfn|McDermott|2010b|p=47}}\n*July 4, 1970, at the [[Atlanta International Pop Festival (1970)]] (''[[Freedom: Atlanta Pop Festival]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/freedom-atlanta-pop-festival/\n| title = Freedom: Jimi Hendrix Experience Atlanta Pop Festival\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2015\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*July 17, 1970, at the New York Pop Festival at [[Downing Stadium]], Randall's Island, New York City (''[[Voodoo Child: The Jimi Hendrix Collection]]''){{sfn|Loder|2001|p=14}}\n*August 30, 1970, at the [[Isle of Wight Festival 1970]] (''[[Blue Wild Angel: Live at the Isle of Wight]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/blue-wild-angel-jimi-hendrix-live-isle-wight/\n| title = Blue Wild Angel: Jimi Hendrix Live at the Isle of Wight\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2011\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*September 6, 1970, at the Open Air Love & Peace Festival in Fehmarn, Germany (''[[Live at the Isle of Fehmarn]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/live-isle-fehmarn/\n| title = Live at the Isle of Fehmarn\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2005\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n\n==Renditions by other artists==\n\"Red House\" has been performed by many blues and other musicians.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/search/songs/red+house\n| title = Song Search Results for Red House\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = August 8, 2014\n}}</ref> Albert King, whose \"Travelin' to California\" inspired Hendrix, recorded a version for his final studio album, ''Red House'' (1991).<ref>{{Discogs master|640099|Red House|type=album}}</ref>  Another Hendrix influence, Buddy Guy, recorded it for ''[[Stone Free: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix]]''.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/stone-free-a-tribute-to-jimi-hendrix-mw0000105470\n| title = Various Artists \u2013 Stone Free: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix\n| last = Erlewine\n| first = Stephen Thomas\n| authorlink = Stephen Thomas Erlewine\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = August 21, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref> Murray describes two versions by John Lee Hooker: a \"more or less straight\" version recorded in 1989 that appears on ''Variations on a Theme'' (1992) and later a \"radically Hookerized and thoroughly deconstructed version\" for the [[Van Morrison]]-produced ''[[Don't Look Back (John Lee Hooker album)|Don't Look Back]]'' (1997).{{sfn|Murray|2002|p=463}}  [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] reworked it as \"Purple House\" for the 2004 tribute ''[[Power of Soul: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix]]'', which also included Hooker's 1997 version of the song.  In an [[AllMusic]] review, critic Sean Westergaard comments: \"Prince reinterprets 'Red House' with great gospel-esque backing vocals and a monstrous guitar solo.\"<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/power-of-soul-a-tribute-to-jimi-hendrix-mw0000331901\n| title = Various artists \u2013 ''Power of Soul: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix''\n| last = Westergaard\n| first = Sean\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = August 26, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{Notelist|30em}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n'''References'''\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Belmo\n| last2 = Loveless\n| first2 = Steve\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Experience the Music\n| year = 1998\n| publisher = [[Collector's Guide Publishing]]\n| location = Burlington, Ontario\n| isbn = 1-896522-45-9\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Black\n| first = Johnny\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: The Ultimate Experience\n| publisher = [[Thunder's Mouth Press]]\n| location = New York City\n| year = 1999\n| isbn = 1-56025-240-5\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/jimihendrixultim00blac\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Carroll\n| first = Jeffrey\n| year = 2005\n| title = When Your Way Gets Dark: A Rhetoric of the Blues\n| location = West Lafayette, Indiana\n| publisher = Parlor Press\n| isbn = 978-1932559385\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Cross\n| first = Charles R.\n| authorlink = Charles R. Cross\n| title = [[Room Full of Mirrors|Room Full of Mirrors: A Biography of Jimi Hendrix]]\n| edition = 1st. Trade Paperback\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[Hachette Books#Hyperion Books|Hyperion Books]]\n| year = 2005\n| isbn = 0-7868-8841-5 \n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite AV media notes\n| title = [[Blues (Jimi Hendrix album)|Jimi Hendrix: Blues]]\n| others = [[Jimi Hendrix]]\n| first = Michael J.\n| last = Fairchild\n| year = 1994\n| type = CD booklet\n| publisher = [[MCA Records]]\n| location = New York City\n| id = MCAD-11060 \n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| author = Hal Leonard\n| title = Experience Hendrix: The Best of Jimi Hendrix Transcribed Scores\n| year = 1998\n| location = Milwaukee, Wisconsin\n| publisher = [[Hal Leonard Corporation|Hal Leonard]]\n| isbn = 978-0-7935-9144-2 \n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Heatley\n| first = Michael\n| authorlink = Michael Heatley\n| year = 2009\n| title = Jimi Hendrix Gear\n| location = Minneapolis, Minnesota\n| publisher = [[Voyageur Press]]\n| isbn = 978-1610604215\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Hendrix\n| first = Janie\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: The Lyrics\n| year = 2003\n| location = Milwaukee, Wisconsin\n| publisher = [[Hal Leonard Corporation|Hal Leonard]]\n| isbn = 0-634-04930-5\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite AV media notes\n| title = [[Voodoo Child: The Jimi Hendrix Collection]]\n| others = [[Jimi Hendrix]]\n| year = 2001\n| last = Loder\n| first = Kurt\n| authorlink = Kurt Loder\n| type = Album notes\n| publisher = [[MCA Records]]\n| id = 088 112 603-2\n| location = Santa Monica, California\n| OCLC = \n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = McDermott\n| first1 = John\n| last2 = Kramer\n| first2 = Eddie\n| authorlink2 = Eddie Kramer\n| last3 = Cox\n| first3 = Billy\n| authorlink3 = Billy Cox\n| title = Ultimate Hendrix\n| publisher = [[Backbeat Books]]\n| location = New York City\n| year = 2009\n| isbn = 0-87930-938-5\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite AV media notes\n| title = [[Valleys of Neptune]]\n| others = Jimi Hendrix\n| year = 2010a\n| last = McDermott\n| first = John\n| type = CD booklet\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[Legacy Records]]\n| id = 88697 64056 2\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite AV media notes\n| title = [[West Coast Seattle Boy: The Jimi Hendrix Anthology]]\n| others = [[Jimi Hendrix]]\n| year = 2010b\n| first  = John\n| last = McDermott\n| type = CD set booklet\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[Sony Legacy|Legacy]]\n| id = 88697769272\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite AV media notes\n| title = Live at George's Club 20\n| others = [[Curtis Knight]] [Featuring Jimi Hendrix]\n| year = 2017\n| last = McDermott\n| first = John\n| type = Album notes\n| publisher = [[Dagger Records]]\n| id = 88985410162\n| location = New York City\n| OCLC = 992175290\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Murray\n| first = Charles Shaar\n| authorlink = Charles Shaar Murray\n| title = Crosstown Traffic\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]]\n| year = 1991\n| isbn = 0-312-06324-5\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/crosstowntraffic00murr\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Murray\n| first = Charles Shaar\n| authorlink = Charles Shaar Murray\n| title = Boogie Man: The Adventures of John Lee Hooker in the American Twentieth Century\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]\n| year = 2002\n| isbn = 978-0-312-27006-3\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Norton\n| first = Kay\n| year = 2016\n| title = Singing and Wellbeing: Ancient Wisdom, Modern Proof\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[Routledge]]\n| isbn =  978-1317578871\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Perry\n| first = John\n| title = Jimi Hendrix's Electric Ladyland\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[Continuum Books]]\n| year = 2004\n| isbn = 978-0826415714\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/electricladyland00perr\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Redding\n| first1 =  Noel\n| authorlink = Noel Redding\n| last2 = Appleby\n| first2 = Carol\n| title = Are You Experienced?\n| publisher = Pan Books\n| year = 1990\n| isbn = 0-330-31923-X \n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Roby\n| first = Steven\n| title = Black Gold: The Lost Archives of Jimi Hendrix\n| publisher = [[Billboard Publications|Billboard Books]]\n| location = New York City\n| year = 2002\n| isbn = 0-8230-7854-X\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/blackgoldlostarc00roby\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Roby\n| first1 = Steven\n| last2 = Schreiber\n| first2 = Brad\n| title = [[Becoming Jimi Hendrix]]\n| publisher = [[Da Capo Press]]\n| location = Cambridge, Massachusetts\n| year = 2010\n| isbn = 978-0-306-81910-0 \n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Shadwick\n| first = Keith\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Musician\n| edition = 1st.\n| publisher = [[Backbeat Books]]\n| location = San Francisco\n| year = 2003\n| isbn = 0-87930-764-1 \n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Shapiro\n| first1 = Harry\n| authorlink1 = Harry Shapiro (author)\n| last2 = Glebbeek\n| first2 = Cesar\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Electric Gypsy\n| publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]]\n| location = New York City\n| year = 1990\n| isbn = 0-312-05861-6\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/jimihendrixelec000shap\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Wheeler\n| first1 = Tom\n| last2 = Gore\n| first2 = Joe\n| title = Variations on a Theme: Red House\n| year = 1992\n| location = Milwaukee, Wisconsin\n| publisher = Bella Godiva Music/[[Hal Leonard Publishing]]\n| isbn = 0-7935-1719-2 \n| ref = harv}}\n\n{{Jimi Hendrix}}\n{{Jimi Hendrix songs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red House (Song)}}\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:The Jimi Hendrix Experience songs]]\n[[Category:Blues songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jimi Hendrix]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Chas Chandler]]\n\n[[sv:Red House]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Song first recorded by the Jimi Hendrix Experience in 1966}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Other uses|Red House (disambiguation){{!}}Red House}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name = Red House\n| type = song\n| artist = [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]]\n| album = [[Are You Experienced]]\n| released = {{Start date|1967|05|12}}\n| recorded = December 13, 1966\n| studio = [[CBS Records International|CBS]], London\n| genre = <!-- Provide reliable sources for changes -->[[Blues]]{{sfn|Carroll|2005|p=107|ps=: \"Hendrix playing 'Red House' in 1966 in England for his first album{{nbsp}}... was not producing the hybrid of blues-rock, as he did later in live performance, but was instead producing an indigenous blues displaying those differences directly attributable to Hendrix's cultural life\".}}\n| length = {{Duration|m=3|s=44}}\n| label = [[Track Records|Track]]\n| writer = [[Jimi Hendrix]]\n| producer = [[Chas Chandler]] \n}}\n\"'''Red House'''\" is a song written by [[Jimi Hendrix]] and one of the first songs recorded in 1966 by [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]].  It has the [[musical form]] of a conventional [[twelve-bar blues]] and features Hendrix's guitar playing.  He developed the song prior to forming the Experience and was inspired by earlier blues songs.  \n\n\"Red House\" was first released on the British edition of Hendrix's debut album ''[[Are You Experienced]]'' in May 1967 (for the American album release, previously released Experience singles were used in its place).  A second similar take was eventually released in the US in July 1969 on the American ''[[Smash Hits (The Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Smash Hits]]'' compilation.\n\nThe song was a fixture of Hendrix concerts throughout his career.  Although the lyrics and basic structure were followed, his performances usually varied from the original recording.  Many were recorded and continue to be released officially for the first time, including on ''[[Miami Pop Festival (Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Miami Pop Festival]]'' (2013) and ''[[Freedom: Atlanta Pop Festival]]'' (2015). \"Red House\" has also been performed and recorded by a variety of blues and other artists.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Albert King 1978.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Albert King in Paris, 1978]]\n\"Red House\" was inspired by blues songs Hendrix was performing early in his career as a sideman.  Music critic [[Charles Shaar Murray]] describes a song he calls \"California Night\", which Hendrix performed with [[Curtis Knight and the Squires]], as \"a dead ringer, both in structure and mood, for his 1967 perennial 'Red House'\".{{sfn|Murray|1991|p=139}}  Originally recorded by [[Albert King]] in 1961 as \"Travelin' to California\",{{sfn|McDermott|2017|p=11}} it is a slow blues with lyrics that follow the common blues theme of the rambling man and his lost love (sometimes also misidentified as \"[[Every Day I Have the Blues]]\" \u2013 both songs use the verse \"nobody loves me\").{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=67}}{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=581}}{{efn|[[Albert King]]'s \"Travelin' to California\" was issued as a single in 1961 (King 5588)<ref>{{Discogs master|1115450|Travelin' to California|type=single}}</ref> and included on his album ''[[The Big Blues]]'' (1962); he also recorded it for [[Chess Records]] in 1961 \u2013 it was released with the title \"California\" or \"California Blues\" on the ''Door to Door'' (1969) compilation album (Chess LP-1538).<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/door-to-door-mw0000201978\n| title = Albert King / Otis Rush: ''Door to Door''\n| last = Koda\n| first = Cub\n| authorlink = Cub Koda\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = August 21, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>}}\n\nHendrix recorded two live versions of \"Travelin' to California\" with Knight, which prominently feature his vocal and guitar playing.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=584}}  Both were recorded at George's Club 22 in Hackensack, New Jersey, on December 26, 1965 and/or January 22, 1966.{{sfn|McDermott|2017|p=10}}  After Hendrix's death in 1970, the recordings (using various names) were released by several European record companies that specialized in [[Bootleg recording|bootleg]] and [[grey-market]] albums.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|pp=581, 584}} In 2017, a version was officially released on ''Curtis Knight [Featuring Jimi Hendrix]: Live at George's Club 20''.{{sfn|McDermott|2017|pp=10\u201311}}\n\nMusic writer Keith Shadwick describes Hendrix's performance as \"a staggering display of blues guitar playing that is worthy of mention in the same breath as his later efforts with the Experience\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=67}} Although Shadwick compares his guitar tone and phraseology to that of [[Buddy Guy]], he adds that his techniques \"simply transcend any previous models, and breaks new ground\" and shows that \"his ability to spin out long and consistently surprising lines across the standard blues changes is already full grown\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=67}} In 1966, during his residency as [[Jimmy James and the Blue Flames]] at the [[Cafe Wha?]] in New York City's Greenwich Village, Hendrix continued to develop his slow blues number that became \"Red House\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=80}}\n\n==Composition==\n\"Red House\" is a moderately slow blues, which music writers Tom Wheeler and Joe Gore describe as having \"the [[twelve-bar blues|twelve-bar structure]], the lyrics, the accompaniment, and the arrangement [that] are more or less conventional\".{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=3}}  The song is notated in 12/8 time in the [[key of B]] with a tempo of 66 [[beats per minute]]{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=217}} (although Hendrix fingered the song in the key of B, he usually tuned his guitar one-half step and sometimes one step lower, resulting in a lower pitch).{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=3}}  The song opens with a [[diminished seventh chord]] frequently found in blues songs, including the intros to the [[Robert Johnson (musician)|Robert Johnson]] songs \"[[Dead Shrimp Blues]]\", \"[[Kind Hearted Woman Blues|Kind Hearted Woman]]\", and \"[[32-20 Blues]]\".{{sfn|Fairchild|1994|pp=21\u201322}}   After the four-bar intro, Redding and Experience drummer [[Mitch Mitchell]] come in while Hendrix solos up to the vocal at bar thirteen.{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|pp=218\u2013219}}  After two twelve-bar vocal sections, Hendrix solos for twelve bars, then finishes up with another vocal section.{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|pp=219\u2013227}}\n\nThe song's most prominent characteristic is Hendrix's guitar work.<ref name=\"Ward\"/>  Author Jeffrey Carroll describes his solo as \"concise and packed solid with vocalisms, the bending and glissandos, jumps, drops and whoops of his guitar kept within a traditional structure of a break\".{{sfn|Carroll|2005|p=109}} Shadwick also compares it to a vocal, calling it a \"close approximation of the human voice{{nbsp}}... scooping and bending his phrases to maximum expressive effect\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=93}}  American bluesman [[John Lee Hooker]] commented, \"That 'Red House', that'll make you grab your mother and choke her!  Man, that's really hard, that tears you apart.  He could get down, he could mash it, yeah, Lord!  He had so many blues\".{{sfn|Fairchild|1994|p=18}}\n\n==Lyrics==\nIn his biography ''[[Room Full of Mirrors]]'', biographer [[Charles R. Cross]] comments that the song's theme is \"as old as the blues itself; the singer's woman doesn't love him any more and has moved\".{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=175}} Author Kay Norton describes the broader blues influence as \"balancing a celebration of love and sex with dark humor and wry commentary on loss, mistreatment, corruption, and poverty\".{{sfn|Norton|2016|p=82}}  The lyrics follow a blues [[Call and response (music)|call and response]] or AAB pattern, where the first line (A) is repeated (often with a slight variation), followed by the response (B):\n{{poemquote|\nWait a minute something's wrong here, the key won't unlock this door\nWait a minute something's wrong, Lord have mercy this key won't unlock this door\n(Something's goin' on here)\nI have a bad, bad feeling, that my baby don't live here no more{{nbsp}}...\n\nWell I might as well go back over yonder, way back among the hills\n(Yeah that's what I'm gonna do)\nLord I might as well go back over yonder, way back yonder across the hills\n'Cause if my baby don't love me no more, I know her sister will\n(Yeah, how's that?){{sfn|Hendrix|2003|p=136}}}}\n\nAccording to Experience bassist [[Noel Redding]], Hendrix told him it was about Hendrix' girlfriend in high school, Betty Jean Morgan.{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=175}}  Jimi's brother, [[Leon Hendrix]], also felt that it was about Betty Jean, but also included her sister Maddy,{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=172}} although their house was brown.{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=175}} Shadwick suggests that the song was inspired by [[Linda Keith]], [[Keith Richards]]' then-girlfriend and early Hendrix supporter.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=93}}  Keith referred to her friend's Manhattan apartment, with its red velvet walls and decor,{{sfn|Roby|Schreiber|2010|p=148}} as the \"red house\", and the two frequently stayed there during the summer of 1966.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=78}} In London in 1970, Hendrix met up with Keith and when he performed \"Red House\" at the [[Isle of Wight Festival 1970|1970 Isle of Wight Festival]], he dedicated the song to her and added \"I got to get out of here, because my Linda don't live here no more\" to the lyrics.{{sfn|Roby|Schreiber| 2010|p=182}} However, [[Billy Cox]], longtime friend and bassist for Hendrix' post-Experience groups, explained, \"As far as I know, 'Red House' didn't have any significance in reference to a particular person, place, or thing. It was just a blues number that Jimi put together\".{{sfn|Fairchild|1994|pp=21\u201322}}\n\n==Recording==\n[[File:Noel Redding playing guitar - Photo by Doug Naismith.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Noel Redding returned to playing guitar after quitting the Experience, 1969]]\n\"Red House\" was one of the earliest songs recorded by the Experience.  The group first attempted it at the [[CBS Records International|CBS]] Studios in London on Tuesday, December 13, 1966, following their performance of \"[[Hey Joe#Tim Rose and Jimi Hendrix (1966)|Hey Joe]]\" for the ''[[Ready Steady Go!]]'' music television program.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=92}} Basic tracks for several songs were recorded during the three-hour session.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=27}} Producer [[Chas Chandler]] recalled: \"The 'Red House' on the album [''[[Are You Experienced]]''] came about during the last fifteen minutes of [the December 13] session.  Noel even played rhythm guitar on the track, playing the bass line. Jimi just winged through one take for reference and we started rolling\".{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=29}}\n\nRedding added, \"I had borrowed a terrible old hollow-body electric guitar from someone at the studio{{nbsp}}... because I liked to play along on rhythm to familiarise myself with a sequence, not being quite at home on the bass yet\".{{sfn|Redding|Appleby|1990|p=45}}  The guitar was tuned down one-half step, with the tone controls set to resemble a bass guitar.{{sfn|Black|1999|p=67}}\n\nAdditional takes of the song were recorded at [[De Lane Lea Studios]] on December 21, 1966, which closely followed the earlier arrangement.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=28\u201329}} However, both Hendrix and Redding had problems with missed notes and the takes were not used, except for a backing track that Hendrix later overdubbed at the [[Olympic Studios]] on March 29{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=107}} or early April 1967.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=28\u201329}}\n\n==Releases==\nWhen preparing the final mixes for the Experience's debut album, Chandler chose to use the December 13, 1966, track recorded at CBS:  \"Later when we were scrambling to put the album together, we carted that [December 13 track] out and gave it a listen.  We remixed it at Olympic and added it to the album\".{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=28\u201329}}  [[Track Records]] issued the monaural mix on ''Are You Experienced'',{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=28\u201329}} which was released on May 12, 1967, in the UK.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=50}}  At the time, it was industry practice in the US to include singles on albums.{{sfn|Perry|2004|p=91}}  So when the album was released in the US, \"[[Purple Haze]]\", \"Hey Joe\" and \"[[The Wind Cries Mary]]\" were included at the expense of \"Red House\" and two other songs.{{sfn|Perry|2004|p=91}}  Hendrix later questioned the choice and commented \"Everybody was scared to release 'Red House' in America because they said, 'America don't like the blues, man!'\"{{sfn|Fairchild|1994|p=12}}\n\n\"Red House\" finally saw an American release on July 30, 1969.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=168\u2013169}} [[Reprise Records]] issued a stereo mix of the version recorded at De Lane Lea/Olympic on the ''[[Smash Hits (The Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Smash Hits]]'' compilation.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=28\u201329}} This version was later released internationally on the 1984 ''[[Kiss the Sky (Jimi Hendrix album)|Kiss the Sky]]'' compilation.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=553}}  The original mono take became available in the US and Canada when it was released  (without most of the studio talk at the end) on the 1994 ''[[Blues (Jimi Hendrix album)|Blues]]'' album.{{sfn|Fairchild|1994|p=21}}\n\n==Other recordings==\n{{quote box|quote=\"Although Hendrix seeks to follow roughly the same musical roadmap in each performance, visiting many of the same locations, he never takes the same route twice\"|source=\u2014Tom Wheeler & Joe Gore, ''Variations on a Theme: Red House'' (1992){{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=3}}|width=25%|bgcolor = #E0E6F8 |align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\n\n\"Red House\" was a staple of Jimi Hendrix's concerts and [[jam session]]s and often his performances showed considerable variety.{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=3}} Some later renditions show [[B.B. King]] influences as well as the use of [[T-Bone Walker]]-style [[ninth chord]]s and [[Curtis Mayfield]] rhythm stylings.{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|pp=3\u20134}}  Also, it was one of few songs that Hendrix sometimes used a guitar other than a [[Fender Stratocaster]], choosing mostly a [[Gibson Flying V]]{{sfn|Heatley|2009|p=134}} and occasionally a [[Gibson SG]] Custom.{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=5}}  Redding normally accompanied him on his signature [[Fender Jazz]] bass,{{sfn|Redding|Appleby|1990|p=45}} instead of a guitar; Cox also used a bass.{{sfn|Heatley|2009|p=142|ps=: \"Billy Cox provided a more solid bass foundation than converted guitarist Noel Redding\".}}\n  \n''Variations on a Theme: Red House'' (1992), a music reference with analyses, transcriptions, and accompanying [[Compact Disc Digital Audio|compact disc]], explores several live versions.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=253}}  Several more performances have been released on various live and compilation albums over the years.{{sfn|Belmo|Loveless|1998|pp=415\u2013425}}<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/song/red-house-mt0008918982\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Red House \u2013 Song Review\n| last = Greenwald \n| first = Matthew\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = December 4, 2013\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Ward\">\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/song/red-house-mt0008575075\n| last = Ward\n| first = Thomas \n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Red House \u2013 Song Review\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = December 4, 2013\n}}</ref>  Generally, these later performances were much longer (on ''Variations'' they range from seven to fourteen minutes){{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|loc=Back cover}}  than the original recording and slower (36 to 60 bpm with shifts in tempo, on ''Variations''). Some of these later versions by the Experience and Hendrix's later lineups include (all live, except two studio performances):{{efn|\"Red House\" appears on several earlier album editions that are now out of print \u2013 the albums listed are limited to those currently available.}}\n*October 9, 1967, at the [[Olympia (Paris)|Olympia Theatre]] in Paris (''[[Paris 1967/San Francisco 1968]]'')<ref name=\"Paris 1967/SF\">\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/paris-1967-san-francisco-1968/\n| title = Paris 1967 / San Francisco 1968\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2003\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*January 29, 1968, also at the Olympia (''[[Live in Paris & Ottawa 1968]]'');<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/live-paris-ottawa-1968/\n| title = Live in Paris & Ottawa 1968\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2008\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>  for the performance, Redding revisited the original by playing the bass part on guitar (a [[Gibson Les Paul]] Custom, borrowed last minute from Keith Richards){{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=245}}{{efn|In Paris in 1968, Hendrix introduced the song as featuring Redding on guitar, although his part is limited to the bass accompaniment.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=245}}}}\n*February 4, 1968,  at the [[The Fillmore|Fillmore Auditorium]] in San Francisco (''Paris 1967/San Francisco 1968'')<ref name=\"Paris 1967/SF\"/>\n*March 1968, at a jam at [[The Scene (performance venue)|the Scene]] club in New York City (''[[Woke Up This Morning and Found Myself Dead]]''); unlike his other versions, Hendrix used a guitar figure similar to [[Cream (band)|Cream]]'s \"[[Crossroads (Cream song)|Crossroads]]\"{{sfn|Murray|1991|p=220}}{{efn|Although [[Cream (band)|Cream]]'s \"[[Crossroads (Cream song)|Crossroads]]\" was not officially released until ''[[Wheels of Fire]]'' in August 1968, they had been playing it since 1966.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/bbc-sessions-mw0000023539\n| title = Cream: BBC Sessions \u2013 Review\n| last = Unterberger\n| first = Richie\n| authorlink = Richie Unterberger\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = December 8, 2014\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>}}\n*March 15, 1968, at [[Clark University]], in Worcester, Massachusetts (''[[Live at Clark University]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/live-clark-university/\n| title = Live at Clark University\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 1999\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*March 19, 1968, at the [[Capitol Cinema (Ottawa)|Capitol Theatre]] in Ottawa, Canada (''[[Live in Ottawa]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/dagger-live-ottawa/\n| title = Dagger: Live in Ottawa\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2001\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*May 18, 1968, at the [[Miami Pop Festival (May 1968)|Miami Pop Festival]] (''[[Miami Pop Festival (Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Miami Pop Festival]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/miami-pop-festival-cd-and-limited-edition-2lp/\n| title = Miami Pop Festival (CD and Limited Edition 2LP)\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2013\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*October 10, 11, and 12, 1968, (three versions) at the [[Winterland Ballroom]] in San Francisco (''[[Winterland (The Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Winterland]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/winterland-4cd-and-8lp-box-sets/\n| title = Winterland (4CD and 8LP Box Sets)\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2011\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*October 29, 1968, at [[TTG Studios]] in Hollywood (''[[Blues (Jimi Hendrix album)|Blues]]''), this version was performed in the style of \"[[Voodoo Chile]]\" with organist [[Lee Michaels]]{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=165}}{{efn|The 1968 [[TTG Studios]] version on ''[[Blues (Jimi Hendrix album)|Blues]]'' is actually a composite of two songs, with an earlier recorded TTG jam named \"Electric Church\" serving as the intro{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=165}} (''Variations on a Theme'' includes an extra 1:15 of the intro jam).}}\n*February 17, 1969, at [[Olympic Studios]] in London (''[[Valleys of Neptune]]''); it was recorded during a rehearsal for the upcoming Experience concerts at the [[Royal Albert Hall]].{{sfn|McDermott|2010a|p=7}}\n*April 27, 1969, at the [[Oakland Coliseum]] (''[[Live at the Oakland Coliseum]]''){{sfn|Belmo|Loveless|1998|p=421}}\n*May 24, 1969, at the [[San Diego Sports Arena]] (''[[Hendrix in the West]]''{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|pp=543\u2013544}} and ''[[The Jimi Hendrix Experience (album)|The Jimi Hendrix Experience]]'' box set<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/jimi-hendrix-experience-box-set-0/\n| title = The Jimi Hendrix Experience Box Set\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2013\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>)\n*August 18, 1969, at [[Woodstock]] (''[[Live at Woodstock (Jimi Hendrix album)|Live at Woodstock]]'');<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/live-woodstock/\n| title = Live at Woodstock (2CD and Vinyl Version)\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2010\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>{{efn|At [[Woodstock]], Hendrix played much of the song with a broken string.{{sfn|Heatley|2009|p=144}}}} it did not appear in the 1970 [[Woodstock (film)|''Woodstock'' film]] or the ''[[Woodstock: Music from the Original Soundtrack and More]]'' album\n*May 30, 1970, at the [[Berkeley Community Theater]] (''[[West Coast Seattle Boy: The Jimi Hendrix Anthology]]''){{sfn|McDermott|2010b|p=47}}\n*July 4, 1970, at the [[Atlanta International Pop Festival (1970)]] (''[[Freedom: Atlanta Pop Festival]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/freedom-atlanta-pop-festival/\n| title = Freedom: Jimi Hendrix Experience Atlanta Pop Festival\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2015\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*July 17, 1970, at the New York Pop Festival at [[Downing Stadium]], Randall's Island, New York City (''[[Voodoo Child: The Jimi Hendrix Collection]]''){{sfn|Loder|2001|p=14}}\n*August 30, 1970, at the [[Isle of Wight Festival 1970]] (''[[Blue Wild Angel: Live at the Isle of Wight]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/blue-wild-angel-jimi-hendrix-live-isle-wight/\n| title = Blue Wild Angel: Jimi Hendrix Live at the Isle of Wight\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2011\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n*September 6, 1970, at the Open Air Love & Peace Festival in Fehmarn, Germany (''[[Live at the Isle of Fehmarn]]'')<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.jimihendrix.com/music/live-isle-fehmarn/\n| title = Live at the Isle of Fehmarn\n| website = JimiHendrix.com (official website)\n| date = 2005\n| accessdate = October 20, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n\n==Renditions by other artists==\n\"Red House\" has been performed by many blues and other musicians.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/search/songs/red+house\n| title = Song Search Results for Red House\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = August 8, 2014\n}}</ref> Albert King, whose \"Travelin' to California\" inspired Hendrix, recorded a version for his final studio album, ''Red House'' (1991).<ref>{{Discogs master|640099|Red House|type=album}}</ref>  Another Hendrix influence, Buddy Guy, recorded it for ''[[Stone Free: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix]]''.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/stone-free-a-tribute-to-jimi-hendrix-mw0000105470\n| title = Various Artists \u2013 Stone Free: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix\n| last = Erlewine\n| first = Stephen Thomas\n| authorlink = Stephen Thomas Erlewine\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = August 21, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref> Murray describes two versions by John Lee Hooker: a \"more or less straight\" version recorded in 1989 that appears on ''Variations on a Theme'' (1992) and later a \"radically Hookerized and thoroughly deconstructed version\" for the [[Van Morrison]]-produced ''[[Don't Look Back (John Lee Hooker album)|Don't Look Back]]'' (1997).{{sfn|Murray|2002|p=463}}  [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] reworked it as \"Purple House\" for the 2004 tribute ''[[Power of Soul: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix]]'', which also included Hooker's 1997 version of the song.  In an [[AllMusic]] review, critic Sean Westergaard comments: \"Prince reinterprets 'Red House' with great gospel-esque backing vocals and a monstrous guitar solo.\"<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/power-of-soul-a-tribute-to-jimi-hendrix-mw0000331901\n| title = Various artists \u2013 ''Power of Soul: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix''\n| last = Westergaard\n| first = Sean\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = August 26, 2017\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{Notelist|30em}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n'''References'''\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Belmo\n| last2 = Loveless\n| first2 = Steve\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Experience the Music\n| year = 1998\n| publisher = [[Collector's Guide Publishing]]\n| location = Burlington, Ontario\n| isbn = 1-896522-45-9\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Black\n| first = Johnny\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: The Ultimate Experience\n| publisher = [[Thunder's Mouth Press]]\n| location = New York City\n| year = 1999\n| isbn = 1-56025-240-5\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/jimihendrixultim00blac\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Carroll\n| first = Jeffrey\n| year = 2005\n| title = When Your Way Gets Dark: A Rhetoric of the Blues\n| location = West Lafayette, Indiana\n| publisher = Parlor Press\n| isbn = 978-1932559385\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Cross\n| first = Charles R.\n| authorlink = Charles R. Cross\n| title = [[Room Full of Mirrors|Room Full of Mirrors: A Biography of Jimi Hendrix]]\n| edition = 1st. Trade Paperback\n| location = New York City\n| pu