{"title_page": "Queen Rania of Jordan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}} \n{{Infobox royalty\n| name           = Rania\n| image          = Queen Rania of Jordan Official Release 05 (cropped).jpg\n| caption        = Queen Rania during a visit in May 2018\n| consort        = yes\n| succession     = [[List of Jordanian consorts|Queen consort of Jordan]]\n| reign          = 7 February 1999\u2013present\n| coronation     = 22 March 1999\n| cor-type       = Proclamation\n| birth_name     = Rania Al-Yassin\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1970|8|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Kuwait City]], Kuwait\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| burial_date    =\n| burial_place   =\n| spouse         = {{marriage|[[Abdullah II of Jordan]]|10 June 1993}}\n| issue          = [[Hussein, Crown Prince of Jordan|Crown Prince Hussein]] <br> [[Princess Iman bint Abdullah|Princess Iman]] <br> [[Princess Salma bint Abdullah|Princess Salma]] <br> [[Prince Hashem bin Abdullah|Prince Hashem]] \n| full name      = Rania Al-Abdullah\n| house          = <!--Do not add a royal house or dynasty unless you have an official source. People are born into dynasties of ruling families. Whether or not a person is confirmed to belong to a dynasty by marriage requires a source that proves that fact. -->\n| father         = Faisal Sedki Al-Yassin\n| mother         = Ilham Yassin\n| religion       = [[Islam]]\n| signature      = Queen Rania of Jordan signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Rania Al-Abdullah''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647}}, {{transl|ar|ALA|''R\u0101niy\u0101 al-\u02bbAbd All\u0101h''}}; born '''Rania Al-Yassin''' on 31 August 1970) is the [[List of Jordanian consorts|queen consort]] of [[Jordan]]. Born in [[Kuwait]] to a Palestinian family, she later moved to Jordan for work, where she met the then prince [[Abdullah II of Jordan|Abdullah]]. Since marrying the now King of Jordan in 1993, she has become known for her advocacy work related to [[Education in Jordan|education]], health, community empowerment, youth, cross-cultural dialogue and [[micro-finance]]. She is also an avid user of social media and she maintains pages on [[Facebook]], [[YouTube]], [[Instagram]] and [[Twitter]]. She has two daughters and two sons and has been awarded various decorations by governments.\n\n==Personal life==\n===Early life===\n{{Jordanian Royal Family}}\nRania Al-Yassin was born in [[Kuwait]], to [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] parents. She received a degree in [[Business Administration]] from the [[American University in Cairo]]. Upon her graduation from the American University, she worked briefly in marketing for [[Citibank]], followed by a job with [[Apple Inc.]] in [[Amman]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile: Jordan's Queen Rania|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/1632614.stm|website=BBC|accessdate=8 January 2018|date=7 November 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107032257/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/1632614.stm|archivedate=7 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Marriage and family===\nShe met Jordanian [[Abdullah II of Jordan|Abdullah bin Al-Hussein]], who was a prince at that time, at a dinner party in August 1992. Six months later, they announced their engagement. On 10 June 1993, they were married. The couple has four children:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/royalty/2013083114363/queen-raina-jordan-43-birthday-facts/|title=Ten facts about Queen Rania of Jordan on her 43rd birthday|publisher=Hello Magazine|date=31 August 2013|accessdate=31 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924051335/http://www.hellomagazine.com/royalty/2013083114363/queen-raina-jordan-43-birthday-facts/|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n*[[Hussein, Crown Prince of Jordan|Crown Prince Hussein]] (born 28 June 1994 in [[Amman]])\n*[[Princess Iman bint Abdullah|Princess Iman]] (born 27 September 1996 in [[Amman]])\n*[[Princess Salma bint Abdullah|Princess Salma]] (born 26 September 2000 in [[Amman]])\n*[[Prince Hashem bin Abdullah|Prince Hashem]] (born 30 January 2005 in [[Amman]])\n\nHer husband ascended the throne on 7 February 1999, and proclaimed her queen on 22 March 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jordanembassyus.org/032299002.htm |title=King proclaims Rania Queen |publisher=Jordanembassyus.org |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605171654/http://www.jordanembassyus.org/032299002.htm |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-incredible-life-of-queen-rania-of-jordan-2018-1#in-february-1999-abdullah-ascended-the-throne-and-proclaimed-rania-as-queen-in-march-now-she-travels-the-world-representing-jordan-but-she-certainly-doesnt-stand-in-her-husbands-shadow-5|title=The incredible life of Jordan's Instagram-famous Queen, an ex-Apple employee, human rights activist, and global style icon|work=Business Insider|access-date=14 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315003756/http://www.businessinsider.com/the-incredible-life-of-queen-rania-of-jordan-2018-1#in-february-1999-abdullah-ascended-the-throne-and-proclaimed-rania-as-queen-in-march-now-she-travels-the-world-representing-jordan-but-she-certainly-doesnt-stand-in-her-husbands-shadow-5|archivedate=15 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Without the proclamation she would have been a princess consort, like her mother-in-law, [[Princess Muna al-Hussein]].\n\n==Areas of work==\nSince her marriage, Queen Rania has used her position to advocate for various sectors of society in Jordan and beyond.\n\n===Domestic agenda===\n\n====Education====\n[[File:Queenraniacopy8452.jpg|thumb|left|Queen Rania during a dinner celebrating the partnership between the Sesame Workshop and the [[Mosaic Foundation]] in Washington, D.C., May 2006]]\nOver the past few years, Queen Rania has launched, championed, and given patronage to several initiatives in education and learning.\n\nIn July 2005, in partnership with the Ministry of Education, the King and Queen launched an annual teachers\u2019 award, the Queen Rania Award for Excellence in Education.<ref name=\"Queen Rania Teachers Award\">[http://www.queenraniaaward.org Queen Rania Award for Excellence in Education] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123042138/http://www.queenraniaaward.org/ |date=23 January 2016 }}.</ref><ref>[http://www1.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-launches-award-honour-school-principals Queen launches award to honor school principals] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722073206/http://www1.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-launches-award-honour-school-principals |date=22 July 2011 }}, 15 April 2009.</ref>\n\nThe Queen is Chairperson of Jordan's first interactive children's museum. Opened in May 2007, it aims to encourage and nurture lifelong learning for children and their families.<ref name=\"Opening Children's Museum\">[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/king-queen-join-jordanian-children-opening-childrens-museum King, Queen join Jordanian children at opening of children's museum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/king-queen-join-jordanian-children-opening-childrens-museum |date=7 January 2016 }}, Jordan Times, 23 May 2007.</ref><ref name=\"Children's Museum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmj.jo/|title=Children's Museum of Jordan|publisher=Cmj|accessdate=20 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725161401/http://www.cmj.jo/|archivedate=25 July 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In April 2008, the Queen launched \u201cMadrasati\u201d (\u201cMy School\u201d), a public-private initiative aimed at refurbishing 500 of Jordan\u2019s public schools over a five-year period.<ref name=\"Madrasati\">{{cite web|url=http://www.madrasati.jo/site.html|title=Madrasati.jo|publisher=Madrasati|accessdate=20 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208230954/http://www.madrasati.jo/site.html|archivedate=8 February 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In higher education, the Queen Rania Scholarship Program<ref name=\"Scholarships\">{{cite web|author=Craig Mead|url=http://www.queenrania.jo/education/students/scholarships|title=Queen Rania Scholarship Program|publisher=Queen Rania|date=27 May 2010|accessdate=20 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102065404/http://www.queenrania.jo/education/students/scholarships|archivedate=2 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> partners with several universities from around the world. Queen Rania is also Chairperson<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-rania-chairs-first-meeting-royal-health-awareness-society Queen Rania chairs first meeting of Royal Health Awareness Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023520/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-rania-chairs-first-meeting-royal-health-awareness-society |date=7 January 2016 }}, 7 September 2005.</ref> of the [[Royal Health Awareness Society]] (RHAS).<ref name=\"RHAS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rhas.org.jo/ |title=Royal Health Awareness Society |publisher=RHAS |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612210717/http://www.rhas.org.jo/ |archivedate=12 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Community empowerment====\n[[File:Queen Rania - World Economic Forum on the Middle East Dead Sea Jordan 2007.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Rania - [[World Economic Forum]] on the Middle East held at the [[Dead Sea, Jordan]], in 2007]]\nQueen Rania's first venture was the establishment of the [[Jordan River Foundation]] (JRF) in 1995.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jordantimes.com/news/local/queen-rania-honours-jordan-river-foundation-supporters|title=Queen Rania honours Jordan River Foundation supporters|date=25 February 2015|work=Jordan Times|access-date=14 March 2018|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315003809/http://jordantimes.com/news/local/queen-rania-honours-jordan-river-foundation-supporters|archivedate=15 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Jordan River Children Program (JRCP) was developed by Queen Rania to place children\u2019s welfare above political agendas and cultural taboos.<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/interviews/il-messaggero-newspaper-lucia-pozzi Interview with Il Messaggero] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/interviews/il-messaggero-newspaper-lucia-pozzi |date=7 January 2016 }}, 13 May 2008.</ref> This led to the launch, in 1998, of JRF\u2019s Child Safety Program, which addresses the immediate needs of children at risk from abuse and initiated a long-term campaign to increase public awareness about violence against children. The deaths of two children in Amman as a result of child abuse in early 2009 led Queen Rania to call for an emergency meeting of government and non-government (including JRF) stakeholders to discuss where the system was failing.<ref>[http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=16383 Queen calls emergency meeting to discuss child abuse cases] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927110546/http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=16383 |date=27 September 2011 }}, Jordan Times, 24 July 2009</ref>\n\nIn 2009, to celebrate the 10th anniversary of her husband's accession to the throne, Queen Rania launched a community champion award ([[Ahel Al Himmeh]]) in March to highlight the accomplishments of groups and individuals who have helped their local communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.himmeh.jo/?q=english |title=Ahel Al Himmeh |publisher=Himmeh.jo |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616062126/http://www.himmeh.jo/?q=english |archivedate=16 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Youth====\nQueen Rania has stated that an essential aspect of education is to equip young people with the necessary skills to perform well in the workplace.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/15840232?video=1199928263 Interview: Gateway to the Middle East], 2009.</ref>\n\nShe initiated the [[Al-Aman Fund for the Future of Orphans]] in 2003,<ref>[http://www.jordanembassyus.org/01222004002.htm Orphans' future security depends on society's commitment, contributions] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314164456/http://www.jordanembassyus.org/01222004002.htm |date=14 March 2012 }}, Jordan Times, 22 January 2004.</ref> and has partnered with international universities providing scholarships for Jordanian students abroad.<ref name=\"Scholarships\"/> She supports [[INJAZ Al-Arab]], which was established by [[Save the Children]] in 1999, and later on with [[Junior Achievement]] and launched as a Jordanian non-profit organization by the Queen in 2001.<ref>[http://www.injazarabic.org INJAZ Al-Arab]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} for the creation of economic opportunity for Jordanian youth.</ref> In her capacity as Regional Ambassador of [[INJAZ Al-Arab]], she has taught classes, and engaged in dialogue with young people in other countries; she also launched [[INJAZ Al-Arab]]'s presence elsewhere in the Arab world.<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/injaz-kuwait-launch INJAZ Kuwait Launch] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/injaz-kuwait-launch |date=7 January 2016 }}, 24 November 2006.</ref> She also chaired a discussion with entrepreneurs in celebration of INJAZ Al-Arab's 10th anniversary, showcasing alumni's success stories <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-chairs-discussion-entrepreneurs-injaz-al-arab-celebrating-its-10th-anniversa |title=Queen Rania  chairs a discussion with entrepreneurs from INJAZ Al-Arab celebrating its 10th anniversary |date=January 2015 |website=Queen rania Al Abdullah |access-date=28 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528104912/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-chairs-discussion-entrepreneurs-injaz-al-arab-celebrating-its-10th-anniversa |archivedate=28 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> At the 2008 World Economic Forum in Davos, she launched the \"Empowering One Million Arab Youth by 2018\" campaign, which was conceived by INJAZ Arabia.<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/empowering-one-million-arab-youth-2018-campaign-launch Queen Rania launches campaign to prepare 1 million Arab youth for workforce] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/empowering-one-million-arab-youth-2018-campaign-launch |date=7 January 2016 }}, 24 January 2008.</ref>\n\n===Global agenda===\n\n====Global education====\n[[File:Queen Rania - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2003.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Rania at the 2003 [[World Economic Forum]] in [[Davos]], [[Switzerland]]]]\nIn November 2000, in recognition of her commitment to the cause of children and youth, the [[United Nations Children\u2019s Fund]] (UNICEF) invited Queen Rania to join its Global Leadership Initiative.<ref name=\"UNICEF GLI\">[http://www.unwire.org/unwire/20001115/11791_story.asp Queen Rania Joins UNICEF Leadership Initiative]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, U.N. Wire, 15 November 2000.</ref> The Queen worked alongside other world leaders, including former South African President Nelson Mandela, in a global movement seeking to improve the welfare of children.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120904053044/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/news/middleeast/news/article_1467254.php/Jordan_s_Queen_Rania_shares_school_bench_in_Soweto_township Jordan's Queen Rania shares school bench in Soweto township], Monsters and Critics, 27 March 2009.</ref> In January 2007, Queen Rania was named UNICEF's first Eminent Advocate for Children.<ref name=\"UNICEF EAC\">[http://www.unicef.org/media/media_38153.html Queen Rania becomes UNICEF\u2019s first Eminent Advocate for Children at the World Economic Forum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303165255/http://www.unicef.org/media/media_38153.html |date=3 March 2016 }}, UNICEF, Press Centre, 26 January 2007.</ref> In August 2009, Queen Rania became Honorary Global Chair of the [[United Nations Girls' Education Initiative]] (UNGEI).<ref name=\"UNGEI\">[http://www.ungei.org/news/index_2181.html Queen Rania designated as Honorary Global Chair of the United Nations Girls\u2019 Education Initiative (UNGEI)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303175515/http://www.ungei.org/news/index_2181.html |date=3 March 2016 }}, UNGEI, 15 July 2009.</ref>\n\nAs a longtime supporter of the Global Campaign for Education (GCE),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.campaignforeducation.org/ |title=Global Campaign for Education |publisher=Campaignforeducation.org |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706205314/http://www.campaignforeducation.org/ |archivedate=6 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Queen Rania met with children and inspirational women in South Africa, both in the cities of Johannesburg and Soweto, in March 2009.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rania-al-abdullah/a-promising-glimpse-of-af_b_180040.html A Promising Glimpse of Africa's Future Can Be Found in Its Children] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131172058/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rania-al-abdullah/a-promising-glimpse-of-af_b_180040.html |date=31 January 2016 }}, Huffington Post, 27 March 2009.</ref> Queen Rania and the women took turns reading a short story out of The Big Read to the children, in an effort to encourage literacy. One of the stories in the book, \u201cMaha of the Mountains\u201d, was contributed by Queen Rania.<ref name=\"Maha\">[http://www.campaignforeducation.org/bigread/stories/queen-rania/index/index.html Maha of the Mountains] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172430/http://www.campaignforeducation.org/bigread/stories/queen-rania/index/index.html |date=3 March 2016 }}, The Big Read, The Global Campaign for Education, 2009.</ref>\nIn Soweto, she was the first to write her name in the back of the Big Read, before passing it on to everyone else to write their name.<ref>[http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/southafrica_48980.html Youth leaders in Soweto greet Queen Rania of Jordan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/southafrica_48980.html |date=7 January 2016 }}, UNICEF, 30 March 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.campaignforeducation.org/docs/pressrelease/Media%20Alert%20-%20Queen%20Rania%20annouced%20as%20honorary%20chair%20of%20Global%20Action%20Week.pdf Queen Rania of Jordan, reads her story to children and announces her role as Honorary Chair of Action Week] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303180126/http://www.campaignforeducation.org/docs/pressrelease/Media%20Alert%20-%20Queen%20Rania%20annouced%20as%20honorary%20chair%20of%20Global%20Action%20Week.pdf |date=3 March 2016 }}, Global Campaign for Education, 27 March 2009.</ref>\n\n[[File:Michelle Obama & Queen Rania of Jordan in the Yellow Oval Room 4-23-09.JPG|left|thumb|First Lady [[Michelle Obama]] hosts Queen Rania in the [[Yellow Oval Room]], April 2009]]\nDuring her April 2009 US trip, Queen Rania joined leading education advocates Congresswoman [[Nita Lowey]] and Counsellor to the Secretary of the Treasury [[Gene Sperling]] to launch \"The Big Read\" as part of Global Campaign for Education's global action week calling for quality basic education for all children.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/21/jordans-queen-rania-congr_n_189690.html Jordan's Queen Rania, Congresswoman Nita Lowey Launch 'The Big Read' Global Education Campaign] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221227/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/21/jordans-queen-rania-congr_n_189690.html |date=3 March 2016 }}, Huffington Post, 21 April 2009.</ref> She was also hosted by first lady of the United States, [[Michelle Obama]], during that same trip.<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/09/04/23/The-First-Lady-and-Queen-Rania/ The First Lady and Queen Rania] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150310041140/http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/09/04/23/The-First-Lady-and-Queen-Rania/ |date=10 March 2015 }}, White House Blog, 23 April 2009.</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2009, Queen Rania co-founded and led the launch of the \"[[1GOAL Education for All|1GOAL: Education for All]]\" campaign alongside [[Gary Lineker]], and with the help of top international footballers at [[Wembley Stadium]], [[London]].<ref name=\"1GOAL\">[http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=19393&searchFor=1GOAL Queen lends support to 1GOAL initiative] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927110552/http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=19393&searchFor=1GOAL |date=27 September 2011 }}, Jordan Times, 21 August 2009.</ref> Queen Rania is co-founder and global co-chair of the 1GOAL campaign to rally World Cup 2010 fans together during the world\u2019s biggest single sporting event and call on world leaders to give 75 million children out of school an education.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.join1goal.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=53&lang=en |title=1GOAL: Education for All |publisher=Join1goal.org |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090827230353/http://www.join1goal.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=53&lang=en |archivedate=27 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 6 October 2009, Queen Rania was joined by Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] of the UK, the President of [[FIFA]], [[Sepp Blatter]], President [[Jacob Zuma]] of South Africa, and other heads of state, for the Global Launch of 1GOAL, which took place across six locations worldwide.<ref name=\"1GOAL Global Launch\">[http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=20517 Queen joins world leaders in launching 1GOAL campaign] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927110557/http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=20517 |date=27 September 2011 }}, Jordan Times, 7 October 2009.</ref> Queen Rania spoke of the need to turn this \u201ctragedy into triumph\u201d and called on political leaders to stand by their aid commitments.<ref name=\"1GOAL Global Launch\"/>\n\nIn 2008, Queen Rania participated in YouTube's In My Name<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/inmyname In My Name] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915030324/https://www.youtube.com/user/inmyname |date=15 September 2016 }}, YouTube Channel.</ref> campaign. She appeared alongside [[The Black Eyed Peas]] member [[will.i.am]] in the video, \"End Poverty \u2013 Be the Generation,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pRyMxSS-KI0 |title=End Poverty \u2013 Be the Generation |publisher=Youtube.com |date=22 September 2008 |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101101012538/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pRyMxSS-KI0 |archivedate=1 November 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which urged world leaders to keep the promises they made in 2000 at the [[United Nations]] [[Millennium Summit]].<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-flumenbaum/celebrities-join-youtube_b_129649.html \"Celebrities Join YouTube at UN to Launch Poverty Campaign\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160212051319/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-flumenbaum/celebrities-join-youtube_b_129649.html |date=12 February 2016 }}, Huffington Post, 26 September 2008.</ref>\n\n====Cross-cultural dialogue====\n[[File:Queen Rania Al Abdullah of Jordan and UK minister Sajid Javid (24182367514).jpg|thumb|right|Queen Rania and [[Sajid Javid]] at ''Supporting Syria and the Region conference'', 2016.]]\nQueen Rania has also been particularly vocal about the importance of cross cultural and interfaith dialogue to foster greater understanding, tolerance and acceptance across the world.<ref>[http://www.jordanembassyus.org/09192005001.htm Queen underscores need to promote cross-cultural dialogue]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301023123/http://www.jordanembassyus.org/09192005001.htm|date=1 March 2012}}, Jordan Times, 19 September 2005.</ref> She has used her status to correct what she sees as misconceptions in [[Western world|the West]] about the [[Arab world]]. Forbes magazine ranked her as one of the world's 100 most powerful women in 2011.<ref name=\"forbes-100\">[https://www.forbes.com/wealth/power-women/list The 100 Most Powerful Women] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101008201657/http://www.forbes.com/wealth/power-women/list |date=8 October 2010 }}, [[Forbes Magazine]], 2011.</ref>\n\nQueen Rania has played a significant role in reaching out to the global community to foster values of tolerance and acceptance, and increase cross-cultural dialogue. For example, regionally and internationally, Queen Rania has campaigned for a greater understanding between cultures in such high-profile forums as the [[Jeddah Economic Forum]],<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-rania-addresses-jeddah-economic-forum-urges-global-community-plant-seeds-accept Queen Rania addresses Jeddah Economic Forum, urges global community to plant seeds of acceptance, dialogue, peace] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-rania-addresses-jeddah-economic-forum-urges-global-community-plant-seeds-accept |date=7 January 2016 }}, 25 February 2007.</ref> the [[Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]],<ref name=\"Harvard\">[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/speeches/john-f-kennedy-school-government-harvard-university Keynote Address] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/speeches/john-f-kennedy-school-government-harvard-university |date=7 January 2016 }}, Harvard University, 3 May 2007.</ref> and the [[Skoll Foundation]]<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/speeches/her-majesty-queen-rania-al-abdullah-remarks-skoll-world-forum-2007 Queen Rania Al Abdullah Remarks at Skoll World Forum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/speeches/her-majesty-queen-rania-al-abdullah-remarks-skoll-world-forum-2007 |date=7 January 2016 }}, 27 March 2007.</ref> in the UK.\n\nQueen Rania has also used [[YouTube]] as a way to promote intercultural dialogue by calling on young people around the world to engage in a global dialogue to dismantle stereotypes of Muslims and the Arab world.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TFf897bUW2Y YOUTUBE EXCLUSIVE: Send me your stereotypes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215045604/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TFf897bUW2Y |date=15 December 2016 }}, Queen Rania Channel, YouTube, 30 March 2008.</ref> She has also made public appearances, including a half-hour television interview on [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]] on 17 May 2006, where she spoke about misconceptions about Islam and especially [[women in Islam]].<ref>[http://www.oprah.com/dated/oprahshow/oprahshow_20060517 Meet the World's Youngest Queen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609012143/http://www.oprah.com/dated/oprahshow/oprahshow_20060517 |date=9 June 2009 }}, Oprah.com, 17 May 2006.</ref><ref>[http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=4057220760334335567&ei=lHAJSujEHobw2gKSi5jABg&q=queen+rania&hl=en Queen Rania on Oprah Winfrey] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629070712/http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=4057220760334335567&ei=lHAJSujEHobw2gKSi5jABg&q=queen+rania&hl=en |date=29 June 2011 }}, Part 1, 17 May 2006.</ref><ref>[http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=7397412902320079243&ei=lHAJSujEHobw2gKSi5jABg&q=queen+rania&hl=en Queen Rania on Oprah Winfrey] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629070657/http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=7397412902320079243&ei=lHAJSujEHobw2gKSi5jABg&q=queen+rania&hl=en |date=29 June 2011 }}, Part 2, 17 May 2006.</ref> For her work in reaching out across cultures she received the [[North-South Prize]] from the [[Council of Europe]] in March 2009<ref>[http://www.coe.int/t/dc/files/events/2008_prix_ns/default_en.asp? North South Prize Acceptance Speech]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522123625/http://www.coe.int/t/dc/files/events/2008_prix_ns/default_en.asp |date=22 May 2011 }}, 16 March 2009.</ref> and the first ever [[YouTube Visionary Award]] in November 2008.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-Z-aQAEA7U8 Queen Rania Accepts YouTube Visionary Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407215356/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-Z-aQAEA7U8 |date=7 April 2016 }}, 22 November 2008.</ref> For her work in cross-cultural peace dialogue Queen Rania accepted the PeaceMaker Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Seeds+of+Peace,+to+Present+Peacemaker+Award+to+Her+Majesty+Queen...-a0162850144 |title=Seeds of Peace, to Present Peacemaker Award to Her Majesty Queen Rania Al-Abdullah of Jordan. \u2013 Free Online Library |publisher=Thefreelibrary.com |date=2 May 2007 |accessdate=20 June 2010}}</ref> from the Non-Profit [[Seeds of Peace]].\n\nIn May 2009, Queen Rania attended the fifth Young Global Leaders Summit at the Dead Sea, Jordan, to address socio-economic challenges facing the region and had trips organized for the Young Global Leaders in which they visited local Madrasati schools, the Jordan River Foundation, and other affiliated organizations.<ref>[http://www.forumblog.org/blog/2009/05/focus-on-leadership-as-queen-rania-opens-ygl-dead-sea-summit.html Focus on leadership as Queen Rania opens YGL Dead Sea Summit] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218080232/http://www.forumblog.org/blog/2009/05/focus-on-leadership-as-queen-rania-opens-ygl-dead-sea-summit.html |date=18 December 2011 }}, 13 May 2009.</ref>\n\nWhen it comes to youth, in early 2002 Queen Rania joined the Board of Directors of the International Youth Foundation, based in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], in the United States.<ref name=\"IYF\">[http://www.iyfnet.org/document.cfm/30/467 HM Queen Rania Al-Abdullah of Jordan Joins International Youth Foundation's Board] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430223307/http://www.iyfnet.org/document.cfm/30/467 |date=30 April 2008 }}, 22 March 2002.</ref> In September 2006, Queen Rania also joined the [[United Nations Foundation]] Board of Directors.<ref name=\"UNF\">[http://www.unfoundation.org/press-center/press-releases/2006/her-majesty-queen-rania-joins-unf-board.html HER MAJESTY QUEEN RANIA JOINS BOARD OF UNITED NATIONS FOUNDATION] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808030752/http://www.unfoundation.org/press-center/press-releases/2006/her-majesty-queen-rania-joins-unf-board.html |date=8 August 2011 }}, 13 September 2006.</ref> The UN Foundation builds and implements public-private partnerships to address the world\u2019s most pressing problems, and broadens support for the UN through advocacy and public outreach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unfoundation.org/about-unf/ |title=United Nations Foundation |publisher=Unfoundation.org |date=16 June 2010 |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616100144/http://www.unfoundation.org/about-unf/ |archivedate=16 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Microfinance====\nIn September 2003, Queen Rania accepted an invitation to join the Board of Directors of the [[Foundation for International Community Assistance]] (FINCA), thus formalizing a relationship of support and advocacy which began in 2000.<ref name=\"FINCA\">[http://www.villagebanking.org/site/c.erKPI2PCIoE/b.2394309/k.2E2B/Press_Wire.htm FINCA\u2019S FINCA International Welcomes Queen Rania Al Abdullah, First Lady of the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan, to Its Board of Directors] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109084553/http://www.villagebanking.org/site/c.erKPI2PCIoE/b.2394309/k.2E2B/Press_Wire.htm |date=9 November 2007 }}, 15 September 2003.</ref>\n\nAn emissary for the United Nations\u2019 [[International Year of Microcredit]] in 2005, Queen Rania\u2019s belief in microfinance and her partnership with FINCA<ref name=\"FINCA\" /> has generated more Jordanian micro-businesses, with the official opening of FINCA Jordan in February 2008.<ref>[http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=5963&searchFor=FINCA%20Jordan Queen highlights power of microfinance, tours FINCA Jordan microbusinesses] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010122146/http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=5963&searchFor=FINCA%20Jordan |date=10 October 2008 }}, 26 February 2008.</ref>\n\n===Online===\nQueen Rania uses online social-networking tools such as [[YouTube]], [[Facebook]], [[Instagram]] and [[Twitter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2009/05/19/an-interview-with-queen-rania-of-jordan-on-how-twitter-can-help-change-the-world/|title=An Interview With Queen Rania of Jordan On How Twitter Can Help Change The World \u2013 TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|language=en-US|access-date=14 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070610/https://techcrunch.com/2009/05/19/an-interview-with-queen-rania-of-jordan-on-how-twitter-can-help-change-the-world/|archivedate=15 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====YouTube====\nOn 30 March 2008, Queen Rania launched her own [https://www.youtube.com/queenrania YouTube channel], initially to invite viewers to give their opinions of the [[Middle East]] and talk about [[stereotypes]] they may have of Arabs and Muslims.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/tech/world/2008-03-31-queen-rania-youtube_N.htm Queen Rania Launched YouTube Channel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081104110713/http://www.usatoday.com/tech/world/2008-03-31-queen-rania-youtube_N.htm |date=4 November 2008 }}, USA Today, 31 March 2008.</ref> Between 30 March and 12 August ([[International Youth Day]]), Queen Rania posted videos on YouTube in which she asked people to send her their questions about [[Islam]] and the Arab world.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7524933.stm \"Queen Rania takes on stereotypes\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304222034/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7524933.stm |date=4 March 2016 }}, BBC, 25 July 2008.</ref> She provided responses to those questions and explained her view of the truth about various Arab and Muslim stereotypes. Over five months she posted videos on subjects that included [[honour killing]]s, terrorism and the rights of Arab women.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/worldlatest/story/0,,-7716861,00.html \"Jordan queen wraps up YouTube plan on stereotypes\"], The Guardian, 11 August 2008.</ref> International personalities such as [[Dean Obeidallah]],<ref>[http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/postglobal/vivian_salama/2008/07/queen_comedians_use_youtube_to.html \"Queen, Comedians Use YouTube To Fight Stereotypes\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054830/http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/postglobal/vivian_salama/2008/07/queen_comedians_use_youtube_to.html |date=4 March 2016 }}, The Washington Post, 31 July 2008.</ref> [[Maz Jobrani]],<ref>[http://chicago.timeout.com/articles/comedy/71413/maz-jobrani-profile \"Blowing up: Maz Jobrani pokes dangerous fun at Middle Eastern stereotypes\"] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160211120051/http://chicago.timeout.com/articles/comedy/71413/maz-jobrani-profile |date=11 February 2016 }}, Time Out, Chicago, 2008.</ref> and YouTube star [[Mia Rose]]<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dbJ9fh9hnRY Mia Rose and Hanna Gargour sing \"Waiting on the World to Change\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427024745/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dbJ9fh9hnRY |date=27 April 2016 }}, YouTube, 30 June 2008.</ref> also contributed videos to the campaign.\n\nQueen Rania also links some of her recent interviews to her YouTube channel, such as her interview with [[Wolf Blitzer]] in [[CNN]]\u2019s \u201cSituation Room\u201d, in April 2009. During this two part interview, Queen Rania discussed the importance of education.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6DAbWQcliXE Queen: Education a top priority] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408173323/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6DAbWQcliXE |date=8 April 2016 }}, YouTube, 25 April 2009.</ref> Queen Rania also uploads other videos on topics close to her heart, such as her appeal to support [[UNRWA]]\u2019s work in [[Gaza City|Gaza]] following the Israeli assault in late December 2008/early January 2009.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJTmhOzyEGw Hell on Earth] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507054044/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJTmhOzyEGw |date=7 May 2016 }}, YouTube, 16 January 2009.</ref>\n\n====Facebook====\n[[File:DE JORDANIE Rania-24x30-2005(2).jpg|thumb|upright|Queen Rania is followed by more than 10.6 million people on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/QueenRania/followers|title=Followers of Queen Rania|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=1 August 2013|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>]]\nQueen Rania is also a member of [[Facebook]], with her own fan page aimed at engaging people to discuss cross-cultural dialogue, education, and more recently, the use of [[social media]] to create [[social change]]. Along with her YouTube videos that have been uploaded, photos of her personal and public life can be found. As of 7 February 2018, more than \"16 million\" people have \"Liked\" her page.<ref>[http://facebook.com/queenrania Queen Rania's Facebook page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307044334/https://www.facebook.com/QueenRania/ |date=7 March 2016 }}. Facebook.com. Retrieved 7 February 2018.</ref>\n\n====Twitter====\nTo coincide with the visit of [[Pope Benedict XVI]] to Jordan on Friday, 8 May 2009, Queen Rania started using the micro-blogging website [[Twitter]] with the username @QueenRania.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/scienceandtechnology/technology/twitter/5298148/Queen-of-tweets-Jordans-Rania-announces-Popes-arrival-on-Twitter.html Queen of tweets: Jordan's Rania announces Pope's arrival on Twitter] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514044258/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/scienceandtechnology/technology/twitter/5298148/Queen-of-tweets-Jordans-Rania-announces-Popes-arrival-on-Twitter.html |date=14 May 2009 }}, 8 May 2009.</ref> On the occasion of the [[World Economic Forum]] held at the [[Dead Sea]] in [[Jordan]], June 2009, Queen Rania conducted her first Twitter interview, answering five questions from the general public via her Twitter account.<ref>[http://www.forumblog.org/blog/2009/05/twitter-interview-with-queen-rania-suggest-your-questions-and-vote.html Twitter interview with Queen Rania] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218080350/http://www.forumblog.org/blog/2009/05/twitter-interview-with-queen-rania-suggest-your-questions-and-vote.html |date=18 December 2011 }}, World Economic Forum, 12 May 2009.</ref>\n\nWhen she joined Twitter, she also gave an interview with [[TechCrunch]] on \u201chow Twitter can help change the world\u201d, where she said ''It\u2019s about using social media for social change: creating a community of advocates who can use their voices on behalf of the voiceless, or leverage their talents, skills, knowledge, and resources to put more children into classrooms, or pressure their elected representatives to get global education top of the agenda''.<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2009/05/19/an-interview-with-queen-rania-of-jordan-on-how-twitter-can-help-change-the-world/ An Interview with Queen Rania of Jordan on how Twitter can help change the world] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070610/https://techcrunch.com/2009/05/19/an-interview-with-queen-rania-of-jordan-on-how-twitter-can-help-change-the-world/ |date=15 March 2018 }}, TechCrunch, 19 May 2009.</ref>\n\nHer tweets have ranged from the personal, including photos of herself and her family, to more serious topics like the [[typhoon Ketsana]] in the Philippines, the [[2009 Iranian presidential election protests]], peace in the Middle East, and promoting [[Jordan]], global education, and initiatives like 1GOAL.<ref>{{cite web |author=QueenRania |url=https://twitter.com/QueenRania |title=Queen Rania's Twitter Page |publisher=Twitter.com |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608105218/http://twitter.com/QueenRania |archivedate=8 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> As of July 2017, Queen Rania has about 7 million followers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/QueenRania|title=Rania Al Abdullah (@QueenRania) - Twitter|website=twitter.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608105218/http://twitter.com/QueenRania|archivedate=8 June 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* As a tribute to King Hussein, and on the first anniversary of his death, Queen Rania produced \u201c[[The King\u2019s Gift]]\u201d, a children\u2019s book about King Hussein. Proceeds of the book go to the benefit of underprivileged children across Jordan. ({{ISBN|1854795724}}, [[Michael O'Mara Books]], 2000)<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/1854795724 The King's Gift] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105195921/http://www.amazon.com/dp/1854795724 |date=5 November 2015 }}, Queen Rania Al Abdullah, Amazon.com, 2000</ref>\n* Queen Rania's second book, entitled \u201cEternal Beauty\u201d, which she wrote in celebration of Mother\u2019s Day 2008 tells the story of a young girl\u2019s conversation with a little sheep as she searches for the most beautiful thing in the world. The book was released as part of the Greater Amman Municipality\u2019s contest \u2013 Mama\u2019s Story.<ref>[http://www.jordanembassyus.org/new/newsarchive/2009/03202009004.htm Ahead of Mother\u2019s Day, Queen Rania announces winners of \u201cMama\u2019s Story\u201d competition highlighting importance of reading]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301023127/http://www.jordanembassyus.org/new/newsarchive/2009/03202009004.htm|date=1 March 2012}}, Jordan Times, 20 March 2009</ref>\n* For the 2009 Big Read event, Queen Rania wrote \u201c[[Maha of the Mountains]]\u201d, which tells of a young girl\u2019s determination to get an education and the challenges she faced.<ref name=\"Maha\" />\n* ''[[The Sandwich Swap]]'' is a book inspired by an incident in Queen Rania\u2019s childhood. It tells the story of Lily and Salma, two best friends, who argue over the \u2018yucky\u2019 taste of their respective peanut butter and jelly and hummus sandwiches. The girls then overcome and embrace their differences. The book was co-authored by Queen Rania and Kelly DiPucchio.({{ISBN|1423124847}}, [[Hachette Books#Hyperion Books|Hyperion Books]], 20 April 2010)<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Sandwich-Queen-Rania-Jordan-Abdullah/dp/1423124847 The Sandwich Swap] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328145113/https://www.amazon.com/Sandwich-Queen-Rania-Jordan-Abdullah/dp/1423124847 |date=28 March 2017 }}, Amazon.com, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Books/Book-Reviews/2010/0427/The-Sandwich-Swap |title=The Sandwich Swap |publisher=CSMonitor.com |date=27 April 2010 |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613020010/http://www.csmonitor.com/Books/Book-Reviews/2010/0427/The-Sandwich-Swap |archivedate=13 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In May 2010 the book went to the top of the [[New York Times Bestseller List]] for children's books.<ref>{{cite news |last=Schuessler |first=Jennifer |url=https://www.nytimes.com/pages/books/bestseller/ |title=Books \u2013 Best-Seller Lists \u2013 The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523060724/http://www.nytimes.com/pages/books/bestseller/ |archivedate=23 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==International roles and positions==\n*In November 2000, the [[United Nations Children\u2019s Fund]] (UNICEF) invited Queen Rania to join its Global Leadership Initiative.<ref name=\"UNICEF GLI\" />\n*At the World Economic Forum in Davos in January 2007, Rania was named UNICEF's first Eminent Advocate for Children.<ref name=\"UNICEF EAC\" />\n*In August 2009, Queen Rania was named Co-Founder and Global Co-Chair of [[1GOAL]].<ref name=\"1GOAL\" />\n*July 2009, the United Nations made Queen Rania Honorary Chairperson for the [[United Nations Girls' Education Initiative]] (UNGEI).<ref name=\"UNGEI\" />\n*For their Global Action Week in April 2009, the Global Campaign for Education named Queen Rania their Honorary Chairperson.<ref>[http://www.campaignforeducation.org/docs/pressrelease/Media%20Alert%20-%20Queen%20Rania%20annouced%20as%20honorary%20chair%20of%20Global%20Action%20Week.pdf Queen Rania announced as Honorary Chair of Global Action Week] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303180126/http://www.campaignforeducation.org/docs/pressrelease/Media%20Alert%20-%20Queen%20Rania%20annouced%20as%20honorary%20chair%20of%20Global%20Action%20Week.pdf |date=3 March 2016 }}, Global Campaign for Education, April 2009.</ref>\n*In early 2002, Queen Rania joined the Board of Directors of the [[International Youth Foundation]], based in Baltimore, Maryland, in the United States.<ref name=\"IYF\" />\n*In September 2002, Queen Rania became a member of the World Economic Forum (WEF) Foundation Board.<ref name=\"WEF\">[https://archive.is/20130416034050/http://www.weforum.org/en/KNContributors/index.htm?personid=95350 Queen Rania, Member of the World Economic Forum Foundation Board], World Economic Forum.</ref> She is also on the Foundation Board of the Forum of Young Global Leaders (YGL) and has been the Chairperson for the Nominations and Selection Committee since July 2004, when the forum was established.<ref name=\"YGL\">[http://www.weforum.org/en/Communities/Young%20Global%20Leaders/Whoweare/YGLFoundationBoard/index.htm Foundation Board for Young Global Leaders] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208162706/http://www.weforum.org/en/Communities/Young%20Global%20Leaders/Whoweare/YGLFoundationBoard/index.htm |date=8 December 2009 }}, World Economic Forum.</ref>\n*In September 2006, Queen Rania joined the [[United Nations Foundation]] Board of Directors.<ref name=\"UNF\" />\n*Rania was a member of the [[Every Child Council]] for the GAVI Alliance.<ref>[http://everychild.gavialliance.org/Page.aspx?pid=270 Every Child Council] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718001123/http://everychild.gavialliance.org/Page.aspx?pid=270 |date=18 July 2011 }}, GAVI.</ref>\n*Rania was an Honorary Member of the International Advisory Council for the [[International Center for Research on Women]] (ICRW).<ref>[http://www.icrw.org/html/about/ICRW-Leadership-Council.html ICRW Leadership Council] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216062933/http://www.icrw.org/html/about/ICRW-Leadership-Council.html |date=16 December 2009 }}</ref>\n*Queen Rania is Co-Chair of the [[Arab Open University]].<ref>[http://www.aou.edu.jo/page.php?id=224 Arab Open University] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204202557/http://www.aou.edu.jo/page.php?id=224 |date=4 December 2009 }}, Board of Trustees.</ref>\n*She was Honorary Chairperson of the Jordanian Chapter of [[Operation Smile]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Zaharicom WebDesign |url=http://www.operationsmile.jo/aboutus/facts/ |title=Operation Smile |publisher=Operationsmile.jo |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704021207/http://www.operationsmile.jo/aboutus/facts/ |archivedate=4 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Titles, honours and awards==\n\n===Titles and styles===\n*31 August 1970 \u2013 10 June 1993: ''Miss'' Rania Al-Yassin\n*10 June 1993 \u2013 24 January 1999: ''Her Royal Highness'' Princess Rania Al-Abdullah of Jordan\n*7 February 1999 \u2013 present: ''Her Majesty'' The Queen of Jordan\n\n===National honours===\n* {{flag|Jordan}}: Knight Grand Cordon with Collar of the [[Order of al-Hussein bin Ali]] (9 June 1999) <ref name=\"RArk\">Royal Ark, [http://www.royalark.net/Jordan/jordan3.htm Jordanian genealogy details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160715090528/http://www.royalark.net/Jordan/jordan3.htm |date=15 July 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Foreign honours===\n[[File:Coat of Arms of Rania, Queen of Jordan (Order of Charles III).svg|thumb|right|180px|Queen Rania's arms as dame of the [[Order of Charles III]]]]\n* {{flag|Bahrain}} : Member 1st Class of the [[Order of al-Khalifa]] (4 November 1999)<ref name=\"RArk\" />\n* {{flag|Belgium}}: Grand Cordon of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]] (18 May 2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanitatis.elconfidencial.com/casas-reales/2016-05-18/duelo-reinas-rania-jordania-matilde-belgica_1202279/|title=Nuevo duelo de reinas: una Rania muy demod\u00e9 no puede con una Matilde sublime. Noticias de Casas Reales|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724180536/http://www.vanitatis.elconfidencial.com/casas-reales/2016-05-18/duelo-reinas-rania-jordania-matilde-belgica_1202279/|archivedate=24 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Brunei}}: Dame Grand Cross of the [[List of post-nominal letters (Brunei)|Royal Family Order of Brunei, 1st Class]] (DK, 13 May 2008)<ref name=\"RArk\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thailanguagehut.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/my-king.jpg |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-09-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720211519/http://www.thailanguagehut.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/my-king.jpg |archivedate=20 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Germany}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany|Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany, Special Class]]\n* {{flag|Italy}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] (19 October 2009)<ref name=\"RArk\" /><ref>Italian Presidency Website, [http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=306419 S.M. la Regina Rania Al Abdullah] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928084106/http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=306419 |date=28 September 2013 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Japan}}: Paulwonia Dame Grand Cordon of the [[Order of the Precious Crown]] (30 November 1999)<ref name=\"RArk\" />\n* {{flag|Netherlands}}: Dame Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Netherlands Lion]] (30 October 2006)<ref name=\"RArk\" /><ref>PPE Agency, State visit of Jordan in Netherlands 2006, [http://www.ppe-agency.com/preview.php?start=0&id=10358&zoektype=2&search=30-10-2006%20Gala Photo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006183000/http://www.ppe-agency.com/preview.php?start=0&id=10358&zoektype=2&search=30-10-2006%20Gala |date=6 October 2013 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Norway}}: Dame Grand Cross of the [[Order of St. Olav|Order of Saint Olav]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scanpix.no/spWebApp/preview/editorial/sp25382e|title=S\u00f8k - Scanpix|website=scanpix.no}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Portugal}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Prince Henry|Order of Infante Henry]]  (5.3.2008)<ref name=\"PrPort\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=154 |title=''Cidad\u00e3os Estrangeiros Agraciados com Ordens Portuguesas'' (search form) |publisher=Portuguese Presidency (presidencia.pt) |language=pt |accessdate=17 September 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65JKSX5Zm?url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=154 |archivedate=9 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Portugal}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Saint James of the Sword]]  (16 March 2009)<ref name=\"PrPort\" />\n* {{flag|Spain}}: Dame Grand Cross of the [[Order of Charles III]] (21 April 2006)<ref name=\"RArk\" /><ref name=\"BOE-A-2006-7242\">[http://www.boe.es/diario_boe/txt.php?id=BOE-A-2006-7242 Royal Decree 502/2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225232716/http://www.boe.es/diario_boe/txt.php?id=BOE-A-2006-7242 |date=25 December 2015 }}. Boletin Oficial del Estado (BOE). Reference: BOE-A-2006-7242.</ref>\n* {{flag|Spain}}: Dame Grand Cross of the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic|Royal Order of Isabella the Catholic]] (18 October 1999)<ref name=\"RArk\" /><ref>[http://boe.es/diario_boe/txt.php?id=BOE-A-1999-20603 Royal Decree 1605/1999] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20151225180553/http://boe.es/diario_boe/txt.php?id=BOE-A-1999-20603 |date=25 December 2015 }}. Boletin Oficial del Estado (BOE). Reference: BOE-A-1999-20603</ref><ref>[http://dinastias.forogratis.es/vestidos-de-gala-de-la-reina-sofia-t1663-360.html Foro Dinast\u00edas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120708151328/http://dinastias.forogratis.es/vestidos-de-gala-de-la-reina-sofia-t1663-360.html |date=8 July 2012 }}, State visit of Jordan in Spain, [http://img402.imageshack.us/img402/4656/sofiajordanos19991.jpg Sofia & Rania]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927103448/http://img402.imageshack.us/img402/4656/sofiajordanos19991.jpg |date=27 September 2013 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Sweden}}: Member Grand Cross of the [[Royal Order of the Seraphim]] (7 October 2003)<ref name=\"RArk\" /><ref>State visit of Jordan in Sweden (2003), [http://cdn.theroyalforums.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=20006&d=1065571474 Group photo] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20120820095832/http://cdn.theroyalforums.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=20006&d=1065571474 |date=20 August 2012 }} of Swedish & Jordanian sovereigns wearing reciprocal orders</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n*2001: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-honored-life-achievement-award Life Achievement Award of International Osteoporosis Foundation, Italy]  \n*2002: Ambrogino D\u2019Oro Award from the Municipality of Milan, Italy\n*2002: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/gold-medal-award-rimini Gold Medal of the President of the Italian Republic from Pio Manz International Research Center, Italy]\n*2003: German Media Award from Deutscher Medienpreis, Germany\n*2005: Golden Plate Award, [[Academy of Achievement]], USA\n*2005: Sesame Workshop Award from Sesame Workshop, USA\n*2007: Mediterranean Prize for Social Solidarity from the Mediterranean Foundation in Italy\n*2007: Global Humanitarian Action Award from UNSA-USA and the Business Council of the UN, USA\n*2007: Bambi Award for Attention Based Charity by Hubert Burda Media, Germany\n*2007: John Wallach Humanitarian Award from Seeds of Peace, USA\n*2008: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/speeches/cond%C3%A9-nast-traveler-%E2%80%9Cworld-savers-awards%E2%80%9D World Savers Award from Conde Nast Traveler, USA]\n*2008: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/news/queen-rania-honored-david-rockefeller-bridging-leadership-award-uses-platform-further-hig David Rockefeller Bridging Leadership Award from Synergos University, USA]\n*2009: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/news/queen-rania-received-prestigious-marisa-bellisario-award-italy The Marisa Bellisario International Award from the Fondazione Bellisario, Italy]\n*2009: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/while-receiving-north-south-prize-lisbon-queen-rania-highlights-importance-moderation North South Prize by the North South Prize, Portugal]\n*2009: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/news/queen-rania-jordan-receives-fifa-presidential-award-%E2%80%9Cwe-can-make-global-education-footbal FIFA Presidential Award, Switzerland]\n*2010: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-receives-arab-knight-giving-award-abu-dhabi Arab Knight of Giving Award from Arab Giving Forum, UAE]\n*2010: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-receives-leadership-award-%E2%80%9Cwomen-inspiration-and-enterprise%E2%80%9D-wie-symposium-n The Leadership Award from White Ribbon Alliance for Safe Motherhood], USA\n*2010: James C. Morgan Global Humanitarian Award from Tech Awards, USA\n*2010: Glamour\u2019s 2010 Woman of the Year, USA\n*2013: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-receives-atlantic-council-global-citizen-award-and-dedicates-it-people-jorda Atlantic Council\u2019s Global Citizen Award, USA]\n*2015: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-receives-walther-rathenau-prize-and-gives-speech-award-ceremony Walther Rathenau Award from Walther Rathenau Institut, Germany]\n*2015: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-receives-award-queen-silvia-sweden-and-speaks-ceremony World Childhood Award from Queen Silvia\u2019s World Childhood Foundation], USA\n*2016: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/media/press-releases/queen-rania-receives-andrea-bocelli-humanitarian-award-and-calls-new Andrea Bocelli Humanitarian Award, Italy]\n*2016: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/r/MjA1OTc1, Foreign Press Association\u2019s Humanitarian Award, UK]\n*2016: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/r/MjA1OTkz, The Golden Heart Award, Germany]\n*2016: Medal of Honor for Women from Sheikh Mohammad Bin Rashid, presented by his Son Sheikh Hamdan at the Global Women Forum in Dubai\n*2017: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/r/MjA2MjA0, Global Trailblazer Award, USA]\n*2017: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/r/MjA2NDYx, The Fellowship Award from Fashion for Relief in Recognition of Her Majesty\u2019s Humanitarian Efforts Towards Children Caught in Conflict, France]\n*2018: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/r/MjA3ODQ0, The Influential Personality of the Year Award, at the third annual Arab Social Media Influencers Summit (ASMIS) in Dubai]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Queen Rania of Jordan}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[https://www.facebook.com/QueenRania/?fref=ts Facebook page]\n*[http://www.madrasati.jo Madrasati]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180424201600/http://www.jei.org.jo/ Jordan Education Initiative]\n*[http://www.campaignforeducation.org Global Campaign for Education]\n*[http://www.educationforall2015.org Education for All: Class of 2015]\n*[http://www.ncfa.org.jo/ National Council for Family Affairs]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-roy}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Queen Noor of Jordan|Noor Al-Hussein]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of Jordanian consorts|Queen consort of Jordan]]\n|years=1999\u2013present}}\n{{S-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Current consorts of sovereigns}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rania Of Jordan, Queen}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American University in Cairo alumni]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. employees]]\n[[Category:Arab Open University staff]]\n[[Category:Arab queens]]\n[[Category:Citigroup employees]]\n[[Category:Jordanian internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:Jordanian royal consorts]]\n[[Category:Jordanian feminists]]\n[[Category:Jordanian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Jordanian people of Palestinian descent]]\n[[Category:UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors]]\n[[Category:Jordanian YouTubers]]\n<!-- Honours -->\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:Dames Grand Cross of the Order of Isabella the Catholic]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of the Precious Crown]]\n[[Category:Proponents of Islamic feminism]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of al-Hussein bin Ali]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses Special Class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:United Nations Foundation]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}} \n{{Infobox royalty\n| name           = Rania\n| image          = Queen Rania of Jordan Official Release 05 (cropped).jpg\n| caption        = Queen Rania during a visit in May 2018\n| consort        = yes\n| succession     = [[List of Jordanian consorts|Queen consort of Jordan]]\n| reign          = 7 February 1999\u2013present\n| coronation     = 22 March 1999\n| cor-type       = Proclamation\n| birth_name     = Rania Al-Yassin\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1970|8|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Kuwait City]], Kuwait\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| burial_date    =\n| burial_place   =\n| spouse         = {{marriage|[[Abdullah II of Jordan]]|10 June 1993}}\n| issue          = [[Hussein, Crown Prince of Jordan|Crown Prince Hussein]] <br> [[Princess Iman bint Abdullah|Princess Iman]] <br> [[Princess Salma bint Abdullah|Princess Salma]] <br> [[Prince Hashem bin Abdullah|Prince Hashem]] \n| full name      = Rania Al-Abdullah\n| house          = <!--Do not add a royal house or dynasty unless you have an official source. People are born into dynasties of ruling families. Whether or not a person is confirmed to belong to a dynasty by marriage requires a source that proves that fact. -->\n| father         = Faisal Sedki Al-Yassin\n| mother         = Ilham Yassin\n| religion       = [[Islam]]\n| signature      = Queen Rania of Jordan signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Rania Al-Abdullah''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647}}, {{transl|ar|ALA|''R\u0101niy\u0101 al-\u02bbAbd All\u0101h''}}; born '''Rania Al-Yassin''' on 31 August 1970) is the [[List of Jordanian consorts|queen consort]] of [[Jordan]]. Born in [[Kuwait]] to a Palestinian family, she later moved to Jordan for work, where she met the then prince [[Abdullah II of Jordan|Abdullah]]. Since marrying the now King of Jordan in 1993, she has become known for her advocacy work related to [[Education in Jordan|education]], health, community empowerment, youth, cross-cultural dialogue and [[micro-finance]]. She is also an avid user of social media and she maintains pages on [[Facebook]], [[YouTube]], [[Instagram]] and [[Twitter]]. She has two daughters and two sons and has been awarded various decorations by governments.\n\n==Personal life==\n===Early life===\n{{Jordanian Royal Family}}\nRania Al-Yassin was born in [[Kuwait]], to [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] parents. She received a degree in [[Business Administration]] from the [[American University in Cairo]]. Upon her graduation from the American University, she worked briefly in marketing for [[Citibank]], followed by a job with [[Apple Inc.]] in [[Amman]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile: Jordan's Queen Rania|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/1632614.stm|website=BBC|accessdate=8 January 2018|date=7 November 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107032257/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/1632614.stm|archivedate=7 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Marriage and family===\nShe met Jordanian [[Abdullah II of Jordan|Abdullah bin Al-Hussein]], who was a prince at that time, at a dinner party in August 1992. Six months later, they announced their engagement. On 10 June 1993, they were married. The couple has four children:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/royalty/2013083114363/queen-raina-jordan-43-birthday-facts/|title=Ten facts about Queen Rania of Jordan on her 43rd birthday|publisher=Hello Magazine|date=31 August 2013|accessdate=31 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924051335/http://www.hellomagazine.com/royalty/2013083114363/queen-raina-jordan-43-birthday-facts/|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n*[[Hussein, Crown Prince of Jordan|Crown Prince Hussein]] (born 28 June 1994 in [[Amman]])\n*[[Princess Iman bint Abdullah|Princess Iman]] (born 27 September 1996 in [[Amman]])\n*[[Princess Salma bint Abdullah|Princess Salma]] (born 26 September 2000 in [[Amman]])\n*[[Prince Hashem bin Abdullah|Prince Hashem]] (born 30 January 2005 in [[Amman]])\n\nHer husband ascended the throne on 7 February 1999, and proclaimed her queen on 22 March 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jordanembassyus.org/032299002.htm |title=King proclaims Rania Queen |publisher=Jordanembassyus.org |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605171654/http://www.jordanembassyus.org/032299002.htm |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-incredible-life-of-queen-rania-of-jordan-2018-1#in-february-1999-abdullah-ascended-the-throne-and-proclaimed-rania-as-queen-in-march-now-she-travels-the-world-representing-jordan-but-she-certainly-doesnt-stand-in-her-husbands-shadow-5|title=The incredible life of Jordan's Instagram-famous Queen, an ex-Apple employee, human rights activist, and global style icon|work=Business Insider|access-date=14 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315003756/http://www.businessinsider.com/the-incredible-life-of-queen-rania-of-jordan-2018-1#in-february-1999-abdullah-ascended-the-throne-and-proclaimed-rania-as-queen-in-march-now-she-travels-the-world-representing-jordan-but-she-certainly-doesnt-stand-in-her-husbands-shadow-5|archivedate=15 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Without the proclamation she would have been a princess consort, like her mother-in-law, [[Princess Muna al-Hussein]].\n\n==Areas of work==\nSince her marriage, Queen Rania has used her position to advocate for various sectors of society in Jordan and beyond.\n\n===Domestic agenda===\n\n====Education====\n[[File:Queenraniacopy8452.jpg|thumb|left|Queen Rania during a dinner celebrating the partnership between the Sesame Workshop and the [[Mosaic Foundation]] in Washington, D.C., May 2006]]\nOver the past few years, Queen Rania has launched, championed, and given patronage to several initiatives in education and learning.\n\nIn July 2005, in partnership with the Ministry of Education, the King and Queen launched an annual teachers\u2019 award, the Queen Rania Award for Excellence in Education.<ref name=\"Queen Rania Teachers Award\">[http://www.queenraniaaward.org Queen Rania Award for Excellence in Education] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123042138/http://www.queenraniaaward.org/ |date=23 January 2016 }}.</ref><ref>[http://www1.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-launches-award-honour-school-principals Queen launches award to honor school principals] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722073206/http://www1.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-launches-award-honour-school-principals |date=22 July 2011 }}, 15 April 2009.</ref>\n\nThe Queen is Chairperson of Jordan's first interactive children's museum. Opened in May 2007, it aims to encourage and nurture lifelong learning for children and their families.<ref name=\"Opening Children's Museum\">[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/king-queen-join-jordanian-children-opening-childrens-museum King, Queen join Jordanian children at opening of children's museum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/king-queen-join-jordanian-children-opening-childrens-museum |date=7 January 2016 }}, Jordan Times, 23 May 2007.</ref><ref name=\"Children's Museum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmj.jo/|title=Children's Museum of Jordan|publisher=Cmj|accessdate=20 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725161401/http://www.cmj.jo/|archivedate=25 July 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In April 2008, the Queen launched \u201cMadrasati\u201d (\u201cMy School\u201d), a public-private initiative aimed at refurbishing 500 of Jordan\u2019s public schools over a five-year period.<ref name=\"Madrasati\">{{cite web|url=http://www.madrasati.jo/site.html|title=Madrasati.jo|publisher=Madrasati|accessdate=20 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208230954/http://www.madrasati.jo/site.html|archivedate=8 February 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In higher education, the Queen Rania Scholarship Program<ref name=\"Scholarships\">{{cite web|author=Craig Mead|url=http://www.queenrania.jo/education/students/scholarships|title=Queen Rania Scholarship Program|publisher=Queen Rania|date=27 May 2010|accessdate=20 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102065404/http://www.queenrania.jo/education/students/scholarships|archivedate=2 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> partners with several universities from around the world. Queen Rania is also Chairperson<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-rania-chairs-first-meeting-royal-health-awareness-society Queen Rania chairs first meeting of Royal Health Awareness Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023520/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-rania-chairs-first-meeting-royal-health-awareness-society |date=7 January 2016 }}, 7 September 2005.</ref> of the [[Royal Health Awareness Society]] (RHAS).<ref name=\"RHAS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rhas.org.jo/ |title=Royal Health Awareness Society |publisher=RHAS |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612210717/http://www.rhas.org.jo/ |archivedate=12 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Community empowerment====\n[[File:Queen Rania - World Economic Forum on the Middle East Dead Sea Jordan 2007.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Rania - [[World Economic Forum]] on the Middle East held at the [[Dead Sea, Jordan]], in 2007]]\nQueen Rania's first venture was the establishment of the [[Jordan River Foundation]] (JRF) in 1995.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jordantimes.com/news/local/queen-rania-honours-jordan-river-foundation-supporters|title=Queen Rania honours Jordan River Foundation supporters|date=25 February 2015|work=Jordan Times|access-date=14 March 2018|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315003809/http://jordantimes.com/news/local/queen-rania-honours-jordan-river-foundation-supporters|archivedate=15 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Jordan River Children Program (JRCP) was developed by Queen Rania to place children\u2019s welfare above political agendas and cultural taboos.<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/interviews/il-messaggero-newspaper-lucia-pozzi Interview with Il Messaggero] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/interviews/il-messaggero-newspaper-lucia-pozzi |date=7 January 2016 }}, 13 May 2008.</ref> This led to the launch, in 1998, of JRF\u2019s Child Safety Program, which addresses the immediate needs of children at risk from abuse and initiated a long-term campaign to increase public awareness about violence against children. The deaths of two children in Amman as a result of child abuse in early 2009 led Queen Rania to call for an emergency meeting of government and non-government (including JRF) stakeholders to discuss where the system was failing.<ref>[http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=16383 Queen calls emergency meeting to discuss child abuse cases] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927110546/http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=16383 |date=27 September 2011 }}, Jordan Times, 24 July 2009</ref>\n\nIn 2009, to celebrate the 10th anniversary of her husband's accession to the throne, Queen Rania launched a community champion award ([[Ahel Al Himmeh]]) in March to highlight the accomplishments of groups and individuals who have helped their local communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.himmeh.jo/?q=english |title=Ahel Al Himmeh |publisher=Himmeh.jo |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616062126/http://www.himmeh.jo/?q=english |archivedate=16 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Youth====\nQueen Rania has stated that an essential aspect of education is to equip young people with the necessary skills to perform well in the workplace.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/15840232?video=1199928263 Interview: Gateway to the Middle East], 2009.</ref>\n\nShe initiated the [[Al-Aman Fund for the Future of Orphans]] in 2003,<ref>[http://www.jordanembassyus.org/01222004002.htm Orphans' future security depends on society's commitment, contributions] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314164456/http://www.jordanembassyus.org/01222004002.htm |date=14 March 2012 }}, Jordan Times, 22 January 2004.</ref> and has partnered with international universities providing scholarships for Jordanian students abroad.<ref name=\"Scholarships\"/> She supports [[INJAZ Al-Arab]], which was established by [[Save the Children]] in 1999, and later on with [[Junior Achievement]] and launched as a Jordanian non-profit organization by the Queen in 2001.<ref>[http://www.injazarabic.org INJAZ Al-Arab]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} for the creation of economic opportunity for Jordanian youth.</ref> In her capacity as Regional Ambassador of [[INJAZ Al-Arab]], she has taught classes, and engaged in dialogue with young people in other countries; she also launched [[INJAZ Al-Arab]]'s presence elsewhere in the Arab world.<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/injaz-kuwait-launch INJAZ Kuwait Launch] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/injaz-kuwait-launch |date=7 January 2016 }}, 24 November 2006.</ref> She also chaired a discussion with entrepreneurs in celebration of INJAZ Al-Arab's 10th anniversary, showcasing alumni's success stories <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-chairs-discussion-entrepreneurs-injaz-al-arab-celebrating-its-10th-anniversa |title=Queen Rania  chairs a discussion with entrepreneurs from INJAZ Al-Arab celebrating its 10th anniversary |date=January 2015 |website=Queen rania Al Abdullah |access-date=28 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528104912/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-chairs-discussion-entrepreneurs-injaz-al-arab-celebrating-its-10th-anniversa |archivedate=28 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> At the 2008 World Economic Forum in Davos, she launched the \"Empowering One Million Arab Youth by 2018\" campaign, which was conceived by INJAZ Arabia.<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/empowering-one-million-arab-youth-2018-campaign-launch Queen Rania launches campaign to prepare 1 million Arab youth for workforce] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/empowering-one-million-arab-youth-2018-campaign-launch |date=7 January 2016 }}, 24 January 2008.</ref>\n\n===Global agenda===\n\n====Global education====\n[[File:Queen Rania - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2003.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Rania at the 2003 [[World Economic Forum]] in [[Davos]], [[Switzerland]]]]\nIn November 2000, in recognition of her commitment to the cause of children and youth, the [[United Nations Children\u2019s Fund]] (UNICEF) invited Queen Rania to join its Global Leadership Initiative.<ref name=\"UNICEF GLI\">[http://www.unwire.org/unwire/20001115/11791_story.asp Queen Rania Joins UNICEF Leadership Initiative]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, U.N. Wire, 15 November 2000.</ref> The Queen worked alongside other world leaders, including former South African President Nelson Mandela, in a global movement seeking to improve the welfare of children.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120904053044/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/news/middleeast/news/article_1467254.php/Jordan_s_Queen_Rania_shares_school_bench_in_Soweto_township Jordan's Queen Rania shares school bench in Soweto township], Monsters and Critics, 27 March 2009.</ref> In January 2007, Queen Rania was named UNICEF's first Eminent Advocate for Children.<ref name=\"UNICEF EAC\">[http://www.unicef.org/media/media_38153.html Queen Rania becomes UNICEF\u2019s first Eminent Advocate for Children at the World Economic Forum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303165255/http://www.unicef.org/media/media_38153.html |date=3 March 2016 }}, UNICEF, Press Centre, 26 January 2007.</ref> In August 2009, Queen Rania became Honorary Global Chair of the [[United Nations Girls' Education Initiative]] (UNGEI).<ref name=\"UNGEI\">[http://www.ungei.org/news/index_2181.html Queen Rania designated as Honorary Global Chair of the United Nations Girls\u2019 Education Initiative (UNGEI)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303175515/http://www.ungei.org/news/index_2181.html |date=3 March 2016 }}, UNGEI, 15 July 2009.</ref>\n\nAs a longtime supporter of the Global Campaign for Education (GCE),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.campaignforeducation.org/ |title=Global Campaign for Education |publisher=Campaignforeducation.org |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706205314/http://www.campaignforeducation.org/ |archivedate=6 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Queen Rania met with children and inspirational women in South Africa, both in the cities of Johannesburg and Soweto, in March 2009.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rania-al-abdullah/a-promising-glimpse-of-af_b_180040.html A Promising Glimpse of Africa's Future Can Be Found in Its Children] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131172058/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rania-al-abdullah/a-promising-glimpse-of-af_b_180040.html |date=31 January 2016 }}, Huffington Post, 27 March 2009.</ref> Queen Rania and the women took turns reading a short story out of The Big Read to the children, in an effort to encourage literacy. One of the stories in the book, \u201cMaha of the Mountains\u201d, was contributed by Queen Rania.<ref name=\"Maha\">[http://www.campaignforeducation.org/bigread/stories/queen-rania/index/index.html Maha of the Mountains] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172430/http://www.campaignforeducation.org/bigread/stories/queen-rania/index/index.html |date=3 March 2016 }}, The Big Read, The Global Campaign for Education, 2009.</ref>\nIn Soweto, she was the first to write her name in the back of the Big Read, before passing it on to everyone else to write their name.<ref>[http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/southafrica_48980.html Youth leaders in Soweto greet Queen Rania of Jordan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/southafrica_48980.html |date=7 January 2016 }}, UNICEF, 30 March 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.campaignforeducation.org/docs/pressrelease/Media%20Alert%20-%20Queen%20Rania%20annouced%20as%20honorary%20chair%20of%20Global%20Action%20Week.pdf Queen Rania of Jordan, reads her story to children and announces her role as Honorary Chair of Action Week] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303180126/http://www.campaignforeducation.org/docs/pressrelease/Media%20Alert%20-%20Queen%20Rania%20annouced%20as%20honorary%20chair%20of%20Global%20Action%20Week.pdf |date=3 March 2016 }}, Global Campaign for Education, 27 March 2009.</ref>\n\n[[File:Michelle Obama & Queen Rania of Jordan in the Yellow Oval Room 4-23-09.JPG|left|thumb|First Lady [[Michelle Obama]] hosts Queen Rania in the [[Yellow Oval Room]], April 2009]]\nDuring her April 2009 US trip, Queen Rania joined leading education advocates Congresswoman [[Nita Lowey]] and Counsellor to the Secretary of the Treasury [[Gene Sperling]] to launch \"The Big Read\" as part of Global Campaign for Education's global action week calling for quality basic education for all children.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/21/jordans-queen-rania-congr_n_189690.html Jordan's Queen Rania, Congresswoman Nita Lowey Launch 'The Big Read' Global Education Campaign] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221227/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/21/jordans-queen-rania-congr_n_189690.html |date=3 March 2016 }}, Huffington Post, 21 April 2009.</ref> She was also hosted by first lady of the United States, [[Michelle Obama]], during that same trip.<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/09/04/23/The-First-Lady-and-Queen-Rania/ The First Lady and Queen Rania] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150310041140/http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/09/04/23/The-First-Lady-and-Queen-Rania/ |date=10 March 2015 }}, White House Blog, 23 April 2009.</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2009, Queen Rania co-founded and led the launch of the \"[[1GOAL Education for All|1GOAL: Education for All]]\" campaign alongside [[Gary Lineker]], and with the help of top international footballers at [[Wembley Stadium]], [[London]].<ref name=\"1GOAL\">[http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=19393&searchFor=1GOAL Queen lends support to 1GOAL initiative] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927110552/http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=19393&searchFor=1GOAL |date=27 September 2011 }}, Jordan Times, 21 August 2009.</ref> Queen Rania is co-founder and global co-chair of the 1GOAL campaign to rally World Cup 2010 fans together during the world\u2019s biggest single sporting event and call on world leaders to give 75 million children out of school an education.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.join1goal.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=53&lang=en |title=1GOAL: Education for All |publisher=Join1goal.org |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090827230353/http://www.join1goal.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=53&lang=en |archivedate=27 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 6 October 2009, Queen Rania was joined by Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] of the UK, the President of [[FIFA]], [[Sepp Blatter]], President [[Jacob Zuma]] of South Africa, and other heads of state, for the Global Launch of 1GOAL, which took place across six locations worldwide.<ref name=\"1GOAL Global Launch\">[http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=20517 Queen joins world leaders in launching 1GOAL campaign] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927110557/http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=20517 |date=27 September 2011 }}, Jordan Times, 7 October 2009.</ref> Queen Rania spoke of the need to turn this \u201ctragedy into triumph\u201d and called on political leaders to stand by their aid commitments.<ref name=\"1GOAL Global Launch\"/>\n\nIn 2008, Queen Rania participated in YouTube's In My Name<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/inmyname In My Name] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915030324/https://www.youtube.com/user/inmyname |date=15 September 2016 }}, YouTube Channel.</ref> campaign. She appeared alongside [[The Black Eyed Peas]] member [[will.i.am]] in the video, \"End Poverty \u2013 Be the Generation,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pRyMxSS-KI0 |title=End Poverty \u2013 Be the Generation |publisher=Youtube.com |date=22 September 2008 |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101101012538/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pRyMxSS-KI0 |archivedate=1 November 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which urged world leaders to keep the promises they made in 2000 at the [[United Nations]] [[Millennium Summit]].<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-flumenbaum/celebrities-join-youtube_b_129649.html \"Celebrities Join YouTube at UN to Launch Poverty Campaign\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160212051319/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-flumenbaum/celebrities-join-youtube_b_129649.html |date=12 February 2016 }}, Huffington Post, 26 September 2008.</ref>\n\n====Cross-cultural dialogue====\n[[File:Queen Rania Al Abdullah of Jordan and UK minister Sajid Javid (24182367514).jpg|thumb|right|Queen Rania and [[Sajid Javid]] at ''Supporting Syria and the Region conference'', 2016.]]\nQueen Rania has also been particularly vocal about the importance of cross cultural and interfaith dialogue to foster greater understanding, tolerance and acceptance across the world.<ref>[http://www.jordanembassyus.org/09192005001.htm Queen underscores need to promote cross-cultural dialogue]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301023123/http://www.jordanembassyus.org/09192005001.htm|date=1 March 2012}}, Jordan Times, 19 September 2005.</ref> She has used her status to correct what she sees as misconceptions in [[Western world|the West]] about the [[Arab world]]. Forbes magazine ranked her as one of the world's 100 most powerful women in 2011.<ref name=\"forbes-100\">[https://www.forbes.com/wealth/power-women/list The 100 Most Powerful Women] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101008201657/http://www.forbes.com/wealth/power-women/list |date=8 October 2010 }}, [[Forbes Magazine]], 2011.</ref>\n\nQueen Rania has played a significant role in reaching out to the global community to foster values of tolerance and acceptance, and increase cross-cultural dialogue. For example, regionally and internationally, Queen Rania has campaigned for a greater understanding between cultures in such high-profile forums as the [[Jeddah Economic Forum]],<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-rania-addresses-jeddah-economic-forum-urges-global-community-plant-seeds-accept Queen Rania addresses Jeddah Economic Forum, urges global community to plant seeds of acceptance, dialogue, peace] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/queen-rania-addresses-jeddah-economic-forum-urges-global-community-plant-seeds-accept |date=7 January 2016 }}, 25 February 2007.</ref> the [[Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]],<ref name=\"Harvard\">[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/speeches/john-f-kennedy-school-government-harvard-university Keynote Address] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/speeches/john-f-kennedy-school-government-harvard-university |date=7 January 2016 }}, Harvard University, 3 May 2007.</ref> and the [[Skoll Foundation]]<ref>[http://www.queenrania.jo/media/speeches/her-majesty-queen-rania-al-abdullah-remarks-skoll-world-forum-2007 Queen Rania Al Abdullah Remarks at Skoll World Forum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107023519/http://www.queenrania.jo/media/speeches/her-majesty-queen-rania-al-abdullah-remarks-skoll-world-forum-2007 |date=7 January 2016 }}, 27 March 2007.</ref> in the UK.\n\nQueen Rania has also used [[YouTube]] as a way to promote intercultural dialogue by calling on young people around the world to engage in a global dialogue to dismantle stereotypes of Muslims and the Arab world.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TFf897bUW2Y YOUTUBE EXCLUSIVE: Send me your stereotypes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215045604/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TFf897bUW2Y |date=15 December 2016 }}, Queen Rania Channel, YouTube, 30 March 2008.</ref> She has also made public appearances, including a half-hour television interview on [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]] on 17 May 2006, where she spoke about misconceptions about Islam and especially [[women in Islam]].<ref>[http://www.oprah.com/dated/oprahshow/oprahshow_20060517 Meet the World's Youngest Queen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609012143/http://www.oprah.com/dated/oprahshow/oprahshow_20060517 |date=9 June 2009 }}, Oprah.com, 17 May 2006.</ref><ref>[http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=4057220760334335567&ei=lHAJSujEHobw2gKSi5jABg&q=queen+rania&hl=en Queen Rania on Oprah Winfrey] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629070712/http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=4057220760334335567&ei=lHAJSujEHobw2gKSi5jABg&q=queen+rania&hl=en |date=29 June 2011 }}, Part 1, 17 May 2006.</ref><ref>[http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=7397412902320079243&ei=lHAJSujEHobw2gKSi5jABg&q=queen+rania&hl=en Queen Rania on Oprah Winfrey] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629070657/http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=7397412902320079243&ei=lHAJSujEHobw2gKSi5jABg&q=queen+rania&hl=en |date=29 June 2011 }}, Part 2, 17 May 2006.</ref> For her work in reaching out across cultures she received the [[North-South Prize]] from the [[Council of Europe]] in March 2009<ref>[http://www.coe.int/t/dc/files/events/2008_prix_ns/default_en.asp? North South Prize Acceptance Speech]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522123625/http://www.coe.int/t/dc/files/events/2008_prix_ns/default_en.asp |date=22 May 2011 }}, 16 March 2009.</ref> and the first ever [[YouTube Visionary Award]] in November 2008.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-Z-aQAEA7U8 Queen Rania Accepts YouTube Visionary Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407215356/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-Z-aQAEA7U8 |date=7 April 2016 }}, 22 November 2008.</ref> For her work in cross-cultural peace dialogue Queen Rania accepted the PeaceMaker Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Seeds+of+Peace,+to+Present+Peacemaker+Award+to+Her+Majesty+Queen...-a0162850144 |title=Seeds of Peace, to Present Peacemaker Award to Her Majesty Queen Rania Al-Abdullah of Jordan. \u2013 Free Online Library |publisher=Thefreelibrary.com |date=2 May 2007 |accessdate=20 June 2010}}</ref> from the Non-Profit [[Seeds of Peace]].\n\nIn May 2009, Queen Rania attended the fifth Young Global Leaders Summit at the Dead Sea, Jordan, to address socio-economic challenges facing the region and had trips organized for the Young Global Leaders in which they visited local Madrasati schools, the Jordan River Foundation, and other affiliated organizations.<ref>[http://www.forumblog.org/blog/2009/05/focus-on-leadership-as-queen-rania-opens-ygl-dead-sea-summit.html Focus on leadership as Queen Rania opens YGL Dead Sea Summit] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218080232/http://www.forumblog.org/blog/2009/05/focus-on-leadership-as-queen-rania-opens-ygl-dead-sea-summit.html |date=18 December 2011 }}, 13 May 2009.</ref>\n\nWhen it comes to youth, in early 2002 Queen Rania joined the Board of Directors of the International Youth Foundation, based in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], in the United States.<ref name=\"IYF\">[http://www.iyfnet.org/document.cfm/30/467 HM Queen Rania Al-Abdullah of Jordan Joins International Youth Foundation's Board] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430223307/http://www.iyfnet.org/document.cfm/30/467 |date=30 April 2008 }}, 22 March 2002.</ref> In September 2006, Queen Rania also joined the [[United Nations Foundation]] Board of Directors.<ref name=\"UNF\">[http://www.unfoundation.org/press-center/press-releases/2006/her-majesty-queen-rania-joins-unf-board.html HER MAJESTY QUEEN RANIA JOINS BOARD OF UNITED NATIONS FOUNDATION] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808030752/http://www.unfoundation.org/press-center/press-releases/2006/her-majesty-queen-rania-joins-unf-board.html |date=8 August 2011 }}, 13 September 2006.</ref> The UN Foundation builds and implements public-private partnerships to address the world\u2019s most pressing problems, and broadens support for the UN through advocacy and public outreach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unfoundation.org/about-unf/ |title=United Nations Foundation |publisher=Unfoundation.org |date=16 June 2010 |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616100144/http://www.unfoundation.org/about-unf/ |archivedate=16 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Microfinance====\nIn September 2003, Queen Rania accepted an invitation to join the Board of Directors of the [[Foundation for International Community Assistance]] (FINCA), thus formalizing a relationship of support and advocacy which began in 2000.<ref name=\"FINCA\">[http://www.villagebanking.org/site/c.erKPI2PCIoE/b.2394309/k.2E2B/Press_Wire.htm FINCA\u2019S FINCA International Welcomes Queen Rania Al Abdullah, First Lady of the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan, to Its Board of Directors] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109084553/http://www.villagebanking.org/site/c.erKPI2PCIoE/b.2394309/k.2E2B/Press_Wire.htm |date=9 November 2007 }}, 15 September 2003.</ref>\n\nAn emissary for the United Nations\u2019 [[International Year of Microcredit]] in 2005, Queen Rania\u2019s belief in microfinance and her partnership with FINCA<ref name=\"FINCA\" /> has generated more Jordanian micro-businesses, with the official opening of FINCA Jordan in February 2008.<ref>[http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=5963&searchFor=FINCA%20Jordan Queen highlights power of microfinance, tours FINCA Jordan microbusinesses] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010122146/http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=5963&searchFor=FINCA%20Jordan |date=10 October 2008 }}, 26 February 2008.</ref>\n\n===Online===\nQueen Rania uses online social-networking tools such as [[YouTube]], [[Facebook]], [[Instagram]] and [[Twitter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2009/05/19/an-interview-with-queen-rania-of-jordan-on-how-twitter-can-help-change-the-world/|title=An Interview With Queen Rania of Jordan On How Twitter Can Help Change The World \u2013 TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|language=en-US|access-date=14 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070610/https://techcrunch.com/2009/05/19/an-interview-with-queen-rania-of-jordan-on-how-twitter-can-help-change-the-world/|archivedate=15 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====YouTube====\nOn 30 March 2008, Queen Rania launched her own [https://www.youtube.com/queenrania YouTube channel], initially to invite viewers to give their opinions of the [[Middle East]] and talk about [[stereotypes]] they may have of Arabs and Muslims.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/tech/world/2008-03-31-queen-rania-youtube_N.htm Queen Rania Launched YouTube Channel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081104110713/http://www.usatoday.com/tech/world/2008-03-31-queen-rania-youtube_N.htm |date=4 November 2008 }}, USA Today, 31 March 2008.</ref> Between 30 March and 12 August ([[International Youth Day]]), Queen Rania posted videos on YouTube in which she asked people to send her their questions about [[Islam]] and the Arab world.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7524933.stm \"Queen Rania takes on stereotypes\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304222034/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7524933.stm |date=4 March 2016 }}, BBC, 25 July 2008.</ref> She provided responses to those questions and explained her view of the truth about various Arab and Muslim stereotypes. Over five months she posted videos on subjects that included [[honour killing]]s, terrorism and the rights of Arab women.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/worldlatest/story/0,,-7716861,00.html \"Jordan queen wraps up YouTube plan on stereotypes\"], The Guardian, 11 August 2008.</ref> International personalities such as [[Dean Obeidallah]],<ref>[http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/postglobal/vivian_salama/2008/07/queen_comedians_use_youtube_to.html \"Queen, Comedians Use YouTube To Fight Stereotypes\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054830/http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/postglobal/vivian_salama/2008/07/queen_comedians_use_youtube_to.html |date=4 March 2016 }}, The Washington Post, 31 July 2008.</ref> [[Maz Jobrani]],<ref>[http://chicago.timeout.com/articles/comedy/71413/maz-jobrani-profile \"Blowing up: Maz Jobrani pokes dangerous fun at Middle Eastern stereotypes\"] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160211120051/http://chicago.timeout.com/articles/comedy/71413/maz-jobrani-profile |date=11 February 2016 }}, Time Out, Chicago, 2008.</ref> and YouTube star [[Mia Rose]]<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dbJ9fh9hnRY Mia Rose and Hanna Gargour sing \"Waiting on the World to Change\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427024745/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dbJ9fh9hnRY |date=27 April 2016 }}, YouTube, 30 June 2008.</ref> also contributed videos to the campaign.\n\nQueen Rania also links some of her recent interviews to her YouTube channel, such as her interview with [[Wolf Blitzer]] in [[CNN]]\u2019s \u201cSituation Room\u201d, in April 2009. During this two part interview, Queen Rania discussed the importance of education.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6DAbWQcliXE Queen: Education a top priority] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408173323/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6DAbWQcliXE |date=8 April 2016 }}, YouTube, 25 April 2009.</ref> Queen Rania also uploads other videos on topics close to her heart, such as her appeal to support [[UNRWA]]\u2019s work in [[Gaza City|Gaza]] following the Israeli assault in late December 2008/early January 2009.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJTmhOzyEGw Hell on Earth] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507054044/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJTmhOzyEGw |date=7 May 2016 }}, YouTube, 16 January 2009.</ref>\n\n====Facebook====\n[[File:DE JORDANIE Rania-24x30-2005(2).jpg|thumb|upright|Queen Rania is followed by more than 10.6 million people on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/QueenRania/followers|title=Followers of Queen Rania|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=1 August 2013|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>]]\nQueen Rania is also a member of [[Facebook]], with her own fan page aimed at engaging people to discuss cross-cultural dialogue, education, and more recently, the use of [[social media]] to create [[social change]]. Along with her YouTube videos that have been uploaded, photos of her personal and public life can be found. As of 7 February 2018, more than \"16 million\" people have \"Liked\" her page.<ref>[http://facebook.com/queenrania Queen Rania's Facebook page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307044334/https://www.facebook.com/QueenRania/ |date=7 March 2016 }}. Facebook.com. Retrieved 7 February 2018.</ref>\n\n====Twitter====\nTo coincide with the visit of [[Pope Benedict XVI]] to Jordan on Friday, 8 May 2009, Queen Rania started using the micro-blogging website [[Twitter]] with the username @QueenRania.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/scienceandtechnology/technology/twitter/5298148/Queen-of-tweets-Jordans-Rania-announces-Popes-arrival-on-Twitter.html Queen of tweets: Jordan's Rania announces Pope's arrival on Twitter] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514044258/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/scienceandtechnology/technology/twitter/5298148/Queen-of-tweets-Jordans-Rania-announces-Popes-arrival-on-Twitter.html |date=14 May 2009 }}, 8 May 2009.</ref> On the occasion of the [[World Economic Forum]] held at the [[Dead Sea]] in [[Jordan]], June 2009, Queen Rania conducted her first Twitter interview, answering five questions from the general public via her Twitter account.<ref>[http://www.forumblog.org/blog/2009/05/twitter-interview-with-queen-rania-suggest-your-questions-and-vote.html Twitter interview with Queen Rania] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218080350/http://www.forumblog.org/blog/2009/05/twitter-interview-with-queen-rania-suggest-your-questions-and-vote.html |date=18 December 2011 }}, World Economic Forum, 12 May 2009.</ref>\n\nWhen she joined Twitter, she also gave an interview with [[TechCrunch]] on \u201chow Twitter can help change the world\u201d, where she said ''It\u2019s about using social media for social change: creating a community of advocates who can use their voices on behalf of the voiceless, or leverage their talents, skills, knowledge, and resources to put more children into classrooms, or pressure their elected representatives to get global education top of the agenda''.<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2009/05/19/an-interview-with-queen-rania-of-jordan-on-how-twitter-can-help-change-the-world/ An Interview with Queen Rania of Jordan on how Twitter can help change the world] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070610/https://techcrunch.com/2009/05/19/an-interview-with-queen-rania-of-jordan-on-how-twitter-can-help-change-the-world/ |date=15 March 2018 }}, TechCrunch, 19 May 2009.</ref>\n\nHer tweets have ranged from the personal, including photos of herself and her family, to more serious topics like the [[typhoon Ketsana]] in the Philippines, the [[2009 Iranian presidential election protests]], peace in the Middle East, and promoting [[Jordan]], global education, and initiatives like 1GOAL.<ref>{{cite web |author=QueenRania |url=https://twitter.com/QueenRania |title=Queen Rania's Twitter Page |publisher=Twitter.com |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608105218/http://twitter.com/QueenRania |archivedate=8 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> As of July 2017, Queen Rania has about 7 million followers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/QueenRania|title=Rania Al Abdullah (@QueenRania) - Twitter|website=twitter.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608105218/http://twitter.com/QueenRania|archivedate=8 June 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* As a tribute to King Hussein, and on the first anniversary of his death, Queen Rania produced \u201c[[The King\u2019s Gift]]\u201d, a children\u2019s book about King Hussein. Proceeds of the book go to the benefit of underprivileged children across Jordan. ({{ISBN|1854795724}}, [[Michael O'Mara Books]], 2000)<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/1854795724 The King's Gift] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105195921/http://www.amazon.com/dp/1854795724 |date=5 November 2015 }}, Queen Rania Al Abdullah, Amazon.com, 2000</ref>\n* Queen Rania's second book, entitled \u201cEternal Beauty\u201d, which she wrote in celebration of Mother\u2019s Day 2008 tells the story of a young girl\u2019s conversation with a little sheep as she searches for the most beautiful thing in the world. The book was released as part of the Greater Amman Municipality\u2019s contest \u2013 Mama\u2019s Story.<ref>[http://www.jordanembassyus.org/new/newsarchive/2009/03202009004.htm Ahead of Mother\u2019s Day, Queen Rania announces winners of \u201cMama\u2019s Story\u201d competition highlighting importance of reading]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301023127/http://www.jordanembassyus.org/new/newsarchive/2009/03202009004.htm|date=1 March 2012}}, Jordan Times, 20 March 2009</ref>\n* For the 2009 Big Read event, Queen Rania wrote \u201c[[Maha of the Mountains]]\u201d, which tells of a young girl\u2019s determination to get an education and the challenges she faced.<ref name=\"Maha\" />\n* ''[[The Sandwich Swap]]'' is a book inspired by an incident in Queen Rania\u2019s childhood. It tells the story of Lily and Salma, two best friends, who argue over the \u2018yucky\u2019 taste of their respective peanut butter and jelly and hummus sandwiches. The girls then overcome and embrace their differences. The book was co-authored by Queen Rania and Kelly DiPucchio.({{ISBN|1423124847}}, [[Hyperion Books]], 20 April 2010)<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Sandwich-Queen-Rania-Jordan-Abdullah/dp/1423124847 The Sandwich Swap] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328145113/https://www.amazon.com/Sandwich-Queen-Rania-Jordan-Abdullah/dp/1423124847 |date=28 March 2017 }}, Amazon.com, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Books/Book-Reviews/2010/0427/The-Sandwich-Swap |title=The Sandwich Swap |publisher=CSMonitor.com |date=27 April 2010 |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613020010/http://www.csmonitor.com/Books/Book-Reviews/2010/0427/The-Sandwich-Swap |archivedate=13 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In May 2010 the book went to the top of the [[New York Times Bestseller List]] for children's books.<ref>{{cite news |last=Schuessler |first=Jennifer |url=https://www.nytimes.com/pages/books/bestseller/ |title=Books \u2013 Best-Seller Lists \u2013 The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523060724/http://www.nytimes.com/pages/books/bestseller/ |archivedate=23 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==International roles and positions==\n*In November 2000, the [[United Nations Children\u2019s Fund]] (UNICEF) invited Queen Rania to join its Global Leadership Initiative.<ref name=\"UNICEF GLI\" />\n*At the World Economic Forum in Davos in January 2007, Rania was named UNICEF's first Eminent Advocate for Children.<ref name=\"UNICEF EAC\" />\n*In August 2009, Queen Rania was named Co-Founder and Global Co-Chair of [[1GOAL]].<ref name=\"1GOAL\" />\n*July 2009, the United Nations made Queen Rania Honorary Chairperson for the [[United Nations Girls' Education Initiative]] (UNGEI).<ref name=\"UNGEI\" />\n*For their Global Action Week in April 2009, the Global Campaign for Education named Queen Rania their Honorary Chairperson.<ref>[http://www.campaignforeducation.org/docs/pressrelease/Media%20Alert%20-%20Queen%20Rania%20annouced%20as%20honorary%20chair%20of%20Global%20Action%20Week.pdf Queen Rania announced as Honorary Chair of Global Action Week] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303180126/http://www.campaignforeducation.org/docs/pressrelease/Media%20Alert%20-%20Queen%20Rania%20annouced%20as%20honorary%20chair%20of%20Global%20Action%20Week.pdf |date=3 March 2016 }}, Global Campaign for Education, April 2009.</ref>\n*In early 2002, Queen Rania joined the Board of Directors of the [[International Youth Foundation]], based in Baltimore, Maryland, in the United States.<ref name=\"IYF\" />\n*In September 2002, Queen Rania became a member of the World Economic Forum (WEF) Foundation Board.<ref name=\"WEF\">[https://archive.is/20130416034050/http://www.weforum.org/en/KNContributors/index.htm?personid=95350 Queen Rania, Member of the World Economic Forum Foundation Board], World Economic Forum.</ref> She is also on the Foundation Board of the Forum of Young Global Leaders (YGL) and has been the Chairperson for the Nominations and Selection Committee since July 2004, when the forum was established.<ref name=\"YGL\">[http://www.weforum.org/en/Communities/Young%20Global%20Leaders/Whoweare/YGLFoundationBoard/index.htm Foundation Board for Young Global Leaders] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208162706/http://www.weforum.org/en/Communities/Young%20Global%20Leaders/Whoweare/YGLFoundationBoard/index.htm |date=8 December 2009 }}, World Economic Forum.</ref>\n*In September 2006, Queen Rania joined the [[United Nations Foundation]] Board of Directors.<ref name=\"UNF\" />\n*Rania was a member of the [[Every Child Council]] for the GAVI Alliance.<ref>[http://everychild.gavialliance.org/Page.aspx?pid=270 Every Child Council] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718001123/http://everychild.gavialliance.org/Page.aspx?pid=270 |date=18 July 2011 }}, GAVI.</ref>\n*Rania was an Honorary Member of the International Advisory Council for the [[International Center for Research on Women]] (ICRW).<ref>[http://www.icrw.org/html/about/ICRW-Leadership-Council.html ICRW Leadership Council] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216062933/http://www.icrw.org/html/about/ICRW-Leadership-Council.html |date=16 December 2009 }}</ref>\n*Queen Rania is Co-Chair of the [[Arab Open University]].<ref>[http://www.aou.edu.jo/page.php?id=224 Arab Open University] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204202557/http://www.aou.edu.jo/page.php?id=224 |date=4 December 2009 }}, Board of Trustees.</ref>\n*She was Honorary Chairperson of the Jordanian Chapter of [[Operation Smile]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Zaharicom WebDesign |url=http://www.operationsmile.jo/aboutus/facts/ |title=Operation Smile |publisher=Operationsmile.jo |accessdate=20 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704021207/http://www.operationsmile.jo/aboutus/facts/ |archivedate=4 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Titles, honours and awards==\n\n===Titles and styles===\n*31 August 1970 \u2013 10 June 1993: ''Miss'' Rania Al-Yassin\n*10 June 1993 \u2013 24 January 1999: ''Her Royal Highness'' Princess Rania Al-Abdullah of Jordan\n*7 February 1999 \u2013 present: ''Her Majesty'' The Queen of Jordan\n\n===National honours===\n* {{flag|Jordan}}: Knight Grand Cordon with Collar of the [[Order of al-Hussein bin Ali]] (9 June 1999) <ref name=\"RArk\">Royal Ark, [http://www.royalark.net/Jordan/jordan3.htm Jordanian genealogy details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160715090528/http://www.royalark.net/Jordan/jordan3.htm |date=15 July 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Foreign honours===\n[[File:Coat of Arms of Rania, Queen of Jordan (Order of Charles III).svg|thumb|right|180px|Queen Rania's arms as dame of the [[Order of Charles III]]]]\n* {{flag|Bahrain}} : Member 1st Class of the [[Order of al-Khalifa]] (4 November 1999)<ref name=\"RArk\" />\n* {{flag|Belgium}}: Grand Cordon of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]] (18 May 2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanitatis.elconfidencial.com/casas-reales/2016-05-18/duelo-reinas-rania-jordania-matilde-belgica_1202279/|title=Nuevo duelo de reinas: una Rania muy demod\u00e9 no puede con una Matilde sublime. Noticias de Casas Reales|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724180536/http://www.vanitatis.elconfidencial.com/casas-reales/2016-05-18/duelo-reinas-rania-jordania-matilde-belgica_1202279/|archivedate=24 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Brunei}}: Dame Grand Cross of the [[List of post-nominal letters (Brunei)|Royal Family Order of Brunei, 1st Class]] (DK, 13 May 2008)<ref name=\"RArk\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thailanguagehut.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/my-king.jpg |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-09-06 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720211519/http://www.thailanguagehut.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/my-king.jpg |archivedate=20 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Germany}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany|Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany, Special Class]]\n* {{flag|Italy}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] (19 October 2009)<ref name=\"RArk\" /><ref>Italian Presidency Website, [http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=306419 S.M. la Regina Rania Al Abdullah] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928084106/http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=306419 |date=28 September 2013 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Japan}}: Paulwonia Dame Grand Cordon of the [[Order of the Precious Crown]] (30 November 1999)<ref name=\"RArk\" />\n* {{flag|Netherlands}}: Dame Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Netherlands Lion]] (30 October 2006)<ref name=\"RArk\" /><ref>PPE Agency, State visit of Jordan in Netherlands 2006, [http://www.ppe-agency.com/preview.php?start=0&id=10358&zoektype=2&search=30-10-2006%20Gala Photo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006183000/http://www.ppe-agency.com/preview.php?start=0&id=10358&zoektype=2&search=30-10-2006%20Gala |date=6 October 2013 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Norway}}: Dame Grand Cross of the [[Order of St. Olav|Order of Saint Olav]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scanpix.no/spWebApp/preview/editorial/sp25382e|title=S\u00f8k - Scanpix|website=scanpix.no}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Portugal}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Prince Henry|Order of Infante Henry]]  (5.3.2008)<ref name=\"PrPort\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=154 |title=''Cidad\u00e3os Estrangeiros Agraciados com Ordens Portuguesas'' (search form) |publisher=Portuguese Presidency (presidencia.pt) |language=pt |accessdate=17 September 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65JKSX5Zm?url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=154 |archivedate=9 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Portugal}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of Saint James of the Sword]]  (16 March 2009)<ref name=\"PrPort\" />\n* {{flag|Spain}}: Dame Grand Cross of the [[Order of Charles III]] (21 April 2006)<ref name=\"RArk\" /><ref name=\"