ard from the Municipality of Milan, Italy\n*2002: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/gold-medal-award-rimini Gold Medal of the President of the Italian Republic from Pio Manz International Research Center, Italy]\n*2003: German Media Award from Deutscher Medienpreis, Germany\n*2005: Golden Plate Award, [[Academy of Achievement]], USA\n*2005: Sesame Workshop Award from Sesame Workshop, USA\n*2007: Mediterranean Prize for Social Solidarity from the Mediterranean Foundation in Italy\n*2007: Global Humanitarian Action Award from UNSA-USA and the Business Council of the UN, USA\n*2007: Bambi Award for Attention Based Charity by Hubert Burda Media, Germany\n*2007: John Wallach Humanitarian Award from Seeds of Peace, USA\n*2008: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/speeches/cond%C3%A9-nast-traveler-%E2%80%9Cworld-savers-awards%E2%80%9D World Savers Award from Conde Nast Traveler, USA]\n*2008: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/news/queen-rania-honored-david-rockefeller-bridging-leadership-award-uses-platform-further-hig David Rockefeller Bridging Leadership Award from Synergos University, USA]\n*2009: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/news/queen-rania-received-prestigious-marisa-bellisario-award-italy The Marisa Bellisario International Award from the Fondazione Bellisario, Italy]\n*2009: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/articles/while-receiving-north-south-prize-lisbon-queen-rania-highlights-importance-moderation North South Prize by the North South Prize, Portugal]\n*2009: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/news/queen-rania-jordan-receives-fifa-presidential-award-%E2%80%9Cwe-can-make-global-education-footbal FIFA Presidential Award, Switzerland]\n*2010: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-receives-arab-knight-giving-award-abu-dhabi Arab Knight of Giving Award from Arab Giving Forum, UAE]\n*2010: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-receives-leadership-award-%E2%80%9Cwomen-inspiration-and-enterprise%E2%80%9D-wie-symposium-n The Leadership Award from White Ribbon Alliance for Safe Motherhood], USA\n*2010: James C. Morgan Global Humanitarian Award from Tech Awards, USA\n*2010: Glamour\u2019s 2010 Woman of the Year, USA\n*2013: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-receives-atlantic-council-global-citizen-award-and-dedicates-it-people-jorda Atlantic Council\u2019s Global Citizen Award, USA]\n*2015: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-receives-walther-rathenau-prize-and-gives-speech-award-ceremony Walther Rathenau Award from Walther Rathenau Institut, Germany]\n*2015: [http://www.queenrania.jo/media/press/queen-rania-receives-award-queen-silvia-sweden-and-speaks-ceremony World Childhood Award from Queen Silvia\u2019s World Childhood Foundation], USA\n*2016: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/media/press-releases/queen-rania-receives-andrea-bocelli-humanitarian-award-and-calls-new Andrea Bocelli Humanitarian Award, Italy]\n*2016: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/r/MjA1OTc1, Foreign Press Association\u2019s Humanitarian Award, UK]\n*2016: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/r/MjA1OTkz, The Golden Heart Award, Germany]\n*2016: Medal of Honor for Women from Sheikh Mohammad Bin Rashid, presented by his Son Sheikh Hamdan at the Global Women Forum in Dubai\n*2017: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/r/MjA2MjA0, Global Trailblazer Award, USA]\n*2017: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/r/MjA2NDYx, The Fellowship Award from Fashion for Relief in Recognition of Her Majesty\u2019s Humanitarian Efforts Towards Children Caught in Conflict, France]\n*2018: [http://www.queenrania.jo/en/r/MjA3ODQ0, The Influential Personality of the Year Award, at the third annual Arab Social Media Influencers Summit (ASMIS) in Dubai]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Queen Rania of Jordan}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[https://www.facebook.com/QueenRania/?fref=ts Facebook page]\n*[http://www.madrasati.jo Madrasati]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180424201600/http://www.jei.org.jo/ Jordan Education Initiative]\n*[http://www.campaignforeducation.org Global Campaign for Education]\n*[http://www.educationforall2015.org Education for All: Class of 2015]\n*[http://www.ncfa.org.jo/ National Council for Family Affairs]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-roy}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Queen Noor of Jordan|Noor Al-Hussein]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of Jordanian consorts|Queen consort of Jordan]]\n|years=1999\u2013present}}\n{{S-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Current consorts of sovereigns}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rania Of Jordan, Queen}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American University in Cairo alumni]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. employees]]\n[[Category:Arab Open University staff]]\n[[Category:Arab queens]]\n[[Category:Citigroup employees]]\n[[Category:Jordanian internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:Jordanian royal consorts]]\n[[Category:Jordanian feminists]]\n[[Category:Jordanian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Jordanian people of Palestinian descent]]\n[[Category:UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors]]\n[[Category:Jordanian YouTubers]]\n<!-- Honours -->\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:Dames Grand Cross of the Order of Isabella the Catholic]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of the Precious Crown]]\n[[Category:Proponents of Islamic feminism]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of al-Hussein bin Ali]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses Special Class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:United Nations Foundation]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublications:Fixinglinks to disambiguation pages, replaced:Hyperion Books\u2192Hyperion Books", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queen_Rania_of_Jordan"}
{"title_page": "Pons", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox brain\n| Name            = Pons\n| Image           = Brain bulbar region.svg\n| Caption         = Pons in the brainstem\n| Image2          = Gray679.png\n| Caption2        = [[Terms for anatomical location|Anteroinferior view]] of the [[medulla oblongata]] and pons\n| IsPartOf        = [[Brain stem]]\n| Components      =\n| Artery          = [[pontine arteries]]\n| Vein            = transverse and lateral pontine veins\n}}\n\nThe '''pons''' (Latin for \"bridge\") is part of the [[brainstem]], and in [[human]]s and other [[biped]]s lies inferior to the [[midbrain]], superior to the [[medulla oblongata]] and anterior to the [[cerebellum]].\n\nThe pons is also called the '''pons Varolii''' (\"bridge of Varolius\"), after the Italian anatomist and surgeon [[Costanzo Varolio]] (1543\u201375).<ref name=\"Gray1862\">{{cite book|author=Henry Gray|title=Anatomy, descriptive and surgical|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=btSyie_UtxAC&pg=PA514|accessdate=10 November 2010|year=1862|publisher=Blanchard and Lea|pages=514\u2013}}</ref> This region of the brainstem includes [[neural pathways]] and [[nerve tract|tracts]] that conduct signals from the [[brain]] down to the [[cerebellum]] and medulla, and tracts that carry the sensory signals up into the [[thalamus]].<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\">Saladin Kenneth S.(2007) Anatomy & physiology the unity of form and function. Dubuque, IA: McGraw-Hill</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe pons is {.  } in the brainstem situated between the midbrain and the medulla oblongata, and in front of the cerebellum. A separating groove between the pons and the medulla is the '''inferior pontine sulcus'''.<ref name=\"braininfo\">{{cite web |title=BrainInfo |url=http://braininfo.rprc.washington.edu/centraldirectory.aspx?ID=541 |website=braininfo.rprc.washington.edu}}</ref> The '''superior pontine sulcus''' separates the pons from the midbrain.<ref name=\"Carpenter\">{{cite book |last1=Carpenter |first1=M |title=Core text of neuroanatomy |date=1985 |publisher=Williams & Wilkins |isbn=0683014552 |page=42 |edition=3rd}}</ref> The pons can be broadly divided into two parts: the [[basilar part of the pons]] (ventral pons), and the [[pontine tegmentum]] (dorsal pons). Running down the midline of the ventral surface is the [[basilar sulcus]], a groove for the [[basilar artery]]. Most of the pons is supplied by the [[pontine arteries]], which arise from the basilar artery. A smaller portion of the pons is supplied by the [[Anterior inferior cerebellar artery|anterior]] and [[posterior inferior cerebellar arteries]].\n\nThe pons in humans measures about {{convert|2.5|cm}} in length. Most of it appears as a broad anterior bulge above the medulla. Posteriorly, it consists mainly of two pairs of thick stalks called [[Cerebellar peduncle|cerebellar peduncles]]. They connect the cerebellum to the pons ([[middle cerebellar peduncle]]) and midbrain ([[superior cerebellar peduncle]]).<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\" />\n\n===Development===\nDuring [[embryogenesis|embryonic development]], the [[metencephalon]] develops from the [[rhombencephalon]] and gives rise to two structures: the pons and the cerebellum.<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\"/> The [[alar plate]] produces sensory [[neuroblast]]s, which will give rise to the [[solitary nucleus]] and its [[special visceral afferent]] (SVA) column; the [[Cochlear nuclei|cochlear]] and [[vestibular nuclei]], which form the [[special somatic afferent]] (SSA) fibers of the [[vestibulocochlear nerve]],  the spinal and principal [[trigeminal nerve nuclei]], which form the [[General somatic afferent fibers|general somatic afferent column]] (GSA) of the [[trigeminal nerve]], and the [[pontine nuclei]] which relays to the [[cerebellum]].\n\n[[Basal plate (neural tube)|Basal plate]] neuroblasts give rise to the [[abducens nucleus]], which forms the [[general somatic efferent fibers]] (GSE); the facial and motor trigeminal nuclei, which form the [[special visceral efferent]] (SVE) column, and the [[superior salivatory nucleus]], which forms the [[general visceral efferent fibers]] (GVE) of the [[facial nerve]].\n\n===Nuclei===\n[[File:Lower pons horizontal KB.svg|thumb|300px|Cross-section of lower pons, axons shown in blue, grey matter in light grey. Anterior is down and posterior is up]]\nA number of [[cranial nerve nuclei]] are present in the pons:\n* mid-pons: the 'chief' or 'pontine' nucleus of the [[trigeminal nerve]] sensory nucleus (V)\n* mid-pons: the [[motor nucleus for the trigeminal nerve]] (V)\n* lower down in the pons: [[abducens nucleus]] (VI)\n* lower down in the pons: [[facial nerve nucleus]] (VII)\n* lower down in the pons: [[Vestibulocochlear nerve|vestibulocochlear]] nuclei ([[vestibular nuclei]] and [[cochlear nuclei]]) (VIII)\n\n==Function==\nThe functions of these four cranial nerves (V-VIII) include regulation of respiration, controls involuntary actions, sensory roles in hearing, equilibrium, and taste, and in facial sensations such as touch and pain, as well as motor roles in eye movement, facial expressions, chewing, swallowing, and the secretion of saliva and tears.<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\"/>\n\nThe pons contains [[Nucleus (neuroanatomy)|nuclei]] that relay signals from the forebrain to the cerebellum, along with nuclei that deal primarily with sleep, respiration, swallowing, bladder control, hearing, equilibrium, taste, eye movement, facial expressions, facial sensation, and posture.<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\" />\n\nWithin the pons is the [[pneumotaxic center]] consisting of the [[subparabrachial nucleus|subparabrachial]] and the [[medial parabrachial nucleus|medial parabrachial]] [[nucleus (neuroanatomy)|nuclei]]. This center regulates the change from inhalation to exhalation.<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\" />\n\nThe pons is implicated in [[sleep paralysis]], and may also play a role in generating dreams.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\n==Clinical significance==\n* [[Central pontine myelinolysis]] is a [[demyelinating disease]] that causes difficulty with sense of balance, walking, sense of touch, swallowing and speaking. In a clinical setting, it is often associated with transplant or rapid correction of blood sodium. Undiagnosed, it can lead to death or [[locked-in syndrome]].\n\n==Other animals==\n===Evolution===\nThe pons first evolved as an offshoot of the medullary [[reticular formation]].<ref name=Pritchard>[[#refPritchard|Pritchard and Alloway ''Medical Neuroscience'']]</ref> Since [[lamprey]]s possess a pons, it has been argued that it must have evolved as a region distinct from the [[medulla oblongata|medulla]] by the time the first [[agnathans]] appeared, 505 million years ago.<ref name=Butler>[[#refButler|Butler and Hodos ''Comparative vertebrate neuroanatomy: evolution and adaptation'']]</ref>\n\n==Additional images==\n<gallery>\n File:Pons.gif|Location and topography of Pons (animation)\n File:Gray701.png|Axial section of the pons, at its upper part\n File:Gray719.png|Hind- and mid-brains; posterolateral view\n File:Gray720.png|Median sagittal section of brain\n File:Brain stem sagittal section.svg|Nuclei of the pons and brainstem\n File:Slide2cuc.JPG|Cerebrum. Deep dissection. Inferior dissection.\n\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n*{{cite book\n| title     = Medical neuroscience\n|author1=Pritchard, TE  |author2=Alloway, D\n |lastauthoramp=yes | publisher = Hayes Barton Press\n| year      = 1999\n| isbn      = 978-1-59377-200-0\n| url       = https://books.google.com/books/about/Medical_neuroscience.html?id=m7Y80PcFHtsC\n|ref=refPritchard}}\n*{{cite book\n| title     = Comparative vertebrate neuroanatomy: evolution and adaptation\n|author1=Butler, AB  |author2=Hodos, W\n |lastauthoramp=yes | publisher = Wiley-Blackwell\n| year      = 2005\n| isbn      = 978-0-471-21005-4\n| url       = https://books.google.com/?id=3nO6ggvV1PUC&dq=%22Comparative+vertebrate+neuroanatomy:+evolution+and+adaptation%22.\n|ref=refButler}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pons}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060502144925/http://faculty.ucc.edu/biology-potter/The_Brain/sld017.htm Diagram at UCC]\n* {{BrainMaps|Pons}}\n\n{{Nervous system}}\n{{Pons}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Pons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox brain\n| Name            = Pons\n| Image           = Brain bulbar region.svg\n| Caption         = Pons in the brainstem\n| Image2          = Gray679.png\n| Caption2        = [[Terms for anatomical location|Anteroinferior view]] of the [[medulla oblongata]] and pons\n| IsPartOf        = [[Brain stem]]\n| Components      =\n| Artery          = [[pontine arteries]]\n| Vein            = transverse and lateral pontine veins\n}}\n\nThe '''pons''' (Latin for \"bridge\") is part of the [[brainstem]], and in [[human]]s and other [[biped]]s lies inferior to the [[midbrain]], superior to the [[medulla oblongata]] and anterior to the [[cerebellum]].\n\nThe pons is also called the '''pons Varolii''' (\"bridge of Varolius\"), after the Italian anatomist and surgeon [[Costanzo Varolio]] (1543\u201375).<ref name=\"Gray1862\">{{cite book|author=Henry Gray|title=Anatomy, descriptive and surgical|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=btSyie_UtxAC&pg=PA514|accessdate=10 November 2010|year=1862|publisher=Blanchard and Lea|pages=514\u2013}}</ref> This region of the brainstem includes [[neural pathways]] and [[nerve tract|tracts]] that conduct signals from the [[brain]] down to the [[cerebellum]] and medulla, and tracts that carry the sensory signals up into the [[thalamus]].<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\">Saladin Kenneth S.(2007) Anatomy & physiology the unity of form and function. Dubuque, IA: McGraw-Hill</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe pons is in the brainstem situated between the midbrain and the medulla oblongata, and in front of the cerebellum. A separating groove between the pons and the medulla is the '''inferior pontine sulcus'''.<ref name=\"braininfo\">{{cite web |title=BrainInfo |url=http://braininfo.rprc.washington.edu/centraldirectory.aspx?ID=541 |website=braininfo.rprc.washington.edu}}</ref> The '''superior pontine sulcus''' separates the pons from the midbrain.<ref name=\"Carpenter\">{{cite book |last1=Carpenter |first1=M |title=Core text of neuroanatomy |date=1985 |publisher=Williams & Wilkins |isbn=0683014552 |page=42 |edition=3rd}}</ref> The pons can be broadly divided into two parts: the [[basilar part of the pons]] (ventral pons), and the [[pontine tegmentum]] (dorsal pons). Running down the midline of the ventral surface is the [[basilar sulcus]], a groove for the [[basilar artery]]. Most of the pons is supplied by the [[pontine arteries]], which arise from the basilar artery. A smaller portion of the pons is supplied by the [[Anterior inferior cerebellar artery|anterior]] and [[posterior inferior cerebellar arteries]].\n\nThe pons in humans measures about {{convert|2.5|cm}} in length. Most of it appears as a broad anterior bulge above the medulla. Posteriorly, it consists mainly of two pairs of thick stalks called [[Cerebellar peduncle|cerebellar peduncles]]. They connect the cerebellum to the pons ([[middle cerebellar peduncle]]) and midbrain ([[superior cerebellar peduncle]]).<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\" />\n\n===Development===\nDuring [[embryogenesis|embryonic development]], the [[metencephalon]] develops from the [[rhombencephalon]] and gives rise to two structures: the pons and the cerebellum.<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\"/> The [[alar plate]] produces sensory [[neuroblast]]s, which will give rise to the [[solitary nucleus]] and its [[special visceral afferent]] (SVA) column; the [[Cochlear nuclei|cochlear]] and [[vestibular nuclei]], which form the [[special somatic afferent]] (SSA) fibers of the [[vestibulocochlear nerve]],  the spinal and principal [[trigeminal nerve nuclei]], which form the [[General somatic afferent fibers|general somatic afferent column]] (GSA) of the [[trigeminal nerve]], and the [[pontine nuclei]] which relays to the [[cerebellum]].\n\n[[Basal plate (neural tube)|Basal plate]] neuroblasts give rise to the [[abducens nucleus]], which forms the [[general somatic efferent fibers]] (GSE); the facial and motor trigeminal nuclei, which form the [[special visceral efferent]] (SVE) column, and the [[superior salivatory nucleus]], which forms the [[general visceral efferent fibers]] (GVE) of the [[facial nerve]].\n\n===Nuclei===\n[[File:Lower pons horizontal KB.svg|thumb|300px|Cross-section of lower pons, axons shown in blue, grey matter in light grey. Anterior is down and posterior is up]]\nA number of [[cranial nerve nuclei]] are present in the pons:\n* mid-pons: the 'chief' or 'pontine' nucleus of the [[trigeminal nerve]] sensory nucleus (V)\n* mid-pons: the [[motor nucleus for the trigeminal nerve]] (V)\n* lower down in the pons: [[abducens nucleus]] (VI)\n* lower down in the pons: [[facial nerve nucleus]] (VII)\n* lower down in the pons: [[Vestibulocochlear nerve|vestibulocochlear]] nuclei ([[vestibular nuclei]] and [[cochlear nuclei]]) (VIII)\n\n==Function==\nThe functions of these four cranial nerves (V-VIII) include regulation of respiration, controls involuntary actions, sensory roles in hearing, equilibrium, and taste, and in facial sensations such as touch and pain, as well as motor roles in eye movement, facial expressions, chewing, swallowing, and the secretion of saliva and tears.<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\"/>\n\nThe pons contains [[Nucleus (neuroanatomy)|nuclei]] that relay signals from the forebrain to the cerebellum, along with nuclei that deal primarily with sleep, respiration, swallowing, bladder control, hearing, equilibrium, taste, eye movement, facial expressions, facial sensation, and posture.<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\" />\n\nWithin the pons is the [[pneumotaxic center]] consisting of the [[subparabrachial nucleus|subparabrachial]] and the [[medial parabrachial nucleus|medial parabrachial]] [[nucleus (neuroanatomy)|nuclei]]. This center regulates the change from inhalation to exhalation.<ref name=\"Saladin Kenneth S.2007\" />\n\nThe pons is implicated in [[sleep paralysis]], and may also play a role in generating dreams.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\n==Clinical significance==\n* [[Central pontine myelinolysis]] is a [[demyelinating disease]] that causes difficulty with sense of balance, walking, sense of touch, swallowing and speaking. In a clinical setting, it is often associated with transplant or rapid correction of blood sodium. Undiagnosed, it can lead to death or [[locked-in syndrome]].\n\n==Other animals==\n===Evolution===\nThe pons first evolved as an offshoot of the medullary [[reticular formation]].<ref name=Pritchard>[[#refPritchard|Pritchard and Alloway ''Medical Neuroscience'']]</ref> Since [[lamprey]]s possess a pons, it has been argued that it must have evolved as a region distinct from the [[medulla oblongata|medulla]] by the time the first [[agnathans]] appeared, 505 million years ago.<ref name=Butler>[[#refButler|Butler and Hodos ''Comparative vertebrate neuroanatomy: evolution and adaptation'']]</ref>\n\n==Additional images==\n<gallery>\n File:Pons.gif|Location and topography of Pons (animation)\n File:Gray701.png|Axial section of the pons, at its upper part\n File:Gray719.png|Hind- and mid-brains; posterolateral view\n File:Gray720.png|Median sagittal section of brain\n File:Brain stem sagittal section.svg|Nuclei of the pons and brainstem\n File:Slide2cuc.JPG|Cerebrum. Deep dissection. Inferior dissection.\n\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n*{{cite book\n| title     = Medical neuroscience\n|author1=Pritchard, TE  |author2=Alloway, D\n |lastauthoramp=yes | publisher = Hayes Barton Press\n| year      = 1999\n| isbn      = 978-1-59377-200-0\n| url       = https://books.google.com/books/about/Medical_neuroscience.html?id=m7Y80PcFHtsC\n|ref=refPritchard}}\n*{{cite book\n| title     = Comparative vertebrate neuroanatomy: evolution and adaptation\n|author1=Butler, AB  |author2=Hodos, W\n |lastauthoramp=yes | publisher = Wiley-Blackwell\n| year      = 2005\n| isbn      = 978-0-471-21005-4\n| url       = https://books.google.com/?id=3nO6ggvV1PUC&dq=%22Comparative+vertebrate+neuroanatomy:+evolution+and+adaptation%22.\n|ref=refButler}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pons}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060502144925/http://faculty.ucc.edu/biology-potter/The_Brain/sld017.htm Diagram at UCC]\n* {{BrainMaps|Pons}}\n\n{{Nervous system}}\n{{Pons}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Pons]]\n", "name_user": "171.76.250.34", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eStructure:Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pons"}
{"title_page": "Purple Haze", "text_new": "{{short description|Song first recorded by the Jimi Hendrix Experience in 1967}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Purple Haze\n| cover      = PurpleHaze-GermanSingle.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = German single picture sleeve\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]]\n| B-side     = \n*\"51st Anniversary\" (UK)\n*\"[[The Wind Cries Mary]]\" (US)\n| released   = \n*{{Start date|1967|03|17}} (UK){{efn|name=\"Track\"|There are conflicting dates given for the Track single release of \"Purple Haze\".  Shapiro,{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=526}} Roby,{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}} and the Jimi Hendrix Encyclopedia{{sfn|Jimi Hendrix Encyclopedia|2012|loc=Entry for March 17th, 1967}} list the date as March 17, 1967; McDermott{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=40}} uses March 1, 1967.}}\n*June 19, 1967 (US)\n| format     = [[Gramophone record#Formats|7-inch 45&nbsp;rpm]]\n| recorded   =\n*January 11, 1967\n*February 3\u20138, 1967\n| studio     = \n*[[De Lane Lea Studios|De Lane Lea]], London\n*[[Olympic Studios|Olympic]], London\n| genre      =\n*[[Psychedelic rock]]{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=148}}\n*[[hard rock]]{{sfn|Tawa|2005|p=193}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=46}}\n| label      = \n*[[Track Records|Track]] (UK)\n*[[Reprise Records|Reprise]] (US)\n| writer     = [[Jimi Hendrix]]\n| producer   = [[Chas Chandler]]\n| chronology = Experience UK\n| prev_title = [[Hey Joe]]\n| prev_year  = 1966\n| next_title = [[The Wind Cries Mary]]\n| next_year  = 1967\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Experience US\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Hey Joe#Tim Rose and Jimi Hendrix (1966)|Hey Joe]]\n | prev_year  = 1967\n | title      = Purple Haze\n | year       = 1967\n | next_title = [[Foxey Lady]]<!--US single used the American spelling, see McDermott 2009 p.81-->\n | next_year  = 1967\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Purple Haze'''\" is a song written by [[Jimi Hendrix]] and released as the second record single by [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]] on March 17, 1967. As a record chart hit in several countries and the opening number on the Experience's debut American album, it was many people's first exposure to Hendrix's [[psychedelic rock]] sound.\n\nThe song features his inventive guitar playing, which uses the signature [[Hendrix chord]] and a mix of blues and Eastern modalities, shaped by novel sound processing techniques.  Because of ambiguities in the lyrics, listeners often interpret the song as referring to a [[psychedelic experience]], although Hendrix described it as a love song.\n\n\"Purple Haze\" is one of Hendrix's best-known songs and appears on many Hendrix compilation albums.  The song featured regularly in concerts and each of Hendrix's group configurations issued live recordings. It was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] and is included on lists of the greatest guitar songs, including at number two by ''Rolling Stone'' and number one by ''Q'' magazine.\n\n==Background and recording==\nBy January 5, 1967, the Jimi Hendrix Experience's first single, \"[[Hey Joe]]\", backed with \"[[Stone Free]]\", had peaked at number six on the UK record chart.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=28}} \"Hey Joe\" was not a Hendrix composition \u2013 it was written by [[Billy Roberts]] and recorded by several groups prior to the Experience. Hendrix commented, \"That record isn't us. The next one's gonna be different.  We're working on an LP which will mainly be our stuff.\"{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=95}} The group recorded several demos of original material at studios in London, including \"Can You See Me\", \"[[Foxy Lady]]\", \"[[Third Stone from the Sun]]\", \"[[Red House (song)|Red House]]\", and \"Remember\".{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=27\u201329}}  In the middle of December, producer [[Chas Chandler]] heard Hendrix toying around with a new guitar riff. \"I heard him playing it at the flat and was knocked out. I told him to keep working on that, saying, 'That's the next single!{{'\"}}{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=32}}  Chandler claimed that after some more urging, Hendrix wrote the rest of \"Purple Haze\" in the dressing room of a London club during the afternoon of December 26, 1966, before a gig.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|1992|p=31}} In several interviews, Hendrix spoke about writing the song, but did not mention where or when he wrote it.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=149}}\n\nThe Experience began recording \"Purple Haze\" on January 11, 1967, at [[De Lane Lea Studios]] in London. According to drummer [[Mitch Mitchell]], he and bassist [[Noel Redding]] learned the song in the studio: \"Hendrix came in and kind of hummed us the riff and showed Noel the chords and the changes. I listened to it and we went, 'OK, let's do it.' We got it on the third take as I recall.\"{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}} The basic track was recorded in four hours, according to Chandler.{{sfn|McDermott|Cox|Kramer|1995|p=25}}  [[Multitrack recording]] technology allowed engineers to record and complete additional parts on the final master.  After the basic track was finished, Chandler explained that he and Hendrix developed the song:\n{{quote|With 'Purple Haze', Hendrix and I were striving for a sound and just kept going back in [to the studio], two hours at a time, trying to achieve it. It wasn't like we were there for days on end.  We recorded it, and then Hendrix and I would be sitting at home saying, 'Let's try that.' Then we would go in for an hour or two. That's how it was in those days. However long it took to record one specific idea, that's how long we would book. We kept going in and out.{{sfn|McDermott|Cox|Kramer|1995|p=25}}}}  Redding and Mitchell were not included in the process because Chandler felt that it was more efficient for him and Hendrix to do it alone.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=33}} To get a better quality recording, Chandler took the four-track tape recorded at De Lane Lea to [[Olympic Studios]] for [[overdubbing]] (although Hendrix had worked with eight-track recording in the US, it was not yet available in the UK).{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=35\u201336}} At Olympic, they were assigned [[Eddie Kramer]], who, as a sound engineer, played an important role in subsequent Hendrix recordings.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=35}} Hendrix added new vocals and guitar parts between February 3 and 8, 1967.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=35\u201336}}  Unlike the conventional techniques used by the Experience to record previous songs, Chandler decided to try out new effects and sounds for \"Purple Haze\".{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=32}} He enhanced background sounds (some contributed by Redding) by playing them back through headphones, which were moved around the recording microphone, creating \"a weird echo\".{{sfn|McDermott|Cox|Kramer|1995|p=27}} Chandler also used sped-up guitar parts recorded at half-speed (which also raises the [[Pitch (music)|pitch]]) and [[Panning (audio)|panning]] to create novel effects.{{sfn|McDermott|Cox|Kramer|1995|p=27}} The guitar solo features the first use of the [[Octavia (effects pedal)|Octavia]] guitar effects unit.{{sfn|McDermott|Cox|Kramer|1995|p=27}}  Acoustical and electronics engineer [[Roger Mayer (engineer)|Roger Mayer]] developed the unit with input from Hendrix. The Octavia doubles the frequency of the sound it is fed, essentially adding an upper octave.<ref name=\"Mayer\">\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.roger-mayer.co.uk/octavia.htm\n| title = Octavia\n| website = Roger Mayer\n| accessdate = July 7, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics and interpretation==\nIn interviews, Hendrix usually gave different answers about the development of the song's lyrics.  Biographer [[Harry Shapiro (author)|Harry Shapiro]] points out that \"Purple Haze\" is most likely \"a pot-pourri of ideas\" which Hendrix developed over time.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=149}}  As a fan of science fiction, he frequently incorporated its imagery in his songwriting.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}  Hendrix read ''[[Night of Light]]'', a 1966 novel by [[Philip Jos\u00e9 Farmer]], that expanded on a short story published in 1957.{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}}  In the story set on a distant planet, sunspots produce a \"purplish haze\" which has a disorienting effect on the inhabitants.{{sfn|Roby|Schreiber|2010|p=158}}{{efn|The phrase \"purple haze\" appears in literature, including in [[Charles Dickens]]' 1861 novel ''[[Great Expectations]]'': \"There was the red sun, on the low level of the shore, in a purple haze, fast deepening into black\" (Chapter 54).}}  An early handwritten draft by Hendrix, titled \"Purple Haze \u2013 Jesus Saves\", uses dream-like imagery where the sense of direction and time is distorted.{{sfn|Hendrix|2003|p=131}}  In an interview on January 28, 1967, before the song was completed, Hendrix was asked how he wrote songs; he responded, \"I dream a lot and I put my dreams down as songs. I wrote one called 'First Look Around the Corner' and another called 'The Purple Haze,' which was about a dream I had that I was walking under the sea.\"{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}}{{efn|The Hendrix song \"[[Are You Experienced? (song)|Are You Experienced?]]\", recorded in April 1967 and included as the title track for the Experience's debut album, includes a reference to walking under the sea: \"We'll hold hands and then we'll watch the sunrise, from the bottom of the sea\".{{sfn|Hendrix|2003|p=21}}}}  He later expressed frustration that he was unable to more fully develop his ideas for the song:\n{{quote|You know the song we had named 'Purple Haze'? [It] had about a thousand, thousand words&nbsp;... I had it all written out.  It was about going through, through this land.  This mythical&nbsp;... because that's what I like to do is write a lot of mythical scenes.  You know, like the history of the wars on Neptune.{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}}}}\nSo far, only a crumpled single sheet of ruled yellow tablet paper is on exhibit at the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] and does not include any of the lyrics used in the Experience song.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://rockhall.com/photo-gallery/spotlight-artifacts/1531/\n| title = Jimi Hendrix \"Purple Haze' Lyrics, 1966\n| website = [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]\n| accessdate = October 25, 2014\n}}</ref>  Chandler admitted that in the early stages, he helped Hendrix shape the songs and lyrics to radio single length.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=147}}  Biographer Keith Shadwick comments that although much of the complexity may have been sacrificed, it resulted in verses that are \"simple, focused and striking\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}\n \nAfter its release, Hendrix offered another explanation: \"He [the song's protagonist] likes this girl so much, that he doesn't know what [state] he's in, ya know.  A sort of daze, I suppose.  That's what the song is all about.\"{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=149}}  This draws on an experience Hendrix had while still in New York, where he felt that a girl was attempting to use [[Louisiana Voodoo|voodoo]] to trap him and he became ill.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=148}}  Shapiro believes that this is reflected in most of the first two verses:{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=148}}\n{{poemquote|Purple haze all around, don't know if I'm coming up or down\nAm I happy or in misery, whatever it is that girl put a spell on me}}\n\nMany fans and the press interpret the song as referring to a psychedelic experience due to lines such as \"purple haze all in my brain\" and \"'scuse me while I kiss the sky\".{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}}  However, Hendrix and those closest to him never discussed any connection between [[psychedelic drug]]s and the song, although Shapiro admits that, at the time, to do so would have been \"professional suicide\".{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=148}} Chandler, who claimed he was present when Hendrix wrote it, later denied suggestions that Hendrix did so while under the influence of psychedelics.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|1992|p=31}}<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\">\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/song/purple-haze-mt0004552447\n| title = Jimi Hendrix/Jimi Hendrix Experience: Purple Haze \u2013 Song Review\n| last = Ruhlmann\n| first = William\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = July 5, 2014\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>  Commenting on the lyrics, Shadwick concludes \"the music [was allowed] to tell the larger story.  Poised effectively between the twin intoxicants of drugs and desire, they could be interpreted to the listener's taste\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}{{efn|Three months after the UK single release, the Experience performed at the [[Monterey Pop Festival]] on June 18, 1967. Underground chemist [[Owsley Stanley]] had made a special batch of [[LSD]] for the festival, which he dubbed \"Monterey Purple\".{{sfn|Walker|2011|p=A23}}  Although some connected it to \"Purple Haze\",{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=191}} Stanley disliked the association, feeling that it was \"far from inducing haze, [rather it] would confer upon the user preternatural clarity.\"{{sfn|Walker|2011|p=A23}}}}  In concert, Hendrix sometimes substituted lyrics for comic effect; \"'scuse me while I kiss the sky\" was rendered \"'scuse me while I kiss this guy\" (while gesturing towards Mitchell),{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=148}} \"'scuse me while I kiss that policeman\" (at a near riot in Los Angeles), or \"'scuse me while I fuck the sky\" (during a downpour in Seattle).{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=302}}\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n| type        = music\n| filename    = The first 17 seconds of \"Purple Haze\" by the Jimi Hendrix Experience 1967.ogg\n| title       = Purple Haze\n| description = 17 seconds of intro\n| pos         = \n}}\n\nMusic critic William Ruhlmann describes \"Purple Haze\" as having \"relentlessly driving, if relatively slow-paced underlying music, which provides a good platform for some of Hendrix's inventive guitar playing\".<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/>  Beginning with its [[Consonance and dissonance#Dissonance|dissonant]] opening and heavy use of [[Distortion (music)|distortion]], Hendrix's techniques \"all contributed to the dirty, raw, metallic, [and] angular sounds\" heard in the song, according to Shapiro.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=144}}  The intro consists of the melodic [[Interval (music)|interval]] of a [[tritone]] or [[Diminution#Diminution of intervals|diminished]] (sometimes called [[Flat (music)|flattened]]) [[diminished fifth|fifth]].{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}}  Historically, this dissonant interval has been referred to as ''diabolus in musica'' (literally \"Devil in music\") and was reputedly proscribed by [[papal bull]] during the [[Spanish Inquisition]], because \"to play it was like ringing Satan's doorbell\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=144}}{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}} It is sounded during the first two measures by Hendrix playing a B{{music|flat}} on guitar against an E played by Redding on bass, followed by the respective octaves.{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}}  Mitchell on drums comes in for the third measure, when Hendrix introduces the riff that piqued Chandler's interest, and Redding continues playing the octaves in E.{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=13}}\n\nAfter the riff, the verse sections begin, which Shadwick describe as \"simplicity itself, consisting of just three chords\": E7{{music|sharp}}9, G, and A.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=13}}  The E7{{music|sharp}}9, or dominant seventh sharp ninth chord, has come to be called the \"Hendrix chord\" by guitarists and was used primarily in [[rhythm and blues]] and [[jazz]] before Hendrix helped popularize it.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|pp=146\u2013148}}  He also used an unconventional fingering technique for the G and A chords.{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}}  Because Hendrix used his thumb to fret the [[Root (chord)|roots]] of the G and A chords on the sixth string, his fingers were left in a position to create different chord [[Voicing (music)|voicings]].{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}}  Instead of the usual G [[barre chord]] (G\u2013B\u2013G\u2013B\u2013D\u2013G), a G[[Fifth (chord)|5]] (G\u2013X\u2013G\u2013G\u2013D\u2013G) is sometimes played with the [[major third]] (B) being muted on the fifth string and replaced by the open third string (G).{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}}  Redding follows the chord changes mostly by playing the root with occasional [[Nonchord tone|passing notes]],{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|pp=3\u201314}} while Mitchell heightens the tension with drum flourishes that accentuate Hendrix's vocal and guitar.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}\n\nBiographer [[David Henderson (poet)|David Henderson]] describes Hendrix's guitar tone as \"at the razor edge of distort\".{{sfn|Henderson|1981|p=103}}  However, individual notes are still clear, as well as the harmonically more complex chords, even with the use of extreme overdrive for the time.{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=13}}  The tension is maintained until the guitar solo, which \"arrives as something of a release rather than a further racking up of the atmosphere.\"{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}  It is also when Hendrix first introduces the Octavia, coupled with a [[Fuzz Face]] distortion unit.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=146}}  Whitehill describes the solo as \"almost sound[ing] likes he's playing a blues raga.  He starts out playing in the [[Mixolydian mode]] and then he goes right into the blues side.  The Octavia has the effect of a sitar, kind of like Ravi Shankar meets B.B. King.\"{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=4}}  During the song's outro, the guitar part recorded at 7\u00bd [[Tape recorder#Tapedeck speeds|inches per second]] (ips) played back at 15 ips, is combined with the Octavia, further extending the guitar's upper frequency range.{{sfn|Whitehill|Rubin|1992|p=4}}  Henderson describes it as \"an uncanny piercing tone that takes off, Eastern-sounding beyond the range of the guitar\"{{sfn|Henderson|1981|p=104}} and, according to Shadwick, \"gives the impression that the guitar notes are flying off into the ether.\"{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}\n\n==Releases and charts==\n[[File:Are You Experienced - US cover-edit.jpg|right|thumb|upright|240px|\"Purple Haze\" became the opening track on the 1967 American ''[[Are You Experienced]]'' album]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Top singles charts 1967\n!Peak position\n!Weeks on chart\n|-\n| Austria ''Austrian Hitparade''<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url=http://austriancharts.at/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Jimi+Hendrix+Experience&titel=Purple+Haze&cat=s\n| title=Austrian Hitparade: Jimi Hendrix Experience \u2013 Purple Haze (song)\n| website=austriancharts.at\n| publisher=Hung Medien\n| language=German\n| accessdate = July 11, 2014\n}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n| Germany ''Musicline''<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Jimi+Hendrix/10446/?type=single\n| title=Musicline: Jimi Hendrix Single-Charts\n| website=musicline.de\n| publisher=[[Phononet GmbH]]\n| language=German\n| accessdate=July 11, 2014\n| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529195337/http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Jimi+Hendrix/10446/?type=single\n| archive-date=May 29, 2014\n| url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|17\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n| Netherlands ''Dutch Charts''<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Jimi+Hendrix+Experience&titel=Purple+Haze&cat=s \n |title=Dutch Charts: Jimi Hendrix Experience \u2013 Purple Haze \n |website=dutchcharts.nl \n |publisher=Hung Medien \n |language=Dutch \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428145343/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Jimi%20Hendrix%20Experience&titel=Purple%20Haze&cat=s \n |archivedate=April 28, 2014 \n |accessdate=November 2, 2014 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n| Norway ''Norwegian Charts''<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url=http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Jimi+Hendrix+Experience&titel=Purple+Haze&cat=s\n| title=Norwegian Charts: Jimi Hendrix Experience \u2013 Purple Haze (song)\n| website=norwegiancharts.com\n| publisher=Hung Medien\n| accessdate=July 11, 2014\n}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n| UK ''[[UK Singles Chart|Official Singles Chart]]''<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/jimi%20hendrix%20experience/\n| title = Jimi Hendrix Experience \u2013 Singles\n| website = [[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]]\n| accessdate = July 11, 2014\n}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|align=\"center\"|14\n|-\n| US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]{{sfn|Whitburn|2008|p=176}}\n|align=\"center\"|65\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n|}\nOn March 17, 1967, \"Purple Haze\" was released in the UK as the first single on [[Track Records]].{{efn|name=\"Track\"}}  Another Hendrix composition, the [[R&B]]-influenced \"51st Anniversary\" was included as the [[B-side]].{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=40}}  [[Paul McCartney]], who was an early Hendrix supporter, gave the record an enthusiastic pre-release review in ''[[Melody Maker]]''.{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}}  The single entered the charts at number 39 on ''[[Record Mirror]]'' and at number 43 on ''Melody Maker''.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|1992|p=51}} It peaked at number three and spent 14 weeks on the chart.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/jimi%20hendrix%20experience/\n| title = Jimi Hendrix Experience \u2013 Singles\n| website = [[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]]\n| accessdate = Jul 5, 2014\n}}</ref>  During March 1967, several performances of \"Purple Haze\" were filmed to promote the song and used for television programs, such as ''[[Beat-Club]]'', [[Simon Dee|''Dee Time'']], and ''[[Top of the Pops]]''.{{sfn|Roby|2002|pp=215\u2013216}}  Live performances were also broadcast on German [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] and [[BBC Radio]]'s ''[[Saturday Club (BBC radio)|Saturday Club]]''.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=40\u201341}}\n\nFor the American single, [[Reprise Records]] paired the song with \"[[The Wind Cries Mary]]\".{{sfn|Whitburn|2008|p=176}}{{efn|Track Records marked on the box with master tape sent to Reprise Records for its remastering, \"DELIBERATE DISTORTION. DO NOT CORRECT.\"{{sfn|Roby|Shreiber|2010|p=184}}}}  It was released on June 19, 1967, the day following the Experience's performance at the [[Monterey Pop Festival]].{{efn|There are also conflicting dates for the Reprise single release.  Shapiro,{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=528}} Roby,{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}} and Shadwick{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=116}} list it as June 19, 1967; McDermott{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=60}} uses August 16, 1967, one week before the American release of ''Are You Experienced''.}} The single entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] pop chart on August 26, where it spent eight weeks and reached number 65.{{sfn|Whitburn|2008|p=176}}  \"Purple Haze\" was included as the opening track on the American release of ''Are You Experienced'' on August 23, 1967.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=61}}  Because of the song's airplay on [[Progressive rock (radio format)|underground FM radio]], the album became more popular than Hendrix's singles.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=60}}{{efn|[[KMPX (defunct)|KMPX]] in San Francisco, one of the pioneers of the \"underground\" or progressive radio formats in the US, began playing an acetate pressing of the song before it was released by Track Records in the UK.{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=75}}}}\n\nOne of Hendrix's most popular songs,<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/> \"Purple Haze\" appears on numerous compilation albums.  Some of these include ''[[Smash Hits (The Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Smash Hits]]'', ''[[The Essential Jimi Hendrix]]'', ''[[The Singles Album (Jimi Hendrix album)|The Singles Album]]'', ''[[Kiss the Sky (Jimi Hendrix album)|Kiss the Sky]]'', ''[[Cornerstones: 1967\u20131970]]'', ''[[The Ultimate Experience]]'', ''[[Experience Hendrix: The Best of Jimi Hendrix]]'', ''[[Voodoo Child: The Jimi Hendrix Collection]]'', and ''[[The Singles Collection (Jimi Hendrix album)|The Singles Collection]]''.<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/>  An alternative version recorded at the same time, but with different vocal and guitar overdubs, is the first song on ''[[The Jimi Hendrix Experience (album)|The Jimi Hendrix Experience]]'' 2000 box set.  Live recordings of \"Purple Haze\" as performed by each of the different Hendrix lineups have been released.{{sfn|Belmo|Loveless|1998|pp=399\u2013412}} These include ''[[Live at Monterey]]'' (the Experience), ''[[Live at Woodstock (Jimi Hendrix album)|Live at Woodstock]]'' (Gypsy Sun and Rainbows), ''[[Live at the Fillmore East (Jimi Hendrix album)|Live at the Fillmore East]]'' (Band of Gypsys), and ''[[Live at Berkeley]]'' (the Cry of Love touring group).<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/>  Additional live recordings with the Experience appear on ''[[Winterland (The Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Winterland]]'' (2011 ''Billboard'' number 49 album) and ''[[Miami Pop Festival (Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Miami Pop Festival]]'' (2013 ''Billboard'' number 39 album).\n\n==Recognition and influence==\nIn March 2005, [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]] ranked \"Purple Haze\" at number one in its list of the \"100 Greatest Guitar Tracks Ever!\"<ref>\n{{cite magazine\n| date = March 2005\n| title = 100 Greatest Guitar Tracks Ever!\n| magazine = [[Q (magazine)|Q]]\n| url = http://www.qthemusic.com/\n| archiveurl = http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage3.htm \n| archivedate = 2013\n| accessdate  = July 5, 2014\n}}</ref> The song placed at number two on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's \"100 Greatest Guitar Songs of All Time\" list, which noted that the song \"unveiled a new guitar language charged with spiritual hunger and the poetry possible in electricity and studio technology\".<ref>\n{{cite magazine\n| year = 2003 \n| title = 100 Greatest Guitar Songs of All Time \n| magazine = [[Rolling Stone]] \n| url = https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/20947527\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080530224813/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/20947527/page/3 \n| archivedate = May 30, 2008 \n| accessdate = July 5, 2014 \n| url-status = dead \n}}</ref> It also appears at number 17 on the magazine's \"[[500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\" list, with the comment that \"it launched not one but two revolutions: late-Sixties psychedelia and the unprecedented genius of Jimi Hendrix\".<ref>\n{{cite magazine\n| date = December 9, 2004\n| title = The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time\n| magazine = [[Rolling Stone]]\n| issue = 963\n| url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/the-jimi-hendrix-experience-purple-haze-20110517\n| accessdate = July 5, 2014\n}}</ref> Author and music critic [[Dave Marsh]] called it the \"debut single of the [[Album Rock Era]]\".{{sfn|Marsh|1999|p=178}}  In 1995, \"Purple Haze\" was included as one of the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]'s \"500 Songs That Shaped Rock and Roll\".<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.rockhall.com/exhibithighlights/500-songs \n| title = 500 Songs That Shaped Rock and Roll \n| website = [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] \n| year = 1995 \n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070502032502/http://www.rockhall.com/exhibithighlights/500-songs-by-name-np/ \n| archivedate = May 2, 2007 \n| accessdate = July 5, 2014 \n| url-status = dead \n}}</ref>  [[NPR]] named the song to its list of the \"100 Most Important American Musical Works of the 20th Century\" in 2000.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.npr.org/programs/specials/vote/list100.html#P\n| title = The NPR 100: The 100 Most Important American Musical Works of the 20th Century\n| website = [[NPR.org]]\n| accessdate = October 24, 2014\n}}</ref>  In 2000, it was given a [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]], which \"honor[s] recordings of lasting qualitative or historical significance\".<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/hall-of-fame#p\n| title = Grammy Hall of Fame Awards \u2013 Past Recipients\n| website = [[Grammy.org]]\n| year = 2000\n| accessdate = July 5, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nMany musicians have recorded their interpretations of the song, making it one of Hendrix's most covered songs.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=526}}  [[Dion DiMucci]] included an acoustic version with strings on his 1968 comeback album ''Dion''.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/dion-mw0000623651\n| title = ''Dion'' \u2013 Review\n| last = Unterberger\n| first = Richie\n| authorlink = Richie Unterberger\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = November 3, 2014\n}}</ref> Released as a single in 1969, it appeared at number 63 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, which was two positions higher than Hendrix' single in 1967.  Also with a new arrangement, [[the Cure]] recorded it for the various artist's ''[[Stone Free: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix]]'' in 1993.<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/> Their rendition reached number two on ''Billboard's'' [[Modern Rock Tracks]] alternative rock chart. \"Purple Haze\" has achieved an unusual level of interest among classical musicians.<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/> The [[Meridian Arts Ensemble]], the [[Hampton String Quartet]], and [[Nigel Kennedy]] have recorded their interpretations and the [[Kronos Quartet]] often play it as an encore.<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{Notelist|30em}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n'''References'''\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Belmo\n| last2 = Loveless\n| first2 = Steve\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Experience the Music\n| year = 1998\n| location = Burlington, Ontario, Canada\n| publisher = Collector's Guide Publishing\n| isbn = 1-896522-45-9\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Cross\n| first = Charles R.\n| authorlink = Charles R. Cross\n| title = [[Room Full of Mirrors]]: A Biography of Jimi Hendrix\n| edition = 1st. Trade Paperback\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[Hachette Books#Hyperion Books|Hyperion Books]]\n| year = 2005\n| isbn = 0-7868-8841-5\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| author = Hal Leonard\n| title = Experience Hendrix: The Best of Jimi Hendrix Transcribed Scores\n| year = 1998\n| location = Milwaukee, Wisconsin\n| publisher = [[Hal Leonard Corporation|Hal Leonard]]\n| isbn = 978-0-7935-9144-2\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Henderson\n| first = David\n| authorlink = David Henderson (poet)\n| title = 'Scuse Me While I Kiss the Sky: The Life of Jimi Hendrix\n| edition = Bantam 10/1981\n| year = 1981\n| publisher = [[Bantam Books]]\n| isbn = 0-553-01334-3\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Hendrix\n| first = Janie\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: The Lyrics\n| year = 2003\n| location = Milwaukee, Wisconsin\n| publisher = [[Hal Leonard Corporation|Hal Leonard]]\n| isbn = 0-634-04930-5\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite web\n |author=Jimi Hendrix Encyclopedia \n |url=http://jimihendrix.com/encyclopedia/index.html \n |title=Jimi Hendrix Encyclopedia \n |year=2012 \n |website=JimiHendrix.com (official website) \n |publisher=Experience Hendrix \n |accessdate=June 21, 2014 \n |ref=harv \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212211203/http://jimihendrix.com/encyclopedia/index.html \n |archivedate=February 12, 2009 \n}}\n*{{cite AV media notes\n| title = [[Are You Experienced]]\n| others = [[The Jimi Hendrix Experience]]\n| year = 1997\n| last = Marsh\n| first = David\n| authorlink = Dave Marsh\n| type = CD reissue notes\n| location = Universal City, California\n| publisher = [[MCA Records]]\n| id = MCAD-11602\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Marsh\n| first = David\n| authorlink = Dave Marsh\n| title = The Heart of Rock & Soul: The 1001 Greatest Singles Ever Made\n| edition = 1st. Da Capo Press\n| year = 1999\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[Da Capo Press]]\n| isbn = 978-0306809019\n| ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = McDermott\n| first1 = John\n| last2 = Kramer\n| first2 = Eddie\n| authorlink2 = Eddie Kramer\n| title = Hendrix: Setting the Record Straight\n| year = 1992\n| publisher = [[Warner Books]]\n| location = New York City\n| isbn = 0-446-39431-9\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = McDermott\n| first1 = John\n| last2 = Cox\n| first2 = Billy\n| authorlink2 = Billy Cox\n| last3 = Kramer\n| first3 = Eddie\n| authorlink3 = Eddie Kramer\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Sessions\n| edition = 1st.\n| year = 1995\n|location = Boston, Massachusetts\n| publisher = [[Little, Brown and Company|Little, Brown]]\n| isbn = 0-316-55549-5\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = McDermott\n| first1 = John\n| last2 = Kramer\n| first2 = Eddie\n| authorlink2 = Eddie Kramer\n| last3 = Cox\n| first3 = Billy\n| authorlink3 = Billy Cox\n| title = Ultimate Hendrix\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[Backbeat Books]]\n| year = 2009\n| isbn = 0-87930-938-5\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Roby\n| first = Steven\n| title = Black Gold: The Lost Archives of Jimi Hendrix\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[Billboard Books]]\n| year = 2002\n| isbn = 0-8230-7854-X\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/blackgoldlostarc00roby\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Roby\n| first1 = Steven\n| last2 = Schreiber\n| first2 = Brad\n| title = Becoming Jimi Hendrix\n| edition = 1st. Da Capo Press\n| location = Cambridge, Massachusetts\n| publisher = [[Da Capo Press]]\n| year = 2010\n| isbn = 978-0-306-81910-0\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/becomingjimihend00roby\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Roby\n| first = Steven\n| title = Hendrix on Hendrix: Interviews and Encounters with Jimi Hendrix \n| publisher = [[Chicago Review Press]]\n| year = 2012\n| isbn = 978-1-61374-322-5\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Shadwick\n| first = Keith\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Musician\n| edition = 1st.\n| location = San Francisco, California\n| publisher = [[Backbeat Books]]\n| year = 2003\n| isbn = 0-87930-764-1\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Shapiro\n| first1 = Harry\n| authorlink1 = Harry Shapiro (author)\n| last2 = Glebbeek\n| first2 = Cesar\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Electric Gypsy\n| location = New York City\n| publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]]\n| year = 1990\n| isbn = 0-312-05861-6\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/jimihendrixelec000shap\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Tawa\n| first = Nicholas E.\n| title = Supremely American: Popular Song in the 20th Century: Styles and Singers \n| url = https://archive.org/details/supremelyamerica0000tawa\n| url-access = registration\n| year = 2005\n| publisher = [[Scarecrow Press]]\n| isbn = 978-0810852952\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite journal\n| last = Walker\n| first = Michael\n| date = March 18, 2011\n| title = Electric Kool-Aid Marketing Trip\n| journal = [[New York Times]]\n| publisher = Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, Jr.\n| issn = 1553-8095\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/19/opinion/19walker.html?_r=3&\n| accessdate = October 23, 2014\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Wheeler\n| first1 = Tom\n| last2 = Gore\n| first2 = Joe\n| title = Fuzz, Feedback & Wah-Wah\n| year = 1992\n| location = Milwaukee, Wisconsin\n| publisher = Bella Godiva Music/[[Hal Leonard Publishing]]\n| isbn = 0-7935-1402-9\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last = Whitburn\n| first = Joel\n| authorlink = Joel Whitburn\n| title = Joel Whitburn Presents: Across The Charts The 1960s\n| year = 2008\n| publisher = [[Record Research]]\n| isbn = 978-0-89820-175-8\n| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Whitehill\n| first1 = Dave\n| last2 = Rubin\n| first2 = Dave\n| title = Octavia & Univibe\n| year = 1992\n| location = Milwaukee, Wisconsin\n| publisher = Bella Godiva Music/[[Hal Leonard Publishing]]\n| isbn = 0-7935-1403-7\n| ref = harv}}\n\n{{Jimi Hendrix singles}}\n{{Jimi Hendrix}}\n{{Dion DiMucci}}\n{{The Cure}}\n\n[[Category:1967 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jimi Hendrix]]\n[[Category:1967 singles]]\n[[Category:The Jimi Hendrix Experience songs]]\n[[Category:Track Records singles]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Dion DiMucci songs]]\n[[Category:The Cure songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Chas Chandler]]\n[[Category:American hard rock songs]]\n[[Category:American psychedelic rock songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Song first recorded by the Jimi Hendrix Experience in 1967}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Purple Haze\n| cover      = PurpleHaze-GermanSingle.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = German single picture sleeve\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]]\n| B-side     = \n*\"51st Anniversary\" (UK)\n*\"[[The Wind Cries Mary]]\" (US)\n| released   = \n*{{Start date|1967|03|17}} (UK){{efn|name=\"Track\"|There are conflicting dates given for the Track single release of \"Purple Haze\".  Shapiro,{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=526}} Roby,{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}} and the Jimi Hendrix Encyclopedia{{sfn|Jimi Hendrix Encyclopedia|2012|loc=Entry for March 17th, 1967}} list the date as March 17, 1967; McDermott{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=40}} uses March 1, 1967.}}\n*June 19, 1967 (US)\n| format     = [[Gramophone record#Formats|7-inch 45&nbsp;rpm]]\n| recorded   =\n*January 11, 1967\n*February 3\u20138, 1967\n| studio     = \n*[[De Lane Lea Studios|De Lane Lea]], London\n*[[Olympic Studios|Olympic]], London\n| genre      =\n*[[Psychedelic rock]]{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=148}}\n*[[hard rock]]{{sfn|Tawa|2005|p=193}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=46}}\n| label      = \n*[[Track Records|Track]] (UK)\n*[[Reprise Records|Reprise]] (US)\n| writer     = [[Jimi Hendrix]]\n| producer   = [[Chas Chandler]]\n| chronology = Experience UK\n| prev_title = [[Hey Joe]]\n| prev_year  = 1966\n| next_title = [[The Wind Cries Mary]]\n| next_year  = 1967\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Experience US\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Hey Joe#Tim Rose and Jimi Hendrix (1966)|Hey Joe]]\n | prev_year  = 1967\n | title      = Purple Haze\n | year       = 1967\n | next_title = [[Foxey Lady]]<!--US single used the American spelling, see McDermott 2009 p.81-->\n | next_year  = 1967\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Purple Haze'''\" is a song written by [[Jimi Hendrix]] and released as the second record single by [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]] on March 17, 1967. As a record chart hit in several countries and the opening number on the Experience's debut American album, it was many people's first exposure to Hendrix's [[psychedelic rock]] sound.\n\nThe song features his inventive guitar playing, which uses the signature [[Hendrix chord]] and a mix of blues and Eastern modalities, shaped by novel sound processing techniques.  Because of ambiguities in the lyrics, listeners often interpret the song as referring to a [[psychedelic experience]], although Hendrix described it as a love song.\n\n\"Purple Haze\" is one of Hendrix's best-known songs and appears on many Hendrix compilation albums.  The song featured regularly in concerts and each of Hendrix's group configurations issued live recordings. It was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] and is included on lists of the greatest guitar songs, including at number two by ''Rolling Stone'' and number one by ''Q'' magazine.\n\n==Background and recording==\nBy January 5, 1967, the Jimi Hendrix Experience's first single, \"[[Hey Joe]]\", backed with \"[[Stone Free]]\", had peaked at number six on the UK record chart.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=28}} \"Hey Joe\" was not a Hendrix composition \u2013 it was written by [[Billy Roberts]] and recorded by several groups prior to the Experience. Hendrix commented, \"That record isn't us. The next one's gonna be different.  We're working on an LP which will mainly be our stuff.\"{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=95}} The group recorded several demos of original material at studios in London, including \"Can You See Me\", \"[[Foxy Lady]]\", \"[[Third Stone from the Sun]]\", \"[[Red House (song)|Red House]]\", and \"Remember\".{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=27\u201329}}  In the middle of December, producer [[Chas Chandler]] heard Hendrix toying around with a new guitar riff. \"I heard him playing it at the flat and was knocked out. I told him to keep working on that, saying, 'That's the next single!{{'\"}}{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=32}}  Chandler claimed that after some more urging, Hendrix wrote the rest of \"Purple Haze\" in the dressing room of a London club during the afternoon of December 26, 1966, before a gig.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|1992|p=31}} In several interviews, Hendrix spoke about writing the song, but did not mention where or when he wrote it.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=149}}\n\nThe Experience began recording \"Purple Haze\" on January 11, 1967, at [[De Lane Lea Studios]] in London. According to drummer [[Mitch Mitchell]], he and bassist [[Noel Redding]] learned the song in the studio: \"Hendrix came in and kind of hummed us the riff and showed Noel the chords and the changes. I listened to it and we went, 'OK, let's do it.' We got it on the third take as I recall.\"{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}} The basic track was recorded in four hours, according to Chandler.{{sfn|McDermott|Cox|Kramer|1995|p=25}}  [[Multitrack recording]] technology allowed engineers to record and complete additional parts on the final master.  After the basic track was finished, Chandler explained that he and Hendrix developed the song:\n{{quote|With 'Purple Haze', Hendrix and I were striving for a sound and just kept going back in [to the studio], two hours at a time, trying to achieve it. It wasn't like we were there for days on end.  We recorded it, and then Hendrix and I would be sitting at home saying, 'Let's try that.' Then we would go in for an hour or two. That's how it was in those days. However long it took to record one specific idea, that's how long we would book. We kept going in and out.{{sfn|McDermott|Cox|Kramer|1995|p=25}}}}  Redding and Mitchell were not included in the process because Chandler felt that it was more efficient for him and Hendrix to do it alone.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=33}} To get a better quality recording, Chandler took the four-track tape recorded at De Lane Lea to [[Olympic Studios]] for [[overdubbing]] (although Hendrix had worked with eight-track recording in the US, it was not yet available in the UK).{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=35\u201336}} At Olympic, they were assigned [[Eddie Kramer]], who, as a sound engineer, played an important role in subsequent Hendrix recordings.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=35}} Hendrix added new vocals and guitar parts between February 3 and 8, 1967.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=35\u201336}}  Unlike the conventional techniques used by the Experience to record previous songs, Chandler decided to try out new effects and sounds for \"Purple Haze\".{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=32}} He enhanced background sounds (some contributed by Redding) by playing them back through headphones, which were moved around the recording microphone, creating \"a weird echo\".{{sfn|McDermott|Cox|Kramer|1995|p=27}} Chandler also used sped-up guitar parts recorded at half-speed (which also raises the [[Pitch (music)|pitch]]) and [[Panning (audio)|panning]] to create novel effects.{{sfn|McDermott|Cox|Kramer|1995|p=27}} The guitar solo features the first use of the [[Octavia (effects pedal)|Octavia]] guitar effects unit.{{sfn|McDermott|Cox|Kramer|1995|p=27}}  Acoustical and electronics engineer [[Roger Mayer (engineer)|Roger Mayer]] developed the unit with input from Hendrix. The Octavia doubles the frequency of the sound it is fed, essentially adding an upper octave.<ref name=\"Mayer\">\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.roger-mayer.co.uk/octavia.htm\n| title = Octavia\n| website = Roger Mayer\n| accessdate = July 7, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics and interpretation==\nIn interviews, Hendrix usually gave different answers about the development of the song's lyrics.  Biographer [[Harry Shapiro (author)|Harry Shapiro]] points out that \"Purple Haze\" is most likely \"a pot-pourri of ideas\" which Hendrix developed over time.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=149}}  As a fan of science fiction, he frequently incorporated its imagery in his songwriting.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}  Hendrix read ''[[Night of Light]]'', a 1966 novel by [[Philip Jos\u00e9 Farmer]], that expanded on a short story published in 1957.{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}}  In the story set on a distant planet, sunspots produce a \"purplish haze\" which has a disorienting effect on the inhabitants.{{sfn|Roby|Schreiber|2010|p=158}}{{efn|The phrase \"purple haze\" appears in literature, including in [[Charles Dickens]]' 1861 novel ''[[Great Expectations]]'': \"There was the red sun, on the low level of the shore, in a purple haze, fast deepening into black\" (Chapter 54).}}  An early handwritten draft by Hendrix, titled \"Purple Haze \u2013 Jesus Saves\", uses dream-like imagery where the sense of direction and time is distorted.{{sfn|Hendrix|2003|p=131}}  In an interview on January 28, 1967, before the song was completed, Hendrix was asked how he wrote songs; he responded, \"I dream a lot and I put my dreams down as songs. I wrote one called 'First Look Around the Corner' and another called 'The Purple Haze,' which was about a dream I had that I was walking under the sea.\"{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}}{{efn|The Hendrix song \"[[Are You Experienced? (song)|Are You Experienced?]]\", recorded in April 1967 and included as the title track for the Experience's debut album, includes a reference to walking under the sea: \"We'll hold hands and then we'll watch the sunrise, from the bottom of the sea\".{{sfn|Hendrix|2003|p=21}}}}  He later expressed frustration that he was unable to more fully develop his ideas for the song:\n{{quote|You know the song we had named 'Purple Haze'? [It] had about a thousand, thousand words&nbsp;... I had it all written out.  It was about going through, through this land.  This mythical&nbsp;... because that's what I like to do is write a lot of mythical scenes.  You know, like the history of the wars on Neptune.{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}}}}\nSo far, only a crumpled single sheet of ruled yellow tablet paper is on exhibit at the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] and does not include any of the lyrics used in the Experience song.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://rockhall.com/photo-gallery/spotlight-artifacts/1531/\n| title = Jimi Hendrix \"Purple Haze' Lyrics, 1966\n| website = [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]\n| accessdate = October 25, 2014\n}}</ref>  Chandler admitted that in the early stages, he helped Hendrix shape the songs and lyrics to radio single length.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=147}}  Biographer Keith Shadwick comments that although much of the complexity may have been sacrificed, it resulted in verses that are \"simple, focused and striking\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}\n \nAfter its release, Hendrix offered another explanation: \"He [the song's protagonist] likes this girl so much, that he doesn't know what [state] he's in, ya know.  A sort of daze, I suppose.  That's what the song is all about.\"{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=149}}  This draws on an experience Hendrix had while still in New York, where he felt that a girl was attempting to use [[Louisiana Voodoo|voodoo]] to trap him and he became ill.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=148}}  Shapiro believes that this is reflected in most of the first two verses:{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=148}}\n{{poemquote|Purple haze all around, don't know if I'm coming up or down\nAm I happy or in misery, whatever it is that girl put a spell on me}}\n\nMany fans and the press interpret the song as referring to a psychedelic experience due to lines such as \"purple haze all in my brain\" and \"'scuse me while I kiss the sky\".{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}}  However, Hendrix and those closest to him never discussed any connection between [[psychedelic drug]]s and the song, although Shapiro admits that, at the time, to do so would have been \"professional suicide\".{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=148}} Chandler, who claimed he was present when Hendrix wrote it, later denied suggestions that Hendrix did so while under the influence of psychedelics.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|1992|p=31}}<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\">\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/song/purple-haze-mt0004552447\n| title = Jimi Hendrix/Jimi Hendrix Experience: Purple Haze \u2013 Song Review\n| last = Ruhlmann\n| first = William\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = July 5, 2014\n| ref = harv\n}}</ref>  Commenting on the lyrics, Shadwick concludes \"the music [was allowed] to tell the larger story.  Poised effectively between the twin intoxicants of drugs and desire, they could be interpreted to the listener's taste\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}{{efn|Three months after the UK single release, the Experience performed at the [[Monterey Pop Festival]] on June 18, 1967. Underground chemist [[Owsley Stanley]] had made a special batch of [[LSD]] for the festival, which he dubbed \"Monterey Purple\".{{sfn|Walker|2011|p=A23}}  Although some connected it to \"Purple Haze\",{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=191}} Stanley disliked the association, feeling that it was \"far from inducing haze, [rather it] would confer upon the user preternatural clarity.\"{{sfn|Walker|2011|p=A23}}}}  In concert, Hendrix sometimes substituted lyrics for comic effect; \"'scuse me while I kiss the sky\" was rendered \"'scuse me while I kiss this guy\" (while gesturing towards Mitchell),{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=148}} \"'scuse me while I kiss that policeman\" (at a near riot in Los Angeles), or \"'scuse me while I fuck the sky\" (during a downpour in Seattle).{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=302}}\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n| type        = music\n| filename    = The first 17 seconds of \"Purple Haze\" by the Jimi Hendrix Experience 1967.ogg\n| title       = Purple Haze\n| description = 17 seconds of intro\n| pos         = \n}}\n\nMusic critic William Ruhlmann describes \"Purple Haze\" as having \"relentlessly driving, if relatively slow-paced underlying music, which provides a good platform for some of Hendrix's inventive guitar playing\".<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/>  Beginning with its [[Consonance and dissonance#Dissonance|dissonant]] opening and heavy use of [[Distortion (music)|distortion]], Hendrix's techniques \"all contributed to the dirty, raw, metallic, [and] angular sounds\" heard in the song, according to Shapiro.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=144}}  The intro consists of the melodic [[Interval (music)|interval]] of a [[tritone]] or [[Diminution#Diminution of intervals|diminished]] (sometimes called [[Flat (music)|flattened]]) [[diminished fifth|fifth]].{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}}  Historically, this dissonant interval has been referred to as ''diabolus in musica'' (literally \"Devil in music\") and was reputedly proscribed by [[papal bull]] during the [[Spanish Inquisition]], because \"to play it was like ringing Satan's doorbell\".{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=144}}{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}} It is sounded during the first two measures by Hendrix playing a B{{music|flat}} on guitar against an E played by Redding on bass, followed by the respective octaves.{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}}  Mitchell on drums comes in for the third measure, when Hendrix introduces the riff that piqued Chandler's interest, and Redding continues playing the octaves in E.{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=13}}\n\nAfter the riff, the verse sections begin, which Shadwick describe as \"simplicity itself, consisting of just three chords\": E7{{music|sharp}}9, G, and A.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=13}}  The E7{{music|sharp}}9, or dominant seventh sharp ninth chord, has come to be called the \"Hendrix chord\" by guitarists and was used primarily in [[rhythm and blues]] and [[jazz]] before Hendrix helped popularize it.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|pp=146\u2013148}}  He also used an unconventional fingering technique for the G and A chords.{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}}  Because Hendrix used his thumb to fret the [[Root (chord)|roots]] of the G and A chords on the sixth string, his fingers were left in a position to create different chord [[Voicing (music)|voicings]].{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}}  Instead of the usual G [[barre chord]] (G\u2013B\u2013G\u2013B\u2013D\u2013G), a G[[Fifth (chord)|5]] (G\u2013X\u2013G\u2013G\u2013D\u2013G) is sometimes played with the [[major third]] (B) being muted on the fifth string and replaced by the open third string (G).{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|p=2}}  Redding follows the chord changes mostly by playing the root with occasional [[Nonchord tone|passing notes]],{{sfn|Hal Leonard|1998|pp=3\u201314}} while Mitchell heightens the tension with drum flourishes that accentuate Hendrix's vocal and guitar.{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}\n\nBiographer [[David Henderson (poet)|David Henderson]] describes Hendrix's guitar tone as \"at the razor edge of distort\".{{sfn|Henderson|1981|p=103}}  However, individual notes are still clear, as well as the harmonically more complex chords, even with the use of extreme overdrive for the time.{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=13}}  The tension is maintained until the guitar solo, which \"arrives as something of a release rather than a further racking up of the atmosphere.\"{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}  It is also when Hendrix first introduces the Octavia, coupled with a [[Fuzz Face]] distortion unit.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=146}}  Whitehill describes the solo as \"almost sound[ing] likes he's playing a blues raga.  He starts out playing in the [[Mixolydian mode]] and then he goes right into the blues side.  The Octavia has the effect of a sitar, kind of like Ravi Shankar meets B.B. King.\"{{sfn|Wheeler|Gore|1992|p=4}}  During the song's outro, the guitar part recorded at 7\u00bd [[Tape recorder#Tapedeck speeds|inches per second]] (ips) played back at 15 ips, is combined with the Octavia, further extending the guitar's upper frequency range.{{sfn|Whitehill|Rubin|1992|p=4}}  Henderson describes it as \"an uncanny piercing tone that takes off, Eastern-sounding beyond the range of the guitar\"{{sfn|Henderson|1981|p=104}} and, according to Shadwick, \"gives the impression that the guitar notes are flying off into the ether.\"{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=96}}\n\n==Releases and charts==\n[[File:Are You Experienced - US cover-edit.jpg|right|thumb|upright|240px|\"Purple Haze\" became the opening track on the 1967 American ''[[Are You Experienced]]'' album]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Top singles charts 1967\n!Peak position\n!Weeks on chart\n|-\n| Austria ''Austrian Hitparade''<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url=http://austriancharts.at/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Jimi+Hendrix+Experience&titel=Purple+Haze&cat=s\n| title=Austrian Hitparade: Jimi Hendrix Experience \u2013 Purple Haze (song)\n| website=austriancharts.at\n| publisher=Hung Medien\n| language=German\n| accessdate = July 11, 2014\n}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n| Germany ''Musicline''<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Jimi+Hendrix/10446/?type=single\n| title=Musicline: Jimi Hendrix Single-Charts\n| website=musicline.de\n| publisher=[[Phononet GmbH]]\n| language=German\n| accessdate=July 11, 2014\n| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529195337/http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Jimi+Hendrix/10446/?type=single\n| archive-date=May 29, 2014\n| url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|17\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n| Netherlands ''Dutch Charts''<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Jimi+Hendrix+Experience&titel=Purple+Haze&cat=s \n |title=Dutch Charts: Jimi Hendrix Experience \u2013 Purple Haze \n |website=dutchcharts.nl \n |publisher=Hung Medien \n |language=Dutch \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428145343/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Jimi%20Hendrix%20Experience&titel=Purple%20Haze&cat=s \n |archivedate=April 28, 2014 \n |accessdate=November 2, 2014 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n| Norway ''Norwegian Charts''<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url=http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Jimi+Hendrix+Experience&titel=Purple+Haze&cat=s\n| title=Norwegian Charts: Jimi Hendrix Experience \u2013 Purple Haze (song)\n| website=norwegiancharts.com\n| publisher=Hung Medien\n| accessdate=July 11, 2014\n}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n| UK ''[[UK Singles Chart|Official Singles Chart]]''<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/jimi%20hendrix%20experience/\n| title = Jimi Hendrix Experience \u2013 Singles\n| website = [[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]]\n| accessdate = July 11, 2014\n}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|align=\"center\"|14\n|-\n| US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]{{sfn|Whitburn|2008|p=176}}\n|align=\"center\"|65\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n|}\nOn March 17, 1967, \"Purple Haze\" was released in the UK as the first single on [[Track Records]].{{efn|name=\"Track\"}}  Another Hendrix composition, the [[R&B]]-influenced \"51st Anniversary\" was included as the [[B-side]].{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=40}}  [[Paul McCartney]], who was an early Hendrix supporter, gave the record an enthusiastic pre-release review in ''[[Melody Maker]]''.{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}}  The single entered the charts at number 39 on ''[[Record Mirror]]'' and at number 43 on ''Melody Maker''.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|1992|p=51}} It peaked at number three and spent 14 weeks on the chart.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/jimi%20hendrix%20experience/\n| title = Jimi Hendrix Experience \u2013 Singles\n| website = [[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]]\n| accessdate = Jul 5, 2014\n}}</ref>  During March 1967, several performances of \"Purple Haze\" were filmed to promote the song and used for television programs, such as ''[[Beat-Club]]'', [[Simon Dee|''Dee Time'']], and ''[[Top of the Pops]]''.{{sfn|Roby|2002|pp=215\u2013216}}  Live performances were also broadcast on German [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] and [[BBC Radio]]'s ''[[Saturday Club (BBC radio)|Saturday Club]]''.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|pp=40\u201341}}\n\nFor the American single, [[Reprise Records]] paired the song with \"[[The Wind Cries Mary]]\".{{sfn|Whitburn|2008|p=176}}{{efn|Track Records marked on the box with master tape sent to Reprise Records for its remastering, \"DELIBERATE DISTORTION. DO NOT CORRECT.\"{{sfn|Roby|Shreiber|2010|p=184}}}}  It was released on June 19, 1967, the day following the Experience's performance at the [[Monterey Pop Festival]].{{efn|There are also conflicting dates for the Reprise single release.  Shapiro,{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=528}} Roby,{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=67}} and Shadwick{{sfn|Shadwick|2003|p=116}} list it as June 19, 1967; McDermott{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=60}} uses August 16, 1967, one week before the American release of ''Are You Experienced''.}} The single entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] pop chart on August 26, where it spent eight weeks and reached number 65.{{sfn|Whitburn|2008|p=176}}  \"Purple Haze\" was included as the opening track on the American release of ''Are You Experienced'' on August 23, 1967.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=61}}  Because of the song's airplay on [[Progressive rock (radio format)|underground FM radio]], the album became more popular than Hendrix's singles.{{sfn|McDermott|Kramer|Cox|2009|p=60}}{{efn|[[KMPX (defunct)|KMPX]] in San Francisco, one of the pioneers of the \"underground\" or progressive radio formats in the US, began playing an acetate pressing of the song before it was released by Track Records in the UK.{{sfn|Roby|2002|p=75}}}}\n\nOne of Hendrix's most popular songs,<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/> \"Purple Haze\" appears on numerous compilation albums.  Some of these include ''[[Smash Hits (The Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Smash Hits]]'', ''[[The Essential Jimi Hendrix]]'', ''[[The Singles Album (Jimi Hendrix album)|The Singles Album]]'', ''[[Kiss the Sky (Jimi Hendrix album)|Kiss the Sky]]'', ''[[Cornerstones: 1967\u20131970]]'', ''[[The Ultimate Experience]]'', ''[[Experience Hendrix: The Best of Jimi Hendrix]]'', ''[[Voodoo Child: The Jimi Hendrix Collection]]'', and ''[[The Singles Collection (Jimi Hendrix album)|The Singles Collection]]''.<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/>  An alternative version recorded at the same time, but with different vocal and guitar overdubs, is the first song on ''[[The Jimi Hendrix Experience (album)|The Jimi Hendrix Experience]]'' 2000 box set.  Live recordings of \"Purple Haze\" as performed by each of the different Hendrix lineups have been released.{{sfn|Belmo|Loveless|1998|pp=399\u2013412}} These include ''[[Live at Monterey]]'' (the Experience), ''[[Live at Woodstock (Jimi Hendrix album)|Live at Woodstock]]'' (Gypsy Sun and Rainbows), ''[[Live at the Fillmore East (Jimi Hendrix album)|Live at the Fillmore East]]'' (Band of Gypsys), and ''[[Live at Berkeley]]'' (the Cry of Love touring group).<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/>  Additional live recordings with the Experience appear on ''[[Winterland (The Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Winterland]]'' (2011 ''Billboard'' number 49 album) and ''[[Miami Pop Festival (Jimi Hendrix Experience album)|Miami Pop Festival]]'' (2013 ''Billboard'' number 39 album).\n\n==Recognition and influence==\nIn March 2005, [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]] ranked \"Purple Haze\" at number one in its list of the \"100 Greatest Guitar Tracks Ever!\"<ref>\n{{cite magazine\n| date = March 2005\n| title = 100 Greatest Guitar Tracks Ever!\n| magazine = [[Q (magazine)|Q]]\n| url = http://www.qthemusic.com/\n| archiveurl = http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage3.htm \n| archivedate = 2013\n| accessdate  = July 5, 2014\n}}</ref> The song placed at number two on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's \"100 Greatest Guitar Songs of All Time\" list, which noted that the song \"unveiled a new guitar language charged with spiritual hunger and the poetry possible in electricity and studio technology\".<ref>\n{{cite magazine\n| year = 2003 \n| title = 100 Greatest Guitar Songs of All Time \n| magazine = [[Rolling Stone]] \n| url = https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/20947527\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080530224813/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/20947527/page/3 \n| archivedate = May 30, 2008 \n| accessdate = July 5, 2014 \n| url-status = dead \n}}</ref> It also appears at number 17 on the magazine's \"[[500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\" list, with the comment that \"it launched not one but two revolutions: late-Sixties psychedelia and the unprecedented genius of Jimi Hendrix\".<ref>\n{{cite magazine\n| date = December 9, 2004\n| title = The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time\n| magazine = [[Rolling Stone]]\n| issue = 963\n| url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/the-jimi-hendrix-experience-purple-haze-20110517\n| accessdate = July 5, 2014\n}}</ref> Author and music critic [[Dave Marsh]] called it the \"debut single of the [[Album Rock Era]]\".{{sfn|Marsh|1999|p=178}}  In 1995, \"Purple Haze\" was included as one of the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]'s \"500 Songs That Shaped Rock and Roll\".<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.rockhall.com/exhibithighlights/500-songs \n| title = 500 Songs That Shaped Rock and Roll \n| website = [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] \n| year = 1995 \n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070502032502/http://www.rockhall.com/exhibithighlights/500-songs-by-name-np/ \n| archivedate = May 2, 2007 \n| accessdate = July 5, 2014 \n| url-status = dead \n}}</ref>  [[NPR]] named the song to its list of the \"100 Most Important American Musical Works of the 20th Century\" in 2000.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.npr.org/programs/specials/vote/list100.html#P\n| title = The NPR 100: The 100 Most Important American Musical Works of the 20th Century\n| website = [[NPR.org]]\n| accessdate = October 24, 2014\n}}</ref>  In 2000, it was given a [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]], which \"honor[s] recordings of lasting qualitative or historical significance\".<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/hall-of-fame#p\n| title = Grammy Hall of Fame Awards \u2013 Past Recipients\n| website = [[Grammy.org]]\n| year = 2000\n| accessdate = July 5, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nMany musicians have recorded their interpretations of the song, making it one of Hendrix's most covered songs.{{sfn|Shapiro|Glebbeek|1990|p=526}}  [[Dion DiMucci]] included an acoustic version with strings on his 1968 comeback album ''Dion''.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/dion-mw0000623651\n| title = ''Dion'' \u2013 Review\n| last = Unterberger\n| first = Richie\n| authorlink = Richie Unterberger\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = November 3, 2014\n}}</ref> Released as a single in 1969, it appeared at number 63 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, which was two positions higher than Hendrix' single in 1967.  Also with a new arrangement, [[the Cure]] recorded it for the various artist's ''[[Stone Free: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix]]'' in 1993.<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/> Their rendition reached number two on ''Billboard's'' [[Modern Rock Tracks]] alternative rock chart. \"Purple Haze\" has achieved an unusual level of interest among classical musicians.<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/> The [[Meridian Arts Ensemble]], the [[Hampton String Quartet]], and [[Nigel Kennedy]] have recorded their interpretations and the [[Kronos Quartet]] often play it as an encore.<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{Notelist|30em}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n'''References'''\n*{{cite book\n| last1 = Belmo\n| last2 = Loveless\n| first2 = Steve\n| title = Jimi Hendrix: Experience the Music\n| year = 1998\n| location = Burlington, Ontario